A defined data format has its implicit or explicit data model, and EDAM does not distinguish the two. Some data models however do not have any standard way of serialisation into an exchange format, and those are thus not considered formats in EDAM. (Remark: even broader - or closely related - term to 'Data model' would be an 'Information model'.)
File format denotes only formats of a computer file, but the same formats apply also to data blobs or exchanged messages.

http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/remark: EDAM editors: Jon Ison, MatÃºÅ¡ KalaÅ¡, HervÃ© MÃ©nager, and Veit SchwÃ¤mmle. Contributors: see http://edamontologydocs.readthedocs.io/en/latest/contributors.html. License: see http://edamontologydocs.readthedocs.io/en/latest/license.html.

EDAM is an ontology of well established, familiar concepts that are prevalent within bioinformatics, including types of data and data identifiers, data formats, operations and topics. EDAM is a simple ontology - essentially a set of terms with synonyms and definitions - organised into an intuitive hierarchy for convenient use by curators, software developers and end-users. EDAM is suitable for large-scale semantic annotations and categorisation of diverse bioinformatics resources.  EDAM is also suitable for diverse application including for example within workbenches and workflow-management systems, software distributions, and resource registries.

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Radiation hybrid scores (RH) scores for one or more markers.
Radiation Hybrid (RH) scores
@graph.rdfs:comment: Radiation Hybrid (RH) scores are used in Radiation Hybrid mapping.
@graph.rdfs:label: RH scores

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A human-readable collection of information about the linkage of alleles.
Gene annotation (linkage)
Linkage disequilibrium (report)
@graph.rdfs:comment: This includes linkage disequilibrium; the non-random association of alleles or polymorphisms at two or more loci (not necessarily on the same chromosome).
@graph.rdfs:label: Genetic linkage report

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Data quantifying the level of expression of (typically) multiple genes, derived for example from microarray experiments.
Gene expression pattern
@graph.rdfs:label: Gene expression profile

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: microarray experiments including conditions, protocol, sample:data relationships etc.
@graph.rdfs:label: Microarray experiment report

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Data on oligonucleotide probes (typically for use with DNA microarrays).
@graph.rdfs:label: Oligonucleotide probe data

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Output from a serial analysis of gene expression (SAGE) experiment.
@graph.rdfs:label: SAGE experimental data

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Massively parallel signature sequencing (MPSS) data.
@graph.rdfs:label: MPSS experimental data

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Sequencing by synthesis (SBS) data.
@graph.rdfs:label: SBS experimental data

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Tag to gene assignments (tag mapping) of SAGE, MPSS and SBS data. Typically this is the sequencing-based expression profile annotated with gene identifiers.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence tag profile (with gene assignment)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Protein X-ray crystallographic data
X-ray crystallography data.
@graph.rdfs:label: Electron density map

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) raw data, typically for a protein.
Protein NMR data
@graph.rdfs:label: Raw NMR data

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Protein secondary structure from protein coordinate or circular dichroism (CD) spectroscopic data.
@graph.rdfs:label: CD spectra

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Volume map data from electron microscopy.
@graph.rdfs:label: Volume map

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Annotation on a structural 3D model (volume map) from electron microscopy.
@graph.rdfs:label: Electron microscopy model

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Two-dimensional gel electrophoresis image
@graph.rdfs:label: 2D PAGE image

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Spectra from mass spectrometry.
Mass spectrometry spectra
@graph.rdfs:label: Mass spectrum

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A set of peptide masses (peptide mass fingerprint) from mass spectrometry.
Molecular weights standard fingerprint
@graph.rdfs:comment: A molecular weight standard fingerprint is standard protonated molecular masses e.g. from trypsin (modified porcine trypsin, Promega) and keratin peptides.
@graph.rdfs:label: Peptide mass fingerprint

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Protein or peptide identifications with evidence supporting the identifications, for example from comparing a peptide mass fingerprint (from mass spectrometry) to a sequence database, or  the set of typical spectra one obtains when running a protein through a mass spectrometer.
'Protein identification'
@graph.rdfs:label: Peptide identification

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An informative report about a specific biological pathway or network, typically including a map (diagram) of the pathway.
@graph.rdfs:label: Pathway or network annotation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A map (typically a diagram) of a biological pathway.
@graph.rdfs:label: Biological pathway map

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A definition of a data resource serving one or more types of data, including metadata and links to the resource or data proper.
@graph.rdfs:label: Data resource definition

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Basic information, annotation or documentation concerning a workflow (but not the workflow itself).
@graph.rdfs:label: Workflow metadata

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A biological model represented in mathematical terms.
Biological model
@graph.rdfs:label: Mathematical model

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A value representing estimated statistical significance of some observed data; typically sequence database hits.
@graph.rdfs:label: Statistical estimate score

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Resource definition for an EMBOSS database.
@graph.rdfs:label: EMBOSS database resource definition

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Information on a version of software or data, for example name, version number and release date.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Development status / maturity may be part of the version information, for example in case of tools, standards, or some data records.
@graph.rdfs:label: Version information

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A mapping of the accession numbers (or other database identifier) of entries between (typically) two biological or biomedical databases.
@graph.rdfs:comment: The cross-mapping is typically a table where each row is an accession number and each column is a database being cross-referenced. The cells give the accession number or identifier of the corresponding entry in a database. If a cell in the table is not filled then no mapping could be found for the database. Additional information might be given on version, date etc.
@graph.rdfs:label: Database cross-mapping

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An index of data of biological relevance.
@graph.rdfs:label: Data index

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A human-readable collection of information concerning an analysis of an index of biological data.
Database index annotation
@graph.rdfs:label: Data index report

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Basic information on bioinformatics database(s) or other data sources such as name, type, description, URL etc.
@graph.rdfs:label: Database metadata

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Basic information about one or more bioinformatics applications or packages, such as name, type, description, or other documentation.
@graph.rdfs:label: Tool metadata

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Textual metadata on a submitted or completed job.
@graph.rdfs:label: Job metadata

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Textual metadata on a software author or end-user, for example a person or other software.
@graph.rdfs:label: User metadata

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A human-readable collection of information about a specific chemical compound.
@graph.rdfs:label: Small molecule report

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A human-readable collection of information about a particular strain of organism cell line including plants, virus, fungi and bacteria. The data typically includes strain number, organism type, growth conditions, source and so on.
@graph.rdfs:label: Cell line report

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An informative report about a specific scent.
@graph.rdfs:label: Scent annotation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A term (name) from an ontology.
@graph.rdfs:label: Ontology term

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Data concerning or derived from a concept from a biological ontology.
@graph.rdfs:label: Ontology concept data

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Keyword(s) or phrase(s) used (typically) for text-searching purposes.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Boolean operators (AND, OR and NOT) and wildcard characters may be allowed.
@graph.rdfs:label: Keyword

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Bibliographic data that uniquely identifies a scientific article, book or other published material.
@graph.rdfs:comment: A bibliographic reference might include information such as authors, title, journal name, date and (possibly) a link to the abstract or full-text of the article if available.
@graph.rdfs:label: Citation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A scientific text, typically a full text article from a scientific journal.
@graph.rdfs:label: Article

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A human-readable collection of information resulting from text mining.
Text mining output
@graph.rdfs:comment: A text mining abstract will typically include an annotated a list of words or sentences extracted from one or more scientific articles.
@graph.rdfs:label: Text mining report

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An identifier of a biological entity or phenomenon.
@graph.rdfs:label: Entity identifier

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An identifier of a data resource.
@graph.rdfs:label: Data resource identifier

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An identifier that identifies a particular type of data.
Identifier (typed)
@graph.rdfs:comment: This concept exists only to assist EDAM maintenance and navigation in graphical browsers.  It does not add semantic information.  This branch provides an alternative organisation of the concepts nested under 'Accession' and 'Name'. All concepts under here are already included under 'Accession' or 'Name'.
@graph.rdfs:label: Identifier (by type of data)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An identifier of a bioinformatics tool, e.g. an application or web service.
@graph.rdfs:label: Tool identifier

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Name or other identifier of a discrete entity (any biological thing with a distinct, discrete physical existence).
@graph.rdfs:label: Discrete entity identifier

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Name or other identifier of an entity feature (a physical part or region of a discrete biological entity, or a feature that can be mapped to such a thing).
@graph.rdfs:label: Entity feature identifier

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Name or other identifier of a collection of discrete biological entities.
@graph.rdfs:label: Entity collection identifier

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Name or other identifier of a physical, observable biological occurrence or event.
@graph.rdfs:label: Phenomenon identifier

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Name or other identifier of a molecule.
@graph.rdfs:label: Molecule identifier

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier (e.g. character symbol) of a specific atom.
Atom identifier
@graph.rdfs:label: Atom ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Name of a specific molecule.
@graph.rdfs:label: Molecule name

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A label (text token) describing the type a molecule.
@graph.rdfs:comment: For example, 'Protein', 'DNA', 'RNA' etc.
@graph.rdfs:label: Molecule type

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Unique identifier of a chemical compound.
@graph.rdfs:label: Chemical identifier

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Name of a chromosome.
@graph.rdfs:label: Chromosome name

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of a peptide chain.
@graph.rdfs:label: Peptide identifier

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of a protein.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein identifier

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Unique name of a chemical compound.
Chemical name
@graph.rdfs:label: Compound name

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Unique registry number of a chemical compound.
@graph.rdfs:label: Chemical registry number

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Code word for a ligand, for example from a PDB file.
@graph.rdfs:label: Ligand identifier

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of a drug.
@graph.rdfs:label: Drug identifier

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of an amino acid.
Residue identifier
@graph.rdfs:label: Amino acid identifier

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Name or other identifier of a nucleotide.
@graph.rdfs:label: Nucleotide identifier

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of a monosaccharide.
@graph.rdfs:label: Monosaccharide identifier

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Unique name from Chemical Entities of Biological Interest (ChEBI) of a chemical compound.
ChEBI chemical name
@graph.rdfs:comment: This is the recommended chemical name for use for example in database annotation.
@graph.rdfs:label: Chemical name (ChEBI)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: IUPAC recommended name of a chemical compound.
IUPAC chemical name
@graph.rdfs:label: Chemical name (IUPAC)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: International Non-proprietary Name (INN or 'generic name') of a chemical compound, assigned by the World Health Organisation (WHO).
INN chemical name
@graph.rdfs:label: Chemical name (INN)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Brand name of a chemical compound.
Brand chemical name
@graph.rdfs:label: Chemical name (brand)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Synonymous name of a chemical compound.
Synonymous chemical name
@graph.rdfs:label: Chemical name (synonymous)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: CAS registry number of a chemical compound; a unique numerical identifier of chemicals in the scientific literature, as assigned by the Chemical Abstracts Service.
@graph.rdfs:label: CAS number

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Beilstein registry number of a chemical compound.
Beilstein chemical registry number
@graph.rdfs:label: Chemical registry number (Beilstein)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Gmelin registry number of a chemical compound.
Gmelin chemical registry number
@graph.rdfs:label: Chemical registry number (Gmelin)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: 3-letter code word for a ligand (HET group) from a PDB file, for example ATP.
@graph.rdfs:label: HET group name

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: String of one or more ASCII characters representing an amino acid.
@graph.rdfs:label: Amino acid name

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: String of one or more ASCII characters representing a nucleotide.
@graph.rdfs:label: Nucleotide code

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of a polypeptide chain from a protein.
@graph.rdfs:comment: This is typically a character (for the chain) appended to a PDB identifier, e.g. 1cukA
@graph.rdfs:label: Polypeptide chain ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Name of a protein.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein name

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Name or other identifier of an enzyme or record from a database of enzymes.
@graph.rdfs:label: Enzyme identifier

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An Enzyme Commission (EC) number of an enzyme.
@graph.rdfs:label: EC number

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Name of an enzyme.
@graph.rdfs:label: Enzyme name

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Name of a restriction enzyme.
@graph.rdfs:label: Restriction enzyme name

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A specification (partial or complete) of one or more positions or regions of a molecular sequence or map.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence position specification

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A unique identifier of molecular sequence feature, for example an ID of a feature that is unique within the scope of the GFF file.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence feature ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A position of one or more points (base or residue) in a sequence, or part of such a specification.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence position

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Specification of range(s) of sequence positions.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence range

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Name or other identifier of an nucleic acid feature.
@graph.rdfs:label: Nucleic acid feature identifier

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Name or other identifier of a protein feature.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein feature identifier

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The type of a sequence feature, typically a term or accession from the Sequence Ontology, for example an EMBL or Swiss-Prot sequence feature key.
@graph.rdfs:comment: A feature key indicates the biological nature of the feature or information about changes to or versions of the sequence.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence feature key

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Typically one of the EMBL or Swiss-Prot feature qualifiers.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Feature qualifiers hold information about a feature beyond that provided by the feature key and location.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence feature qualifier

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A name of a sequence feature, e.g. the name of a feature to be displayed to an end-user. Typically an EMBL or Swiss-Prot feature label.
Sequence feature name
@graph.rdfs:comment: A feature label identifies a feature of a sequence database entry. When used with the database name and the entry's primary accession number, it is a unique identifier of that feature.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence feature label

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The name of a sequence feature-containing entity adhering to the standard feature naming scheme used by all EMBOSS applications.
UFO
@graph.rdfs:label: EMBOSS Uniform Feature Object

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: String of one or more ASCII characters representing a codon.
@graph.rdfs:label: Codon name

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Moby:GeneAccessionList
An identifier of a gene, such as a name/symbol or a unique identifier of a gene in a database.
@graph.rdfs:label: Gene identifier

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The short name of a gene; a single word that does not contain white space characters. It is typically derived from the gene name.
@graph.rdfs:label: Gene symbol

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An NCBI unique identifier of a gene.
@graph.rdfs:label: Gene ID (NCBI)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An NCBI RefSeq unique identifier of a gene.
@graph.rdfs:label: Gene identifier (NCBI RefSeq)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An NCBI UniGene unique identifier of a gene.
@graph.rdfs:label: Gene identifier (NCBI UniGene)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An Entrez unique identifier of a gene.
@graph.rdfs:label: Gene identifier (Entrez)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of a gene or feature from the CGD database.
CGD ID
@graph.rdfs:label: Gene ID (CGD)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of a gene from DictyBase.
@graph.rdfs:label: Gene ID (DictyBase)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Unique identifier for a gene (or other feature) from the Ensembl database.
Gene ID (Ensembl)
@graph.rdfs:label: Ensembl gene ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of an entry from the SGD database.
SGD identifier
@graph.rdfs:label: Gene ID (SGD)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Moby_namespace:GeneDB
Identifier of a gene from the GeneDB database.
GeneDB identifier
@graph.rdfs:label: Gene ID (GeneDB)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of an entry from the TIGR database.
@graph.rdfs:label: TIGR identifier

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of an gene from the TAIR database.
@graph.rdfs:label: TAIR accession (gene)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of a protein structural domain.
@graph.rdfs:comment: This is typically a character or string concatenated with a PDB identifier and a chain identifier.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein domain ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of a protein domain (or other node) from the SCOP database.
@graph.rdfs:label: SCOP domain identifier

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of a protein domain from CATH.
CATH domain identifier
@graph.rdfs:label: CATH domain ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A SCOP concise classification string (sccs) is a compact representation of a SCOP domain classification.
@graph.rdfs:comment: An scss includes the class (alphabetical), fold, superfamily and family (all numerical) to which a given domain belongs.
@graph.rdfs:label: SCOP concise classification string (sccs)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Unique identifier (number) of an entry in the SCOP hierarchy, for example 33229.
@graph.rdfs:comment: A sunid uniquely identifies an entry in the SCOP hierarchy, including leaves (the SCOP domains) and higher level nodes including entries corresponding to the protein level.
@graph.rdfs:label: SCOP sunid

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A code number identifying a node from the CATH database.
@graph.rdfs:label: CATH node ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The name of a biological kingdom (Bacteria, Archaea, or Eukaryotes).
@graph.rdfs:label: Kingdom name

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The name of a species (typically a taxonomic group) of organism.
Organism species
@graph.rdfs:label: Species name

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The name of a strain of an organism variant, typically a plant, virus or bacterium.
@graph.rdfs:label: Strain name

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A string of characters that name or otherwise identify a resource on the Internet.
URIs
@graph.rdfs:label: URI

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An identifier of a biological or bioinformatics database.
Database identifier
@graph.rdfs:label: Database ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The name of a directory.
@graph.rdfs:label: Directory name

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The name (or part of a name) of a file (of any type).
@graph.rdfs:label: File name

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Name of an ontology of biological or bioinformatics concepts and relations.
@graph.rdfs:label: Ontology name

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A Uniform Resource Locator (URL).
@graph.rdfs:label: URL

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A Uniform Resource Name (URN).
@graph.rdfs:label: URN

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A Life Science Identifier (LSID) - a unique identifier of some data.
Life Science Identifier
@graph.rdfs:comment: LSIDs provide a standard way to locate and describe data. An LSID is represented as a Uniform Resource Name (URN) with the following format: URN:LSID:<Authority>:<Namespace>:<ObjectID>[:<Version>]
@graph.rdfs:label: LSID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The name of a biological or bioinformatics database.
@graph.rdfs:label: Database name

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The name of a molecular sequence database.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence database name

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The name of a file (of any type) with restricted possible values.
@graph.rdfs:label: Enumerated file name

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The extension of a file name.
@graph.rdfs:comment: A file extension is the characters appearing after the final '.' in the file name.
@graph.rdfs:label: File name extension

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The base name of a file.
@graph.rdfs:comment: A file base name is the file name stripped of its directory specification and extension.
@graph.rdfs:label: File base name

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Name of a QSAR descriptor.
@graph.rdfs:label: QSAR descriptor name

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An identifier of an entry from a database where the same type of identifier is used for objects (data) of different semantic type.
@graph.rdfs:comment: This concept is required for completeness. It should never have child concepts.
@graph.rdfs:label: Database entry identifier

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An identifier of molecular sequence(s) or entries from a molecular sequence database.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence identifier

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An identifier of a set of molecular sequence(s).
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence set ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of a sequence signature (motif or profile) for example from a database of sequence patterns.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence signature identifier

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of a molecular sequence alignment, for example a record from an alignment database.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence alignment ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of a phylogenetic distance matrix.
@graph.rdfs:label: Phylogenetic distance matrix identifier

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of a phylogenetic tree for example from a phylogenetic tree database.
@graph.rdfs:label: Phylogenetic tree ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An identifier of a comparison matrix.
Substitution matrix identifier
@graph.rdfs:label: Comparison matrix identifier

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A unique and persistent identifier of a molecular tertiary structure, typically an entry from a structure database.
@graph.rdfs:label: Structure ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier or name of a structural (3D) profile or template (representing a structure or structure alignment).
Structural profile identifier
@graph.rdfs:label: Structural (3D) profile ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of an entry from a database of tertiary structure alignments.
@graph.rdfs:label: Structure alignment ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of an index of amino acid physicochemical and biochemical property data.
@graph.rdfs:label: Amino acid index ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Molecular interaction ID
Identifier of a report of protein interactions from a protein interaction database (typically).
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein interaction ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of a protein family.
Protein secondary database record identifier
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein family identifier

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Unique name of a codon usage table.
@graph.rdfs:label: Codon usage table name

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of a transcription factor (or a TF binding site).
@graph.rdfs:label: Transcription factor identifier

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of an entry from a database of microarray data.
@graph.rdfs:label: Experiment annotation ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of an entry from a database of electron microscopy data.
@graph.rdfs:label: Electron microscopy model ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Accession of a report of gene expression (e.g. a gene expression profile) from a database.
Gene expression profile identifier
@graph.rdfs:label: Gene expression report ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of an entry from a database of genotypes and phenotypes.
@graph.rdfs:label: Genotype and phenotype annotation ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of an entry from a database of biological pathways or networks.
@graph.rdfs:label: Pathway or network identifier

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of a biological or biomedical workflow, typically from a database of workflows.
@graph.rdfs:label: Workflow ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of a data type definition from some provider.
Data resource definition identifier
@graph.rdfs:label: Data resource definition ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of a mathematical model, typically an entry from a database.
Biological model identifier
@graph.rdfs:label: Biological model ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of an entry from a database of chemicals.
@graph.rdfs:label: Compound identifier

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A unique (typically numerical) identifier of a concept in an ontology of biological or bioinformatics concepts and relations.
@graph.rdfs:label: Ontology concept ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Unique identifier of a scientific article.
Article identifier
@graph.rdfs:label: Article ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of an object from the FlyBase database.
@graph.rdfs:label: FlyBase ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Name of an object from the WormBase database, usually a human-readable name.
@graph.rdfs:label: WormBase name

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Class of an object from the WormBase database.
@graph.rdfs:comment: A WormBase class describes the type of object such as 'sequence' or 'protein'.
@graph.rdfs:label: WormBase class

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A persistent, unique identifier of a molecular sequence database entry.
Sequence accession number
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence accession

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A label (text token) describing a type of molecular sequence.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Sequence type might reflect the molecule (protein, nucleic acid etc) or the sequence itself (gapped, ambiguous etc).
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence type

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The name of a sequence-based entity adhering to the standard sequence naming scheme used by all EMBOSS applications.
EMBOSS USA
@graph.rdfs:label: EMBOSS Uniform Sequence Address

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Accession number of a protein sequence database entry.
Protein sequence accession number
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence accession (protein)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Accession number of a nucleotide sequence database entry.
Nucleotide sequence accession number
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence accession (nucleic acid)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Accession number of a RefSeq database entry.
RefSeq ID
@graph.rdfs:label: RefSeq accession

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Accession number of a UniProt (protein sequence) database entry. May contain version or isoform number.
@graph.rdfs:label: UniProt accession (extended)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An identifier of PIR sequence database entry.
@graph.rdfs:label: PIR identifier

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of a TREMBL sequence database entry.
@graph.rdfs:label: TREMBL accession

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Primary identifier of a Gramene database entry.
Gramene primary ID
@graph.rdfs:label: Gramene primary identifier

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of a (nucleic acid) entry from the EMBL/GenBank/DDBJ databases.
@graph.rdfs:label: EMBL/GenBank/DDBJ ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A unique identifier of an entry (gene cluster) from the NCBI UniGene database.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence cluster ID (UniGene)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of a dbEST database entry.
dbEST ID
@graph.rdfs:label: dbEST accession

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of a dbSNP database entry.
dbSNP identifier
@graph.rdfs:label: dbSNP ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The EMBOSS type of a molecular sequence.
@graph.rdfs:comment: See the EMBOSS documentation (http://emboss.sourceforge.net/) for a definition of what this includes.
@graph.rdfs:label: EMBOSS sequence type

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: List of EMBOSS Uniform Sequence Addresses (EMBOSS listfile).
@graph.rdfs:label: EMBOSS listfile

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An identifier of a cluster of molecular sequence(s).
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence cluster ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Unique identifier of an entry from the COG database.
COG ID
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence cluster ID (COG)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of a sequence motif, for example an entry from a motif database.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence motif identifier

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of a sequence profile.
@graph.rdfs:comment: A sequence profile typically represents a sequence alignment.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence profile ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of an entry from the ELMdb database of protein functional sites.
@graph.rdfs:label: ELM ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Accession number of an entry from the Prosite database.
Prosite ID
@graph.rdfs:label: Prosite accession number

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Unique identifier or name of a HMMER hidden Markov model.
@graph.rdfs:label: HMMER hidden Markov model ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Unique identifier or name of a profile from the JASPAR database.
@graph.rdfs:label: JASPAR profile ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A label (text token) describing the type of a sequence alignment.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Possible values include for example the EMBOSS alignment types, BLAST alignment types and so on.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence alignment type

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The type of a BLAST sequence alignment.
@graph.rdfs:label: BLAST sequence alignment type

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A label (text token) describing the type of a phylogenetic tree.
@graph.rdfs:comment: For example 'nj', 'upgmp' etc.
@graph.rdfs:label: Phylogenetic tree type

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Accession number of an entry from the TreeBASE database.
@graph.rdfs:label: TreeBASE study accession number

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Accession number of an entry from the TreeFam database.
@graph.rdfs:label: TreeFam accession number

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A label (text token) describing the type of a comparison matrix.
@graph.rdfs:comment: For example 'blosum', 'pam', 'gonnet', 'id' etc. Comparison matrix type may be required where a series of matrices of a certain type are used.
@graph.rdfs:label: Comparison matrix type

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Unique name or identifier of a comparison matrix.
Substitution matrix name
@graph.rdfs:comment: See for example http://www.ebi.ac.uk/Tools/webservices/help/matrix.
@graph.rdfs:label: Comparison matrix name

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An identifier of an entry from the PDB database.
@graph.rdfs:comment: A PDB identification code which consists of 4 characters, the first of which is a digit in the range 0 - 9; the remaining 3 are alpha-numeric, and letters are upper case only. (source: https://cdn.rcsb.org/wwpdb/docs/documentation/file-format/PDB_format_1996.pdf)
@graph.rdfs:label: PDB ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of an entry from the AAindex database.
@graph.rdfs:label: AAindex ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Accession number of an entry from the BIND database.
@graph.rdfs:label: BIND accession number

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Accession number of an entry from the IntAct database.
@graph.rdfs:label: IntAct accession number

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Name of a protein family.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein family name

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Name of an InterPro entry, usually indicating the type of protein matches for that entry.
@graph.rdfs:label: InterPro entry name

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Primary accession number of an InterPro entry.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Every InterPro entry has a unique accession number to provide a persistent citation of database records.
@graph.rdfs:label: InterPro accession

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Secondary accession number of an InterPro entry.
InterPro secondary accession number
@graph.rdfs:label: InterPro secondary accession

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Unique identifier of an entry from the Gene3D database.
@graph.rdfs:label: Gene3D ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Unique identifier of an entry from the PIRSF database.
@graph.rdfs:label: PIRSF ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The unique identifier of an entry in the PRINTS database.
@graph.rdfs:label: PRINTS code

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Accession number of a Pfam entry.
@graph.rdfs:label: Pfam accession number

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Accession number of an entry from the SMART database.
@graph.rdfs:label: SMART accession number

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Unique identifier (number) of a hidden Markov model from the Superfamily database.
@graph.rdfs:label: Superfamily hidden Markov model number

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Accession number of an entry (family) from the TIGRFam database.
TIGRFam accession number
@graph.rdfs:label: TIGRFam ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A ProDom domain family accession number.
@graph.rdfs:comment: ProDom is a protein domain family database.
@graph.rdfs:label: ProDom accession number

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of an entry from the TRANSFAC database.
@graph.rdfs:label: TRANSFAC accession number

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Accession number of an entry from the ArrayExpress database.
ArrayExpress experiment ID
@graph.rdfs:label: ArrayExpress accession number

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: PRIDE experiment accession number.
@graph.rdfs:label: PRIDE experiment accession number

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of an entry from the EMDB electron microscopy database.
@graph.rdfs:label: EMDB ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Accession number of an entry from the GEO database.
@graph.rdfs:label: GEO accession number

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of an entry from the GermOnline database.
@graph.rdfs:label: GermOnline ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of an entry from the EMAGE database.
@graph.rdfs:label: EMAGE ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Accession number of an entry from a database of disease.
@graph.rdfs:label: Disease ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of an entry from the HGVbase database.
@graph.rdfs:label: HGVbase ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of an entry from the HIVDB database.
@graph.rdfs:label: HIVDB identifier

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of an entry from the OMIM database.
@graph.rdfs:label: OMIM ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Unique identifier of an object from one of the KEGG databases (excluding the GENES division).
@graph.rdfs:label: KEGG object identifier

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of an entry from the Reactome database.
Reactome ID
@graph.rdfs:label: Pathway ID (reactome)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of an entry from the aMAZE database.
aMAZE ID
@graph.rdfs:label: Pathway ID (aMAZE)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of an pathway from the BioCyc biological pathways database.
BioCyc pathway ID
@graph.rdfs:label: Pathway ID (BioCyc)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of an entry from the INOH database.
INOH identifier
@graph.rdfs:label: Pathway ID (INOH)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of an entry from the PATIKA database.
PATIKA ID
@graph.rdfs:label: Pathway ID (PATIKA)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of an entry from the CPDB (ConsensusPathDB) biological pathways database, which is an identifier from an external database integrated into CPDB.
CPDB ID
@graph.rdfs:comment: This concept refers to identifiers used by the databases collated in CPDB; CPDB identifiers are not independently defined.
@graph.rdfs:label: Pathway ID (CPDB)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of a biological pathway from the Panther Pathways database.
Panther Pathways ID
@graph.rdfs:label: Pathway ID (Panther)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Unique identifier of a MIRIAM data resource.
@graph.rdfs:comment: This is the identifier used internally by MIRIAM for a data type.
@graph.rdfs:label: MIRIAM identifier

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The name of a data type from the MIRIAM database.
@graph.rdfs:label: MIRIAM data type name

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The URI (URL or URN) of a data entity from the MIRIAM database.
identifiers.org synonym
@graph.rdfs:comment: A MIRIAM URI consists of the URI of the MIRIAM data type (PubMed, UniProt etc) followed by the identifier of an element of that data type, for example PMID for a publication or an accession number for a GO term.
@graph.rdfs:label: MIRIAM URI

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The primary name of a data type from the MIRIAM database.
@graph.rdfs:comment: The primary name of a MIRIAM data type is taken from a controlled vocabulary.
@graph.rdfs:label: MIRIAM data type primary name

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A synonymous name of a data type from the MIRIAM database.
@graph.rdfs:comment: A synonymous name for a MIRIAM data type taken from a controlled vocabulary.
@graph.rdfs:label: MIRIAM data type synonymous name

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Unique identifier of a Taverna workflow.
@graph.rdfs:label: Taverna workflow ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Name of a biological (mathematical) model.
@graph.rdfs:label: Biological model name

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Unique identifier of an entry from the BioModel database.
@graph.rdfs:label: BioModel ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Chemical structure specified in PubChem Compound Identification (CID), a non-zero integer identifier for a unique chemical structure.
PubChem compound accession identifier
@graph.rdfs:label: PubChem CID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of an entry from the ChemSpider database.
@graph.rdfs:label: ChemSpider ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of an entry from the ChEBI database.
@graph.rdfs:label: ChEBI ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An identifier of a concept from the BioPax ontology.
@graph.rdfs:label: BioPax concept ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An identifier of a concept from The Gene Ontology.
GO concept identifier
@graph.rdfs:label: GO concept ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An identifier of a concept from the MeSH vocabulary.
@graph.rdfs:label: MeSH concept ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An identifier of a concept from the HGNC controlled vocabulary.
@graph.rdfs:label: HGNC concept ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A stable unique identifier for each taxon (for a species, a family, an order, or any other group in the NCBI taxonomy database.
@graph.rdfs:label: NCBI taxonomy ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An identifier of a concept from the Plant Ontology (PO).
@graph.rdfs:label: Plant Ontology concept ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An identifier of a concept from the UMLS vocabulary.
@graph.rdfs:label: UMLS concept ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An identifier of a concept from Foundational Model of Anatomy.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Classifies anatomical entities according to their shared characteristics (genus) and distinguishing characteristics (differentia). Specifies the part-whole and spatial relationships of the entities, morphological transformation of the entities during prenatal development and the postnatal life cycle and principles, rules and definitions according to which classes and relationships in the other three components of FMA are represented.
@graph.rdfs:label: FMA concept ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An identifier of a concept from the EMAP mouse ontology.
@graph.rdfs:label: EMAP concept ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An identifier of a concept from the ChEBI ontology.
@graph.rdfs:label: ChEBI concept ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An identifier of a concept from the MGED ontology.
@graph.rdfs:label: MGED concept ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An identifier of a concept from the myGrid ontology.
@graph.rdfs:comment: The ontology is provided as two components, the service ontology and the domain ontology. The domain ontology acts provides concepts for core bioinformatics data types and their relations. The service ontology describes the physical and operational features of web services.
@graph.rdfs:label: myGrid concept ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: PubMed unique identifier of an article.
PMID
@graph.rdfs:label: PubMed ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Digital Object Identifier (DOI) of a published article.
Digital Object Identifier
@graph.rdfs:label: DOI

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Medline UI (unique identifier) of an article.
Medline unique identifier
@graph.rdfs:comment: The use of Medline UI has been replaced by the PubMed unique identifier.
@graph.rdfs:label: Medline UI

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The name of a computer package, application, method or function.
@graph.rdfs:label: Tool name

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The unique name of a signature (sequence classifier) method.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Signature methods from http://www.ebi.ac.uk/Tools/InterProScan/help.html#results include BlastProDom, FPrintScan, HMMPIR, HMMPfam, HMMSmart, HMMTigr, ProfileScan, ScanRegExp, SuperFamily and HAMAP.
@graph.rdfs:label: Tool name (signature)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The name of a BLAST tool.
BLAST name
@graph.rdfs:comment: This include 'blastn', 'blastp', 'blastx', 'tblastn' and 'tblastx'.
@graph.rdfs:label: Tool name (BLAST)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The name of a FASTA tool.
@graph.rdfs:comment: This includes 'fasta3', 'fastx3', 'fasty3', 'fastf3', 'fasts3' and 'ssearch'.
@graph.rdfs:label: Tool name (FASTA)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The name of an EMBOSS application.
@graph.rdfs:label: Tool name (EMBOSS)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The name of an EMBASSY package.
@graph.rdfs:label: Tool name (EMBASSY package)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A QSAR constitutional descriptor.
QSAR constitutional descriptor
@graph.rdfs:label: QSAR descriptor (constitutional)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A QSAR electronic descriptor.
QSAR electronic descriptor
@graph.rdfs:label: QSAR descriptor (electronic)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A QSAR geometrical descriptor.
QSAR geometrical descriptor
@graph.rdfs:label: QSAR descriptor (geometrical)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A QSAR topological descriptor.
QSAR topological descriptor
@graph.rdfs:label: QSAR descriptor (topological)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A QSAR molecular descriptor.
QSAR molecular descriptor
@graph.rdfs:label: QSAR descriptor (molecular)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Any collection of multiple protein sequences and associated metadata that do not (typically) correspond to common sequence database records or database entries.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence set (protein)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Any collection of multiple nucleotide sequences and associated metadata that do not (typically) correspond to common sequence database records or database entries.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence set (nucleic acid)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A set of sequences that have been clustered or otherwise classified as belonging to a group including (typically) sequence cluster information.
@graph.rdfs:comment: The cluster might include sequences identifiers, short descriptions, alignment and summary information.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence cluster

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A file of intermediate results from a PSIBLAST search that is used for priming the search in the next PSIBLAST iteration.
@graph.rdfs:comment: A Psiblast checkpoint file uses ASN.1 Binary Format and usually has the extension '.asn'.
@graph.rdfs:label: Psiblast checkpoint file

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Sequences generated by HMMER package in FASTA-style format.
@graph.rdfs:label: HMMER synthetic sequences set

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A protein sequence cleaved into peptide fragments (by enzymatic or chemical cleavage) with fragment masses.
@graph.rdfs:label: Proteolytic digest

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Restriction digest fragments from digesting a nucleotide sequence with restriction sites using a restriction endonuclease.
@graph.rdfs:label: Restriction digest

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Oligonucleotide primer(s) for PCR and DNA amplification, for example a minimal primer set.
@graph.rdfs:label: PCR primers

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: File of sequence vectors used by EMBOSS vectorstrip application, or any file in same format.
@graph.rdfs:label: vectorstrip cloning vector definition file

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A library of nucleotide sequences to avoid during hybridisation events. Hybridisation of the internal oligo to sequences in this library is avoided, rather than priming from them. The file is in a restricted FASTA format.
@graph.rdfs:label: Primer3 internal oligo mishybridizing library

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A nucleotide sequence library of sequences to avoid during amplification (for example repetitive sequences, or possibly the sequences of genes in a gene family that should not be amplified. The file must is in a restricted FASTA format.
@graph.rdfs:label: Primer3 mispriming library file

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: File of one or more pairs of primer sequences, as used by EMBOSS primersearch application.
@graph.rdfs:label: primersearch primer pairs sequence record

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A cluster of protein sequences.
Protein sequence cluster
@graph.rdfs:comment: The sequences are typically related, for example a family of sequences.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence cluster (protein)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A cluster of nucleotide sequences.
Nucleotide sequence cluster
@graph.rdfs:comment: The sequences are typically related, for example a family of sequences.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence cluster (nucleic acid)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The size (length) of a sequence, subsequence or region in a sequence, or range(s) of lengths.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence length

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Size of a sequence word.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Word size is used for example in word-based sequence database search methods.
@graph.rdfs:label: Word size

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Size of a sequence window.
@graph.rdfs:comment: A window is a region of fixed size but not fixed position over a molecular sequence. It is typically moved (computationally) over a sequence during scoring.
@graph.rdfs:label: Window size

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Specification of range(s) of length of sequences.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence length range

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Report on basic information about a molecular sequence such as name, accession number, type (nucleic or protein), length, description etc.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence information report

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An informative report about non-positional sequence features, typically a report on general molecular sequence properties derived from sequence analysis.
Sequence properties report
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence property

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Annotation of positional features of molecular sequence(s), i.e. that can be mapped to position(s) in the sequence.
@graph.rdfs:comment: This includes annotation of positional sequence features, organised into a standard feature table, or any other report of sequence features.  General feature reports are a source of sequence feature table information although internal conversion would be required.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence features

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Comparative data on sequence features such as statistics, intersections (and data on intersections), differences etc.
@graph.rdfs:comment: This is a broad data type and is used a placeholder for other, more specific types.  It is primarily intended to help navigation of EDAM and would not typically be used for annotation.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence features (comparative)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A report of general sequence properties derived from protein sequence data.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence property (protein)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A report of general sequence properties derived from nucleotide sequence data.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence property (nucleic acid)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A report on sequence complexity, for example low-complexity or repeat regions in sequences.
Sequence property (complexity)
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence complexity report

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A report on ambiguity in molecular sequence(s).
Sequence property (ambiguity)
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence ambiguity report

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A report (typically a table) on character or word composition / frequency of a molecular sequence(s).
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence composition report

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A report on peptide fragments of certain molecular weight(s) in one or more protein sequences.
@graph.rdfs:label: Peptide molecular weight hits

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A plot of third base position variability in a nucleotide sequence.
@graph.rdfs:label: Base position variability plot

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A table of character or word composition / frequency of a molecular sequence.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence composition table

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A table of base frequencies of a nucleotide sequence.
@graph.rdfs:label: Base frequencies table

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A table of word composition of a nucleotide sequence.
@graph.rdfs:label: Base word frequencies table

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A table of amino acid frequencies of a protein sequence.
Sequence composition (amino acid frequencies)
@graph.rdfs:label: Amino acid frequencies table

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A table of amino acid word composition of a protein sequence.
Sequence composition (amino acid words)
@graph.rdfs:label: Amino acid word frequencies table

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Annotation of a molecular sequence in DAS format.
@graph.rdfs:label: DAS sequence feature annotation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Annotation of positional sequence features, organised into a standard feature table.
Sequence feature table
@graph.rdfs:label: Feature table

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A map of (typically one) DNA sequence annotated with positional or non-positional features.
DNA map
@graph.rdfs:label: Map

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An informative report on intrinsic positional features of a nucleotide sequence, formatted to be machine-readable.
@graph.rdfs:comment: This includes nucleotide sequence feature annotation in any known sequence feature table format and any other report of nucleic acid features.
@graph.rdfs:label: Nucleic acid features

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An informative report on intrinsic positional features of a protein sequence.
@graph.rdfs:comment: This includes protein sequence feature annotation in any known sequence feature table format and any other report of protein features.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein features

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Moby:GeneticMap
A map showing the relative positions of genetic markers in a nucleic acid sequence, based on estimation of non-physical distance such as recombination frequencies.
Linkage map
@graph.rdfs:comment: A genetic (linkage) map indicates the proximity of two genes on a chromosome, whether two genes are linked and the frequency they are transmitted together to an offspring. They are limited to genetic markers of traits observable only in whole organisms.
@graph.rdfs:label: Genetic map

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A map of genetic markers in a contiguous, assembled genomic sequence, with the sizes and separation of markers measured in base pairs.
@graph.rdfs:comment: A sequence map typically includes annotation on significant subsequences such as contigs, haplotypes and genes. The contigs shown will (typically) be a set of small overlapping clones representing a complete chromosomal segment.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence map

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A map of DNA (linear or circular) annotated with physical features or landmarks such as restriction sites, cloned DNA fragments, genes or genetic markers, along with the physical distances between them.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Distance in a physical map is measured in base pairs. A physical map might be ordered relative to a reference map (typically a genetic map) in the process of genome sequencing.
@graph.rdfs:label: Physical map

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Image of a sequence with matches to signatures, motifs or profiles.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence signature map

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A map showing banding patterns derived from direct observation of a stained chromosome.
@graph.rdfs:comment: This is the lowest-resolution physical map and can provide only rough estimates of physical (base pair) distances.  Like a genetic map, they are limited to genetic markers of traits observable only in whole organisms.
@graph.rdfs:label: Cytogenetic map

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A gene map showing distances between loci based on relative cotransduction frequencies.
@graph.rdfs:label: DNA transduction map

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Sequence map of a single gene annotated with genetic features such as introns, exons, untranslated regions, polyA signals, promoters, enhancers and (possibly) mutations defining alleles of a gene.
@graph.rdfs:label: Gene map

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Sequence map of a plasmid (circular DNA).
@graph.rdfs:label: Plasmid map

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Sequence map of a whole genome.
@graph.rdfs:label: Genome map

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Image of the restriction enzyme cleavage sites (restriction sites) in a nucleic acid sequence.
@graph.rdfs:label: Restriction map

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Image showing matches between protein sequence(s) and InterPro Entries.
@graph.rdfs:comment: The sequence(s) might be screened against InterPro, or be the sequences from the InterPro entry itself. Each protein is represented as a scaled horizontal line with colored bars indicating the position of the matches.
@graph.rdfs:label: InterPro compact match image

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Image showing detailed information on matches between protein sequence(s) and InterPro Entries.
@graph.rdfs:comment: The sequence(s) might be screened against InterPro, or be the sequences from the InterPro entry itself.
@graph.rdfs:label: InterPro detailed match image

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Image showing the architecture of InterPro domains in a protein sequence.
@graph.rdfs:comment: The sequence(s) might be screened against InterPro, or be the sequences from the InterPro entry itself. Domain architecture is shown as a series of non-overlapping domains in the protein.
@graph.rdfs:label: InterPro architecture image

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: SMART protein schematic in PNG format.
@graph.rdfs:label: SMART protein schematic

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Images based on GlobPlot prediction of intrinsic disordered regions and globular domains in protein sequences.
@graph.rdfs:label: GlobPlot domain image

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Report on the location of matches to profiles, motifs (conserved or functional patterns) or other signatures in one or more sequences.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence motif matches

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Location of short repetitive subsequences (repeat sequences) in (typically nucleotide) sequences.
@graph.rdfs:comment: The report might include derived data map such as classification, annotation, organisation, periodicity etc.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence features (repeats)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A report on predicted or actual gene structure, regions which make an RNA product and features such as promoters, coding regions, splice sites etc.
@graph.rdfs:label: Gene and transcript structure (report)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: regions of a nucleic acid sequence containing mobile genetic elements.
@graph.rdfs:label: Mobile genetic elements

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A report on quadruplex-forming motifs in a nucleotide sequence.
@graph.rdfs:label: Nucleic acid features (quadruplexes)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Report on nucleosome formation potential or exclusion sequence(s).
@graph.rdfs:label: Nucleosome exclusion sequences

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A report on exonic splicing enhancers (ESE) in an exon.
@graph.rdfs:label: Gene features (exonic splicing enhancer)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A report on microRNA sequence (miRNA) or precursor, microRNA targets, miRNA binding sites in an RNA sequence etc.
@graph.rdfs:label: Nucleic acid features (microRNA)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: protein-coding regions including coding sequences (CDS), exons, translation initiation sites and open reading frames.
@graph.rdfs:label: Coding region

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A report on selenocysteine insertion sequence (SECIS) element in a DNA sequence.
@graph.rdfs:label: Gene features (SECIS element)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: transcription factor binding sites (TFBS) in a DNA sequence.
@graph.rdfs:label: Transcription factor binding sites

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A report on predicted or known key residue positions (sites) in a protein sequence, such as binding or functional sites.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Use this concept for collections of specific sites which are not necessarily contiguous, rather than contiguous stretches of amino acids.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein features (sites)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: signal peptides or signal peptide cleavage sites in protein sequences.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein features report (signal peptides)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: cleavage sites (for a proteolytic enzyme or agent) in a protein sequence.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein features report (cleavage sites)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: post-translation modifications in a protein sequence, typically describing the specific sites involved.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein features (post-translation modifications)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: catalytic residues (active site) of an enzyme.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein features report (active sites)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: ligand-binding (non-catalytic) residues of a protein, such as sites that bind metal, prosthetic groups or lipids.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein features report (binding sites)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A report on antigenic determinant sites (epitopes) in proteins, from sequence and / or structural data.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Epitope mapping is commonly done during vaccine design.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein features (epitopes)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: RNA and DNA-binding proteins and binding sites in protein sequences.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein features report (nucleic acid binding sites)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A report on epitopes that bind to MHC class I molecules.
@graph.rdfs:label: MHC Class I epitopes report

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A report on predicted epitopes that bind to MHC class II molecules.
@graph.rdfs:label: MHC Class II epitopes report

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A report or plot of PEST sites in a protein sequence.
@graph.rdfs:comment: 'PEST' motifs target proteins for proteolytic degradation and reduce the half-lives of proteins dramatically.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein features (PEST sites)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Scores from a sequence database search (for example a BLAST search).
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence database hits scores list

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Alignments from a sequence database search (for example a BLAST search).
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence database hits alignments list

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A report on the evaluation of the significance of sequence similarity scores from a sequence database search (for example a BLAST search).
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence database hits evaluation data

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Alphabet for the motifs (patterns) that MEME will search for.
@graph.rdfs:label: MEME motif alphabet

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: MEME background frequencies file.
@graph.rdfs:label: MEME background frequencies file

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: File of directives for ordering and spacing of MEME motifs.
@graph.rdfs:label: MEME motifs directive file

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Dirichlet distribution used by hidden Markov model analysis programs.
@graph.rdfs:label: Dirichlet distribution

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Emission and transition counts of a hidden Markov model, generated once HMM has been determined, for example after residues/gaps have been assigned to match, delete and insert states.
@graph.rdfs:label: HMM emission and transition counts

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Regular expression pattern.
@graph.rdfs:label: Regular expression

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Any specific or conserved pattern (typically expressed as a regular expression) in a molecular sequence.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence motif

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Some type of statistical model representing a (typically multiple) sequence alignment.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence profile

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An informative report about a specific or conserved protein sequence pattern.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein signature

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A nucleotide regular expression pattern from the Prosite database.
@graph.rdfs:label: Prosite nucleotide pattern

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A protein regular expression pattern from the Prosite database.
@graph.rdfs:label: Prosite protein pattern

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A profile (typically representing a sequence alignment) that is a simple matrix of nucleotide (or amino acid) counts per position.
PFM
@graph.rdfs:label: Position frequency matrix

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A profile (typically representing a sequence alignment) that is weighted matrix of nucleotide (or amino acid) counts per position.
PWM
@graph.rdfs:comment: Contributions of individual sequences to the matrix might be uneven (weighted).
@graph.rdfs:label: Position weight matrix

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A profile (typically representing a sequence alignment) derived from a matrix of nucleotide (or amino acid) counts per position that reflects information content at each position.
ICM
@graph.rdfs:label: Information content matrix

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A statistical Markov model of a system which is assumed to be a Markov process with unobserved (hidden) states.  For example, a hidden Markov model representation of a set or alignment of sequences.
HMM
@graph.rdfs:label: Hidden Markov model

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: One or more fingerprints (sequence classifiers) as used in the PRINTS database.
@graph.rdfs:label: Fingerprint

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A protein signature of the type used in the EMBASSY Signature package.
@graph.rdfs:label: Domainatrix signature

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: NULL hidden Markov model representation used by the HMMER package.
@graph.rdfs:label: HMMER NULL hidden Markov model

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A protein family signature (sequence classifier) from the InterPro database.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Protein family signatures cover all domains in the matching proteins and span >80% of the protein length and with no adjacent protein domain signatures or protein region signatures.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein family signature

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A protein domain signature (sequence classifier) from the InterPro database.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Protein domain signatures identify structural or functional domains or other units with defined boundaries.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein domain signature

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A protein region signature (sequence classifier) from the InterPro database.
@graph.rdfs:comment: A protein region signature defines a region which cannot be described as a protein family or domain signature.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein region signature

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A protein repeat signature (sequence classifier) from the InterPro database.
@graph.rdfs:comment: A protein repeat signature is a repeated protein motif, that is not in single copy expected to independently fold into a globular domain.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein repeat signature

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A protein site signature (sequence classifier) from the InterPro database.
@graph.rdfs:comment: A protein site signature is a classifier for a specific site in a protein.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein site signature

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A protein conserved site signature (sequence classifier) from the InterPro database.
@graph.rdfs:comment: A protein conserved site signature is any short sequence pattern that may contain one or more unique residues and is cannot be described as a active site, binding site or post-translational modification.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein conserved site signature

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A protein active site signature (sequence classifier) from the InterPro database.
@graph.rdfs:comment: A protein active site signature corresponds to an enzyme catalytic pocket. An active site typically includes non-contiguous residues, therefore multiple signatures may be required to describe an active site. ; residues involved in enzymatic reactions for which mutational data is typically available.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein active site signature

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A protein binding site signature (sequence classifier) from the InterPro database.
@graph.rdfs:comment: A protein binding site signature corresponds to a site that reversibly binds chemical compounds, which are not themselves substrates of the enzymatic reaction. This includes enzyme cofactors and residues involved in electron transport or protein structure modification.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein binding site signature

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A protein post-translational modification signature (sequence classifier) from the InterPro database.
@graph.rdfs:comment: A protein post-translational modification signature corresponds to sites that undergo modification of the primary structure, typically to activate or de-activate a function. For example, methylation, sumoylation, glycosylation etc. The modification might be permanent or reversible.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein post-translational modification signature

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Alignment of exactly two molecular sequences.
Sequence alignment (pair)
@graph.rdfs:label: Pair sequence alignment

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Alignment of more than two molecular sequences.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence alignment (multiple)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Alignment of multiple nucleotide sequences.
Sequence alignment (nucleic acid)
@graph.rdfs:label: Nucleic acid sequence alignment

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Alignment of multiple protein sequences.
Sequence alignment (protein)
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein sequence alignment

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Alignment of multiple molecular sequences of different types.
Sequence alignment (hybrid)
@graph.rdfs:comment: Hybrid sequence alignments include for example genomic DNA to EST, cDNA or mRNA.
@graph.rdfs:label: Hybrid sequence alignment

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Alignment of exactly two nucleotide sequences.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence alignment (nucleic acid pair)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Alignment of exactly two protein sequences.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence alignment (protein pair)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Alignment of exactly two molecular sequences of different types.
@graph.rdfs:label: Hybrid sequence alignment (pair)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Alignment of more than two nucleotide sequences.
@graph.rdfs:label: Multiple nucleotide sequence alignment

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Alignment of more than two protein sequences.
@graph.rdfs:label: Multiple protein sequence alignment

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A simple floating point number defining the penalty for opening or extending a gap in an alignment.
@graph.rdfs:label: Alignment score or penalty

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Whether end gaps are scored or not.
@graph.rdfs:label: Score end gaps control

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Controls the order of sequences in an output sequence alignment.
@graph.rdfs:label: Aligned sequence order

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A penalty for opening a gap in an alignment.
@graph.rdfs:label: Gap opening penalty

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A penalty for extending a gap in an alignment.
@graph.rdfs:label: Gap extension penalty

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A penalty for gaps that are close together in an alignment.
@graph.rdfs:label: Gap separation penalty

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A penalty for gaps at the termini of an alignment, either from the N/C terminal of protein or 5'/3' terminal of nucleotide sequences.
@graph.rdfs:label: Terminal gap penalty

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The score for a 'match' used in various sequence database search applications with simple scoring schemes.
@graph.rdfs:label: Match reward score

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The score (penalty) for a 'mismatch' used in various alignment and sequence database search applications with simple scoring schemes.
@graph.rdfs:label: Mismatch penalty score

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: This is the threshold drop in score at which extension of word alignment is halted.
@graph.rdfs:label: Drop off score

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A simple floating point number defining the penalty for opening a gap in an alignment.
@graph.rdfs:label: Gap opening penalty (integer)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A simple floating point number defining the penalty for opening a gap in an alignment.
@graph.rdfs:label: Gap opening penalty (float)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A simple floating point number defining the penalty for extending a gap in an alignment.
@graph.rdfs:label: Gap extension penalty (integer)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A simple floating point number defining the penalty for extending a gap in an alignment.
