@graph.rdfs:label: Gap extension penalty (float)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A simple floating point number defining the penalty for gaps that are close together in an alignment.
@graph.rdfs:label: Gap separation penalty (integer)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A simple floating point number defining the penalty for gaps that are close together in an alignment.
@graph.rdfs:label: Gap separation penalty (float)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A number defining the penalty for opening gaps at the termini of an alignment, either from the N/C terminal of protein or 5'/3' terminal of nucleotide sequences.
@graph.rdfs:label: Terminal gap opening penalty

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A number defining the penalty for extending gaps at the termini of an alignment, either from the N/C terminal of protein or 5'/3' terminal of nucleotide sequences.
@graph.rdfs:label: Terminal gap extension penalty

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Sequence identity is the number (%) of matches (identical characters) in positions from an alignment of two molecular sequences.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence identity

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Sequence similarity is the similarity (expressed as a percentage) of two molecular sequences calculated from their alignment, a scoring matrix for scoring characters substitutions and penalties for gap insertion and extension.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Data Type is float probably.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence similarity

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Data on molecular sequence alignment quality (estimated accuracy).
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence alignment metadata (quality report)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Data on character conservation in a molecular sequence alignment.
@graph.rdfs:comment: This is a broad data type and is used a placeholder for other, more specific types.  It is primarily intended to help navigation of EDAM and would not typically be used for annotation. Use this concept for calculated substitution rates, relative site variability, data on sites with biased properties, highly conserved or very poorly conserved sites, regions, blocks etc.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence alignment report (site conservation)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Data on correlations between sites in a molecular sequence alignment, typically to identify possible covarying positions and predict contacts or structural constraints in protein structures.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence alignment report (site correlation)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Alignment of molecular sequences to a Domainatrix signature (representing a sequence alignment).
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence-profile alignment (Domainatrix signature)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Alignment of molecular sequence(s) to a hidden Markov model(s).
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence-profile alignment (HMM)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Alignment of molecular sequences to a protein fingerprint from the PRINTS database.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence-profile alignment (fingerprint)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Continuous quantitative data that may be read during phylogenetic tree calculation.
@graph.rdfs:label: Phylogenetic continuous quantitative data

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Character data with discrete states that may be read during phylogenetic tree calculation.
@graph.rdfs:label: Phylogenetic discrete data

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: One or more cliques of mutually compatible characters that are generated, for example from analysis of discrete character data, and are used to generate a phylogeny.
Phylogenetic report (cliques)
@graph.rdfs:label: Phylogenetic character cliques

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Phylogenetic invariants data for testing alternative tree topologies.
Phylogenetic report (invariants)
@graph.rdfs:label: Phylogenetic invariants

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A report of data concerning or derived from a phylogenetic tree, or from comparing two or more phylogenetic trees.
@graph.rdfs:comment: This is a broad data type and is used  for example for reports on confidence, shape or stratigraphic (age) data derived from phylogenetic tree analysis.
@graph.rdfs:label: Phylogenetic report

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A model of DNA substitution that explains a DNA sequence alignment, derived from phylogenetic tree analysis.
@graph.rdfs:label: DNA substitution model

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Data about the shape of a phylogenetic tree.
@graph.rdfs:label: Phylogenetic tree report (tree shape)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Data on the confidence of a phylogenetic tree.
@graph.rdfs:label: Phylogenetic tree report (tree evaluation)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Distances, such as Branch Score distance, between two or more phylogenetic trees.
Phylogenetic tree report (tree distances)
@graph.rdfs:label: Phylogenetic tree distances

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Molecular clock and stratigraphic (age) data derived from phylogenetic tree analysis.
@graph.rdfs:label: Phylogenetic tree report (tree stratigraphic)

CHEBI:23367

@graph.rdfs:comment: C-beta atoms from amino acid side-chains may be included.

@graph.rdfs:comment: C-beta atoms from amino acid side-chains may be included.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein domain (C-alpha atoms)

Structure alignment (protein)
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein structure alignment

@graph.rdfs:label: Structure alignment (protein pair)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Alignment (superimposition) of more than two protein tertiary (3D) structures.

@graph.rdfs:label: Structure alignment (protein all atoms)

@graph.rdfs:label: Multiple protein tertiary structure alignment (C-alpha atoms)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Alignment (superimposition) of exactly two nucleic acid tertiary (3D) structures.
@graph.rdfs:label: Structure alignment (nucleic acid pair)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Alignment (superimposition) of more than two nucleic acid tertiary (3D) structures.
@graph.rdfs:label: Multiple nucleic acid tertiary structure alignment

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Alignment (superimposition) of RNA tertiary (3D) structures.
Structure alignment (RNA)
@graph.rdfs:label: RNA structure alignment

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Matrix to transform (rotate/translate) 3D coordinates, typically the transformation necessary to superimpose two molecular structures.

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: DaliLite hit table of protein chain tertiary structure alignment data.
@graph.rdfs:comment: The significant and top-scoring hits for regions of the compared structures is shown. Data such as Z-Scores, number of aligned residues, root-mean-square deviation (RMSD) of atoms and sequence identity are given.
@graph.rdfs:label: DaliLite hit table

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A score reflecting structural similarities of two molecules.
@graph.rdfs:label: Molecular similarity score

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Root-mean-square deviation (RMSD) is calculated to measure the average distance between superimposed macromolecular coordinates.
RMSD
@graph.rdfs:label: Root-mean-square deviation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A measure of the similarity between two ligand fingerprints.
@graph.rdfs:comment: A ligand fingerprint is derived from ligand structural data from a Protein DataBank file. It reflects the elements or groups present or absent, covalent bonds and bond orders and the bonded environment in terms of SATIS codes and BLEEP atom types.
@graph.rdfs:label: Tanimoto similarity score

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A matrix of 3D-1D scores reflecting the probability of amino acids to occur in different tertiary structural environments.
@graph.rdfs:label: 3D-1D scoring matrix

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A table of 20 numerical values which quantify a property (e.g. physicochemical or biochemical) of the common amino acids.
@graph.rdfs:label: Amino acid index

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Chemical classification (small, aliphatic, aromatic, polar, charged etc) of amino acids.
Chemical classes (amino acids)
@graph.rdfs:label: Amino acid index (chemical classes)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Statistical protein contact potentials.
Contact potentials (amino acid pair-wise)
@graph.rdfs:label: Amino acid pair-wise contact potentials

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Molecular weights of amino acids.
Molecular weight (amino acids)
@graph.rdfs:label: Amino acid index (molecular weight)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Hydrophobic, hydrophilic or charge properties of amino acids.
Hydropathy (amino acids)
@graph.rdfs:label: Amino acid index (hydropathy)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Experimental free energy values for the water-interface and water-octanol transitions for the amino acids.
White-Wimley data (amino acids)
@graph.rdfs:label: Amino acid index (White-Wimley data)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Van der Waals radii of atoms for different amino acid residues.
van der Waals radii (amino acids)
@graph.rdfs:label: Amino acid index (van der Waals radii)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An informative report on a specific enzyme.
@graph.rdfs:label: Enzyme report

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An informative report on a specific restriction enzyme such as enzyme reference data.
@graph.rdfs:comment: This might include name of enzyme, organism, isoschizomers, methylation, source, suppliers, literature references, or data on restriction enzyme patterns such as name of enzyme, recognition site, length of pattern, number of cuts made by enzyme, details of blunt or sticky end cut etc.
@graph.rdfs:label: Restriction enzyme report

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: List of molecular weight(s) of one or more proteins or peptides, for example cut by proteolytic enzymes or reagents.
@graph.rdfs:comment: The report might include associated data such as frequency of peptide fragment molecular weights.
@graph.rdfs:label: Peptide molecular weights

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Report on the hydrophobic moment of a polypeptide sequence.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Hydrophobic moment is a peptides hydrophobicity measured for different angles of rotation.
@graph.rdfs:label: Peptide hydrophobic moment

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The aliphatic index of a protein.
@graph.rdfs:comment: The aliphatic index is the relative protein volume occupied by aliphatic side chains.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein aliphatic index

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A protein sequence with annotation on hydrophobic or hydrophilic / charged regions, hydrophobicity plot etc.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Hydrophobic moment is a peptides hydrophobicity measured for different angles of rotation.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein sequence hydropathy plot

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A plot of the mean charge of the amino acids within a window of specified length as the window is moved along a protein sequence.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein charge plot

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The solubility or atomic solvation energy of a protein sequence or structure.
Protein solubility data
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein solubility

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Data on the crystallizability of a protein sequence.
Protein crystallizability data
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein crystallizability

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Data on the stability, intrinsic disorder or globularity of a protein sequence.
Protein globularity data
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein globularity

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The titration curve of a protein.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein titration curve

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The isoelectric point of one proteins.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein isoelectric point

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The pKa value of a protein.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein pKa value

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The hydrogen exchange rate of a protein.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein hydrogen exchange rate

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The extinction coefficient of a protein.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein extinction coefficient

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The optical density of a protein.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein optical density

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An informative report on protein subcellular localisation (nuclear, cytoplasmic, mitochondrial, chloroplast, plastid, membrane etc) or destination (exported / extracellular proteins).

@graph.rdfs:label: Protein subcellular localisation

@graph.rdfs:comment: This includes data on peptide ligands that elicit an immune response (immunogens), allergic cross-reactivity, predicted antigenicity (Hopp and Woods plot) etc. These data are useful in the development of peptide-specific antibodies or multi-epitope vaccines. Methods might use sequence data (for example motifs) and / or structural data.
@graph.rdfs:label: Peptide immunogenicity data

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A report on the immunogenicity of MHC class I or class II binding peptides.
@graph.rdfs:label: MHC peptide immunogenicity report

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A human-readable collection of information about one or more specific protein 3D structure(s) or structural domains.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein structure report

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Report on the quality of a protein three-dimensional model.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Model validation might involve checks for atomic packing, steric clashes, agreement with electron density maps etc.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein structural quality report

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Data on inter-atomic or inter-residue contacts, distances and interactions in protein structure(s) or on the interactions of protein atoms or residues with non-protein groups.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein non-covalent interactions report

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Informative report on flexibility or motion of a protein structure.
@graph.rdfs:comment: This is a broad data type and is used a placeholder for other, more specific types.  It is primarily intended to help navigation of EDAM and would not typically be used for annotation.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein flexibility or motion report

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Data on the solvent accessible or buried surface area of a protein structure.
@graph.rdfs:comment: This concept covers definitions of the protein surface, interior and interfaces, accessible and buried residues, surface accessible pockets, interior inaccessible cavities etc.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein solvent accessibility

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Data on the surface properties (shape, hydropathy, electrostatic patches etc) of a protein structure.
@graph.rdfs:comment: This is a broad data type and is used a placeholder for other, more specific types.  It is primarily intended to help navigation of EDAM and would not typically be used for annotation.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein surface report

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Phi/psi angle data or a Ramachandran plot of a protein structure.
@graph.rdfs:label: Ramachandran plot

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Data on the net charge distribution (dipole moment) of a protein structure.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein dipole moment

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A matrix of distances between amino acid residues (for example the C-alpha atoms) in a protein structure.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein distance matrix

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An amino acid residue contact map for a protein structure.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein contact map

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Report on clusters of contacting residues in protein structures such as a key structural residue network.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein residue 3D cluster

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Patterns of hydrogen bonding in protein structures.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein hydrogen bonds

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Non-canonical atomic interactions in protein structures.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein non-canonical interactions

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Information on a node from the CATH database.
@graph.rdfs:comment: The report (for example http://www.cathdb.info/cathnode/1.10.10.10) includes CATH code (of the node and upper levels in the hierarchy), classification text (of appropriate levels in hierarchy), list of child nodes, representative domain and other relevant data and links.
@graph.rdfs:label: CATH node

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Information on a node from the SCOP database.
@graph.rdfs:label: SCOP node

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An EMBASSY domain classification file (DCF) of classification and other data for domains from SCOP or CATH, in EMBL-like format.
@graph.rdfs:label: EMBASSY domain classification

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Information on a protein 'class' node from the CATH database.
@graph.rdfs:label: CATH class

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Information on a protein 'architecture' node from the CATH database.
@graph.rdfs:label: CATH architecture

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Information on a protein 'topology' node from the CATH database.
@graph.rdfs:label: CATH topology

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Information on a protein 'homologous superfamily' node from the CATH database.
@graph.rdfs:label: CATH homologous superfamily

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Information on a protein 'structurally similar group' node from the CATH database.
@graph.rdfs:label: CATH structurally similar group

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Information on a protein 'functional category' node from the CATH database.
@graph.rdfs:label: CATH functional category

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A report on known protein structural domains or folds that are recognised (identified) in protein sequence(s).
@graph.rdfs:comment: Methods use some type of mapping between sequence and fold, for example secondary structure prediction and alignment, profile comparison, sequence properties, homologous sequence search, kernel machines etc. Domains and folds might be taken from SCOP or CATH.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein fold recognition report

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: protein-protein interaction(s), including interactions between protein domains.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein-protein interaction report

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An informative report on protein-ligand (small molecule) interaction(s).
Protein-drug interaction report
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein-ligand interaction report

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: protein-DNA/RNA interaction(s).
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein-nucleic acid interactions report

http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Nucleic acid melting curve: a melting curve of a double-stranded nucleic acid molecule (DNA or DNA/RNA). Shows the proportion of nucleic acid which are double-stranded versus temperature.

Nucleic acid probability profile: a probability profile of a double-stranded nucleic acid molecule (DNA or DNA/RNA). Shows the probability of a base pair not being melted (i.e. remaining as double-stranded DNA) at a specified temperature

Nucleic acid stitch profile: stitch profile of hybridised or double stranded nucleic acid (DNA or RNA/DNA). A stitch profile diagram shows partly melted DNA conformations (with probabilities) at a range of temperatures. For example, a stitch profile might show possible loop openings with their location, size, probability and fluctuations at a given temperature.
Nucleic acid temperature profile: a temperature profile of a double-stranded nucleic acid molecule (DNA or DNA/RNA). Plots melting temperature versus base position.
@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Data on the dissociation characteristics of a double-stranded nucleic acid molecule (DNA or a DNA/RNA hybrid) during heating.
Nucleic acid stability profile
@graph.rdfs:comment: A melting (stability) profile calculated the free energy required to unwind and separate the nucleic acid strands, plotted for sliding windows over a sequence.
@graph.rdfs:label: Nucleic acid melting profile

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Enthalpy of hybridised or double stranded nucleic acid (DNA or RNA/DNA).
@graph.rdfs:label: Nucleic acid enthalpy

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Entropy of hybridised or double stranded nucleic acid (DNA or RNA/DNA).
@graph.rdfs:label: Nucleic acid entropy

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Melting temperature of hybridised or double stranded nucleic acid (DNA or RNA/DNA).
@graph.rdfs:label: Nucleic acid melting temperature

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Stitch profile of hybridised or double stranded nucleic acid (DNA or RNA/DNA).
@graph.rdfs:label: Nucleic acid stitch profile

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: DNA base pair stacking energies data.
@graph.rdfs:label: DNA base pair stacking energies data

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: DNA base pair twist angle data.
@graph.rdfs:label: DNA base pair twist angle data

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: DNA base trimer roll angles data.
@graph.rdfs:label: DNA base trimer roll angles data

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: RNA parameters used by the Vienna package.
@graph.rdfs:label: Vienna RNA parameters

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Structure constraints used by the Vienna package.
@graph.rdfs:label: Vienna RNA structure constraints

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: RNA concentration data used by the Vienna package.
@graph.rdfs:label: Vienna RNA concentration data

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: RNA calculated energy data generated by the Vienna package.
@graph.rdfs:label: Vienna RNA calculated energy

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Dotplot of RNA base pairing probability matrix.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Such as generated by the Vienna package.
@graph.rdfs:label: Base pairing probability matrix dotplot

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A human-readable collection of information about RNA/DNA folding, minimum folding energies for DNA or RNA sequences, energy landscape of RNA mutants etc.
@graph.rdfs:label: Nucleic acid folding report

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Table of codon usage data calculated from one or more nucleic acid sequences.
@graph.rdfs:comment: A codon usage table might include the codon usage table name, optional comments and a table with columns for codons and corresponding codon usage data. A genetic code can be extracted from or represented by a codon usage table.
@graph.rdfs:label: Codon usage table

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A genetic code for an organism.
@graph.rdfs:comment: A genetic code need not include detailed codon usage information.
@graph.rdfs:label: Genetic code

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A simple measure of synonymous codon usage bias often used to predict gene expression levels.
@graph.rdfs:label: Codon adaptation index

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A plot of the synonymous codon usage calculated for windows over a nucleotide sequence.
Synonymous codon usage statistic plot
@graph.rdfs:label: Codon usage bias plot

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The effective number of codons used in a gene sequence.  This reflects how far codon usage of a gene departs from equal usage of synonymous codons.
@graph.rdfs:label: Nc statistic

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The differences in codon usage fractions between two codon usage tables.
@graph.rdfs:label: Codon usage fraction difference

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A human-readable collection of information about the influence of genotype on drug response.
@graph.rdfs:comment: The report might correlate gene expression or single-nucleotide polymorphisms with drug efficacy or toxicity.
@graph.rdfs:label: Pharmacogenomic test report

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A human-readable collection of information about a specific disease.
@graph.rdfs:comment: For example, an informative report on a specific tumor including nature and origin of the sample, anatomic site, organ or tissue, tumor type, including morphology and/or histologic type, and so on.
@graph.rdfs:label: Disease report

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A report on linkage disequilibrium; the non-random association of alleles or polymorphisms at two or more loci (not necessarily on the same chromosome).
@graph.rdfs:label: Linkage disequilibrium (report)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A graphical 2D tabular representation of expression data, typically derived from an omics experiment. A heat map is a table where rows and columns correspond to different features and contexts (for example, cells or samples) and the cell colour represents the level of expression of a gene that context.
@graph.rdfs:label: Heat map

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Affymetrix library file of information about which probes belong to which probe set.
@graph.rdfs:label: Affymetrix probe sets library file

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Affymetrix library file of information about the probe sets such as the gene name with which the probe set is associated.
GIN file
@graph.rdfs:label: Affymetrix probe sets information library file

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An entry (data type) from the Minimal Information Requested in the Annotation of Biochemical Models (MIRIAM) database of data resources.
@graph.rdfs:comment: A MIRIAM entry describes a MIRIAM data type including the official name, synonyms, root URI, identifier pattern (regular expression applied to a unique identifier of the data type) and documentation. Each data type can be associated with several resources. Each resource is a physical location of a service (typically a database) providing information on the elements of a data type. Several resources may exist for each data type, provided the same (mirrors) or different information. MIRIAM provides a stable and persistent reference to its data types.
@graph.rdfs:label: MIRIAM datatype

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A simple floating point number defining the lower or upper limit of an expectation value (E-value).
Expectation value
@graph.rdfs:comment: An expectation value (E-Value) is the expected number of observations which are at least as extreme as observations expected to occur by random chance. The E-value describes the number of hits with a given score or better that are expected to occur at random when searching a database of a particular size. It decreases exponentially with the score (S) of a hit. A low E value indicates a more significant score.
@graph.rdfs:label: E-value

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The z-value is the number of standard deviations a data value is above or below a mean value.
@graph.rdfs:comment: A z-value might be specified as a threshold for reporting hits from database searches.
@graph.rdfs:label: Z-value

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The P-value is the probability of obtaining by random chance a result that is at least as extreme as an observed result, assuming a NULL hypothesis is true.
@graph.rdfs:comment: A z-value might be specified as a threshold for reporting hits from database searches.
@graph.rdfs:label: P-value

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The name of a taxon from the NCBI taxonomy database.
@graph.rdfs:label: NCBI taxon

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An alternative for a word.
@graph.rdfs:label: Synonym

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A common misspelling of a word.
@graph.rdfs:label: Misspelling

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An abbreviation of a phrase or word.
@graph.rdfs:label: Acronym

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A term which is likely to be misleading of its meaning.
@graph.rdfs:label: Misnomer

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Moby:Author
Information on the authors of a published work.
@graph.rdfs:label: Author ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An identifier representing an author in the DragonDB database.
@graph.rdfs:label: DragonDB author identifier

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Moby:DescribedLink
A URI along with annotation describing the data found at the address.
@graph.rdfs:label: Annotated URI

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A controlled vocabulary for words and phrases that can appear in the keywords field (KW line) of entries from the UniProt database.
@graph.rdfs:label: UniProt keywords

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Moby_namespace:GENEFARM_GeneID
Identifier of a gene from the GeneFarm database.
@graph.rdfs:label: Gene ID (GeneFarm)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Moby_namespace:Blattner_number
The blattner identifier for a gene.
@graph.rdfs:label: Blattner number

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Moby_namespace:MIPS_GE_Maize
Identifier for genetic elements in MIPS Maize database.
@graph.rdfs:label: Gene ID (MIPS Maize)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Moby_namespace:MIPS_GE_Medicago
Identifier for genetic elements in MIPS Medicago database.
@graph.rdfs:label: Gene ID (MIPS Medicago)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Moby_namespace:DragonDB_Gene
The name of an Antirrhinum Gene from the DragonDB database.
@graph.rdfs:label: Gene name (DragonDB)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A unique identifier for an Arabidopsis gene, which is an acronym or abbreviation of the gene name.
@graph.rdfs:label: Gene name (Arabidopsis)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Moby_namespace:iHOPsymbol
A unique identifier of a protein or gene used in the iHOP database.
@graph.rdfs:label: iHOP symbol

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Name of a gene from the GeneFarm database.
GeneFarm gene ID
@graph.rdfs:label: Gene name (GeneFarm)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A unique name or other identifier of a genetic locus, typically conforming to a scheme that names loci (such as predicted genes) depending on their position in a molecular sequence, for example a completely sequenced genome or chromosome.
@graph.rdfs:label: Locus ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: http://www.geneontology.org/doc/GO.xrf_abbs:AGI_LocusCode
Locus identifier for Arabidopsis Genome Initiative (TAIR, TIGR and MIPS databases)
@graph.rdfs:label: Locus ID (AGI)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier for loci from ASPGD (Aspergillus Genome Database).
@graph.rdfs:label: Locus ID (ASPGD)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: http://www.geneontology.org/doc/GO.xrf_abbs: Broad_MGG
Identifier for loci from Magnaporthe grisea Database at the Broad Institute.
@graph.rdfs:label: Locus ID (MGG)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier for loci from CGD (Candida Genome Database).
@graph.rdfs:label: Locus ID (CGD)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Locus identifier for Comprehensive Microbial Resource at the J. Craig Venter Institute.
@graph.rdfs:label: Locus ID (CMR)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier for loci from NCBI database.
Locus ID (NCBI)
@graph.rdfs:label: NCBI locus tag

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier for loci from SGD (Saccharomyces Genome Database).
SGDID
@graph.rdfs:label: Locus ID (SGD)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Moby_namespace:MMP_Locus
Identifier of loci from Maize Mapping Project.
@graph.rdfs:label: Locus ID (MMP)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Moby_namespace:DDB_gene
Identifier of locus from DictyBase (Dictyostelium discoideum).
@graph.rdfs:label: Locus ID (DictyBase)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of a locus from EntrezGene database.
@graph.rdfs:label: Locus ID (EntrezGene)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Moby_namespace:MaizeGDB_Locus
Identifier of locus from MaizeGDB (Maize genome database).
@graph.rdfs:label: Locus ID (MaizeGDB)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Moby:SO_QTL

A stretch of DNA that is closely linked to the genes underlying a quantitative trait (a phenotype that varies in degree and depends upon the interactions between multiple genes and their environment).
@graph.rdfs:comment: A QTL sometimes but does not necessarily correspond to a gene.
@graph.rdfs:label: Quantitative trait locus

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Moby_namespace:GeneId
Identifier of a gene from the KOME database.
@graph.rdfs:label: Gene ID (KOME)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Moby:Tropgene_locus
Identifier of a locus from the Tropgene database.
@graph.rdfs:label: Locus ID (Tropgene)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An alignment of molecular sequences, structures or profiles derived from them.
@graph.rdfs:label: Alignment

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Data for an atom (in a molecular structure).
General atomic property
@graph.rdfs:label: Atomic property

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A word or phrase that can appear in the keywords field (KW line) of entries from the UniProt database.
@graph.rdfs:label: UniProt keyword

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A name for a genetic locus conforming to a scheme that names loci (such as predicted genes) depending on their position in a molecular sequence, for example a completely sequenced genome or chromosome.
@graph.rdfs:label: Ordered locus name

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A position in a map (for example a genetic map), either a single position (point) or a region / interval.
@graph.rdfs:comment: This includes positions in genomes based on a reference sequence. A position may be specified for any mappable object, i.e. anything that may have positional information such as a physical position in a chromosome. Data might include sequence region name, strand, coordinate system name, assembly name, start position and end position.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence coordinates

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Data concerning the intrinsic physical (e.g. structural) or chemical properties of one, more or all amino acids.
Amino acid data
@graph.rdfs:label: Amino acid property

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A human-readable collection of information which (typically) is generated or collated by hand and which describes a biological entity, phenomena or associated primary (e.g. sequence or structural) data, as distinct from the primary data itself and computer-generated reports derived from it.
@graph.rdfs:comment: This is a broad data type and is used a placeholder for other, more specific types.
@graph.rdfs:label: Annotation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Data describing a molecular map (genetic or physical) or a set of such maps, including various attributes of, data extracted from or derived from the analysis of them, but exluding the map(s) themselves. This  includes metadata for map sets that share a common set of features which are mapped.
@graph.rdfs:label: Map data

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Data used by the Vienna RNA analysis package.
@graph.rdfs:label: Vienna RNA structural data

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Data used to replace (mask) characters in a molecular sequence.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence mask parameter

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Data concerning chemical reaction(s) catalysed by enzyme(s).
@graph.rdfs:comment: This is a broad data type and is used a placeholder for other, more specific types.
@graph.rdfs:label: Enzyme kinetics data

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A plot giving an approximation of the kinetics of an enzyme-catalysed reaction, assuming simple kinetics (i.e. no intermediate or product inhibition, allostericity or cooperativity). It plots initial reaction rate to the substrate concentration (S) from which the maximum rate (vmax) is apparent.
@graph.rdfs:label: Michaelis Menten plot

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A plot based on the Michaelis Menten equation of enzyme kinetics plotting the ratio of the initial substrate concentration (S) against the reaction velocity (v).
@graph.rdfs:label: Hanes Woolf plot

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Raw data from or annotation on laboratory experiments.
@graph.rdfs:comment: This is a broad data type and is used a placeholder for other, more specific types.  It is primarily intended to help navigation of EDAM and would not typically be used for annotation.
@graph.rdfs:label: Experimental data

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Information on a genome version.
@graph.rdfs:label: Genome version information

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Typically a human-readable summary of body of facts or information indicating why a statement is true or valid. This may include a computational prediction, laboratory experiment, literature reference etc.
@graph.rdfs:label: Evidence

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A molecular sequence and minimal metadata, typically an identifier of the sequence and/or a comment.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence record lite

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: One or more molecular sequences, possibly with associated annotation.
Sequences
@graph.rdfs:comment: This concept is a placeholder of concepts for primary sequence data including raw sequences and sequence records.  It should not normally be used for derivatives such as sequence alignments, motifs or profiles.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A nucleic acid sequence and minimal metadata, typically an identifier of the sequence and/or a comment.
@graph.rdfs:label: Nucleic acid sequence record (lite)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A protein sequence and minimal metadata, typically an identifier of the sequence and/or a comment.
Sequence record lite (protein)
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein sequence record (lite)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A human-readable collection of information including annotation on a biological entity or phenomena, computer-generated reports of analysis of primary data (e.g. sequence or structural), and metadata (data about primary data) or any other free (essentially unformatted) text, as distinct from the primary data itself.
@graph.rdfs:comment: You can use this term by default for any textual report, in case you can't find another, more specific term. Reports may be generated automatically or collated by hand and can include metadata on the origin, source, history, ownership or location of some thing.
@graph.rdfs:label: Report

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: General data for a molecule.
General molecular property
@graph.rdfs:label: Molecular property (general)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Data concerning molecular structural data.
@graph.rdfs:comment: This is a broad data type and is used a placeholder for other, more specific types.
@graph.rdfs:label: Structural data

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A nucleotide sequence motif.
Nucleic acid sequence motif
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence motif (nucleic acid)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An amino acid sequence motif.
Protein sequence motif
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence motif (protein)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Some simple value controlling a search operation, typically a search of a database.
@graph.rdfs:label: Search parameter

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A report of hits from searching a database of some type.
@graph.rdfs:label: Database search results

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The secondary structure assignment (predicted or real) of a nucleic acid or protein.
@graph.rdfs:label: Secondary structure

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An array of numerical values.
Array
@graph.rdfs:comment: This is a broad data type and is used a placeholder for other, more specific types.
@graph.rdfs:label: Matrix

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Data concerning, extracted from, or derived from the analysis of molecular alignment of some type.
@graph.rdfs:comment: This is a broad data type and is used a placeholder for other, more specific types.
@graph.rdfs:label: Alignment data

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A human-readable collection of information about one or more specific nucleic acid molecules.
@graph.rdfs:label: Nucleic acid report

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A human-readable collection of information about one or more molecular tertiary (3D) structures.  It might include annotation on the structure, a computer-generated report of analysis of structural data, and metadata (data about primary data) or any other free (essentially unformatted) text, as distinct from the primary data itself.
Structure-derived report
@graph.rdfs:label: Structure report

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A report on nucleic acid structure-derived data, describing structural properties of a DNA molecule, or any other annotation or information about specific nucleic acid 3D structure(s).
@graph.rdfs:label: Nucleic acid structure data

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A report on the physical (e.g. structural) or chemical properties of molecules, or parts of a molecule.
Physicochemical property
@graph.rdfs:label: Molecular property

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Structural data for DNA base pairs or runs of bases, such as energy or angle data.
@graph.rdfs:label: DNA base structural data

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Information on a database (or ontology) entry version, such as name (or other identifier) or parent database, unique identifier of entry, data, author and so on.
@graph.rdfs:label: Database entry version information

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A persistent (stable) and unique identifier, typically identifying an object (entry) from a database.
@graph.rdfs:label: Accession

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: single nucleotide polymorphism (SNP) in a DNA sequence.
@graph.rdfs:label: SNP

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Reference to a dataset (or a cross-reference between two datasets), typically one or more entries in a biological database or ontology.
@graph.rdfs:comment: A list of database accessions or identifiers are usually included.
@graph.rdfs:label: Data reference

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An identifier of a submitted job.
@graph.rdfs:label: Job identifier

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A name of a thing, which need not necessarily uniquely identify it.
Symbolic name
@graph.rdfs:label: Name

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A label (text token) describing the type of a thing, typically an enumerated string (a string with one of a limited set of values).
@graph.rdfs:label: Type

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An identifier of a software end-user (typically a person).
@graph.rdfs:label: User ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A three-letter code used in the KEGG databases to uniquely identify organisms.
@graph.rdfs:label: KEGG organism code

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Moby_namespace:GeneId
Name of an entry (gene) from the KEGG GENES database.
@graph.rdfs:label: Gene name (KEGG GENES)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of an object from one of the BioCyc databases.
@graph.rdfs:label: BioCyc ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of a compound from the BioCyc chemical compounds database.
@graph.rdfs:label: Compound ID (BioCyc)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of a biological reaction from the BioCyc reactions database.
@graph.rdfs:label: Reaction ID (BioCyc)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of an enzyme from the BioCyc enzymes database.
BioCyc enzyme ID
@graph.rdfs:label: Enzyme ID (BioCyc)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of a biological reaction from a database.
@graph.rdfs:label: Reaction ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An identifier that is re-used for data objects of fundamentally different types (typically served from a single database).
@graph.rdfs:comment: This branch provides an alternative organisation of the concepts nested under 'Accession' and 'Name'. All concepts under here are already included under 'Accession' or 'Name'.
@graph.rdfs:label: Identifier (hybrid)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of a molecular property.
@graph.rdfs:label: Molecular property identifier

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of a codon usage table, for example a genetic code.
Codon usage table identifier
@graph.rdfs:label: Codon usage table ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Primary identifier of an object from the FlyBase database.
@graph.rdfs:label: FlyBase primary identifier

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of an object from the WormBase database.
@graph.rdfs:label: WormBase identifier

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Protein identifier used by WormBase database.
@graph.rdfs:label: WormBase wormpep ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An informative report on a trinucleotide sequence that encodes an amino acid including the triplet sequence, the encoded amino acid or whether it is a start or stop codon.
@graph.rdfs:label: Nucleic acid features (codon)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An identifier of a map of a molecular sequence.
@graph.rdfs:label: Map identifier

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An identifier of a software end-user (typically a person).
@graph.rdfs:label: Person identifier

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Name or other identifier of a nucleic acid molecule.
@graph.rdfs:label: Nucleic acid identifier

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Frame for translation of DNA (3 forward and 3 reverse frames relative to a chromosome).
@graph.rdfs:label: Translation frame specification

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An identifier of a genetic code.
@graph.rdfs:label: Genetic code identifier

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Informal name for a genetic code, typically an organism name.
@graph.rdfs:label: Genetic code name

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Name of a file format such as HTML, PNG, PDF, EMBL, GenBank and so on.
@graph.rdfs:label: File format name

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A label (text token) describing a type of sequence profile such as frequency matrix, Gribskov profile, hidden Markov model etc.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence profile type

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Name of a computer operating system such as Linux, PC or Mac.
@graph.rdfs:label: Operating system name

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A type of point or block mutation, including insertion, deletion, change, duplication and moves.
@graph.rdfs:label: Mutation type

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A logical operator such as OR, AND, XOR, and NOT.
@graph.rdfs:label: Logical operator

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A control of the order of data that is output, for example the order of sequences in an alignment.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Possible options including sorting by score, rank, by increasing P-value (probability, i.e. most statistically significant hits given first) and so on.
@graph.rdfs:label: Results sort order

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A simple parameter that is a toggle (boolean value), typically a control for a modal tool.
@graph.rdfs:label: Toggle

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The width of an output sequence or alignment.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence width

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A penalty for introducing or extending a gap in an alignment.
@graph.rdfs:label: Gap penalty

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A temperature concerning nucleic acid denaturation, typically the temperature at which the two strands of a hybridised or double stranded nucleic acid (DNA or RNA/DNA) molecule separate.
Melting temperature
@graph.rdfs:label: Nucleic acid melting temperature

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The concentration of a chemical compound.
@graph.rdfs:label: Concentration

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Size of the incremental 'step' a sequence window is moved over a sequence.
@graph.rdfs:label: Window step size

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An image of a graph generated by the EMBOSS suite.
@graph.rdfs:label: EMBOSS graph

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An application report generated by the EMBOSS suite.
@graph.rdfs:label: EMBOSS report

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An offset for a single-point sequence position.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence offset

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A value that serves as a threshold for a tool (usually to control scoring or output).
@graph.rdfs:label: Threshold

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An informative report on a transcription factor protein.
@graph.rdfs:comment: This might include conformational or physicochemical properties, as well as sequence information for transcription factor(s) binding sites.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein report (transcription factor)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The name of a category of biological or bioinformatics database.
@graph.rdfs:label: Database category name

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Name of a sequence profile.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence profile name

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Specification of one or more colors.
@graph.rdfs:label: Color

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A parameter that is used to control rendering (drawing) to a device or image.
@graph.rdfs:label: Rendering parameter

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Any arbitrary name of a molecular sequence.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence name

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A temporal date.
@graph.rdfs:label: Date

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Word composition data for a molecular sequence.
@graph.rdfs:label: Word composition

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A plot of Fickett testcode statistic (identifying protein coding regions) in a nucleotide sequences.
@graph.rdfs:label: Fickett testcode plot

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A plot of sequence similarities identified from word-matching or character comparison.
Sequence conservation report
@graph.rdfs:comment: Use this concept for calculated substitution rates, relative site variability, data on sites with biased properties, highly conserved or very poorly conserved sites, regions, blocks etc.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence similarity plot

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An image of peptide sequence sequence looking down the axis of the helix for highlighting amphipathicity and other properties.
@graph.rdfs:label: Helical wheel

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An image of peptide sequence sequence in a simple 3,4,3,4 repeating pattern that emulates at a simple level the arrangement of residues around an alpha helix.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Useful for highlighting amphipathicity and other properties.
@graph.rdfs:label: Helical net

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A plot of general physicochemical properties of a protein sequence.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein sequence properties plot

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A plot of pK versus pH for a protein.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein ionisation curve

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A plot of character or word composition / frequency of a molecular sequence.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence composition plot

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Density plot (of base composition) for a nucleotide sequence.
@graph.rdfs:label: Nucleic acid density plot

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Image of a sequence trace (nucleotide sequence versus probabilities of each of the 4 bases).
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence trace image

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A report on siRNA duplexes in mRNA.
@graph.rdfs:label: Nucleic acid features (siRNA)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A collection of multiple molecular sequences and (typically) associated metadata that is intended for sequential processing.
@graph.rdfs:comment: This concept may be used for sequence sets that are expected to be read and processed a single sequence at a time.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence set (stream)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Secondary identifier of an object from the FlyBase database.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Secondary identifier are used to handle entries that were merged with or split from other entries in the database.
@graph.rdfs:label: FlyBase secondary identifier

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The number of a certain thing.
@graph.rdfs:label: Cardinality

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A single thing.
@graph.rdfs:label: Exactly 1

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: One or more things.
@graph.rdfs:label: 1 or more

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Exactly two things.
@graph.rdfs:label: Exactly 2

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Two or more things.
@graph.rdfs:label: 2 or more

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A fixed-size datum calculated (by using a hash function) for a molecular sequence, typically for purposes of error detection or indexing.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence checksum

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: chemical modification of a protein.
