@graph.rdfs:comment: This is a broad data type and is used a placeholder for other, more specific types.
@graph.rdfs:label: Reaction data

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Data concerning small peptides.
Peptide data
@graph.rdfs:label: Peptide property

@graph.http://edamontology.org/deprecation_comm: Was deprecated since 1.5, but not correctly (fully) obsoleted until 1.19.
@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An informative report concerning the classification of protein sequences or structures.
@graph.rdfs:comment: This is a broad data type and is used a placeholder for other, more specific types.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein classification

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Data concerning specific or conserved pattern in molecular sequences.
@graph.rdfs:comment: This is a broad data type and is used a placeholder for other, more specific types.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence motif data

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Data concerning models representing a (typically multiple) sequence alignment.
@graph.rdfs:comment: This is a broad data type and is used a placeholder for other, more specific types.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence profile data

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Data concerning a specific biological pathway or network.
@graph.rdfs:label: Pathway or network data

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An informative report concerning or derived from the analysis of a biological pathway or network, such as a map (diagram) or annotation.
@graph.rdfs:label: Pathway or network report

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A thermodynamic or kinetic property of a nucleic acid molecule.
@graph.rdfs:label: Nucleic acid thermodynamic data

@graph.http://edamontology.org/deprecation_comm: Was deprecated since 1.5, but not correctly (fully) obsoleted until 1.19.
@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Data concerning the classification of nucleic acid sequences or structures.
@graph.rdfs:comment: This is a broad data type and is used a placeholder for other, more specific types.
@graph.rdfs:label: Nucleic acid classification

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A report on a classification of molecular sequences, structures or other entities.
@graph.rdfs:comment: This can include an entire classification, components such as classifiers, assignments of entities to a classification and so on.
@graph.rdfs:label: Classification report

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: key residues involved in protein folding.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein features report (key folding sites)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Geometry data for a protein structure, for example bond lengths, bond angles, torsion angles, chiralities, planaraties etc.
Torsion angle data
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein geometry data

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An image of protein structure.
Structure image (protein)
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein structure image

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Weights for sequence positions or characters in phylogenetic analysis where zero is defined as unweighted.
@graph.rdfs:label: Phylogenetic character weights

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Annotation of one particular positional feature on a biomolecular (typically genome) sequence, suitable for import and display in a genome browser.
@graph.rdfs:label: Annotation track

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Accession number of a UniProt (protein sequence) database entry.
@graph.rdfs:label: UniProt accession

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of a genetic code in the NCBI list of genetic codes.
@graph.rdfs:label: NCBI genetic code ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of a concept in an ontology of biological or bioinformatics concepts and relations.
@graph.rdfs:label: Ontology concept identifier

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The name of a concept for a biological process from the GO ontology.
@graph.rdfs:label: GO concept name (biological process)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The name of a concept for a molecular function from the GO ontology.
@graph.rdfs:label: GO concept name (molecular function)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Data concerning the classification, identification and naming of organisms.
Taxonomic data
@graph.rdfs:comment: This is a broad data type and is used a placeholder for other, more specific types.
@graph.rdfs:label: Taxonomy

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: EMBL/GENBANK/DDBJ coding feature protein identifier, issued by International collaborators.
@graph.rdfs:comment: This qualifier consists of a stable ID portion (3+5 format with 3 position letters and 5 numbers) plus a version number after the decimal point. When the protein sequence encoded by the CDS changes, only the version number of the /protein_id value is incremented; the stable part of the /protein_id remains unchanged and as a result will permanently be associated with a given protein; this qualifier is valid only on CDS features which translate into a valid protein.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein ID (EMBL/GenBank/DDBJ)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A type of data that (typically) corresponds to entries from the primary biological databases and which is (typically) the primary input or output of a tool, i.e. the data the tool processes or generates, as distinct from metadata and identifiers which describe and identify such core data, parameters that control the behaviour of tools, reports of derivative data generated by tools and annotation.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Core data entities typically have a format and may be identified by an accession number.
@graph.rdfs:label: Core data

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Name or other identifier of molecular sequence feature(s).
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence feature identifier

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An identifier of a molecular tertiary structure, typically an entry from a structure database.
@graph.rdfs:label: Structure identifier

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An identifier of an array of numerical values, such as a comparison matrix.
@graph.rdfs:label: Matrix identifier

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A report (typically a table) on character or word composition / frequency of protein sequence(s).
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein sequence composition

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A report (typically a table) on character or word composition / frequency of nucleic acid sequence(s).
@graph.rdfs:label: Nucleic acid sequence composition (report)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A node from a classification of protein structural domain(s).
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein domain classification node

@graph.http://edamontology.org/deprecation_comm: Duplicates http://edamontology.org/data_1002, hence deprecated.
@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Unique numerical identifier of chemicals in the scientific literature, as assigned by the Chemical Abstracts Service.
@graph.rdfs:label: CAS number

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Unique identifier of a drug conforming to the Anatomical Therapeutic Chemical (ATC) Classification System, a drug classification system controlled by the WHO Collaborating Centre for Drug Statistics Methodology (WHOCC).
@graph.rdfs:label: ATC code

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A unique, unambiguous, alphanumeric identifier of a chemical substance as catalogued by the Substance Registration System of the Food and Drug Administration (FDA).
Unique Ingredient Identifier
@graph.rdfs:label: UNII

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Basic information concerning geographical location or time.
@graph.rdfs:label: Geotemporal metadata

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Metadata concerning the software, hardware or other aspects of a computer system.
@graph.rdfs:label: System metadata

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A name of a sequence feature, e.g. the name of a feature to be displayed to an end-user.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence feature name

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Raw data such as measurements or other results from laboratory experiments, as generated from laboratory hardware.
@graph.rdfs:comment: This is a broad data type and is used a placeholder for other, more specific types. It is primarily intended to help navigation of EDAM and would not typically be used for annotation.
@graph.rdfs:label: Experimental measurement

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Raw data (typically MIAME-compliant) for hybridisations from a microarray experiment.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Such data as found in Affymetrix CEL or GPR files.
@graph.rdfs:label: Raw microarray data

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Data generated from processing and analysis of probe set data from a microarray experiment.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Such data as found in Affymetrix .CHP files or data from other software such as RMA or dChip.
@graph.rdfs:label: Processed microarray data

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The final processed (normalised) data for a set of hybridisations in a microarray experiment.
@graph.rdfs:comment: This combines data from all hybridisations.
@graph.rdfs:label: Gene expression matrix

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Annotation on a biological sample, for example experimental factors and their values.
@graph.rdfs:comment: This might include compound and dose in a dose response experiment.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sample annotation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Annotation on the array itself used in a microarray experiment.
@graph.rdfs:comment: This might include gene identifiers, genomic coordinates, probe oligonucleotide sequences etc.
@graph.rdfs:label: Microarray metadata

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Annotation on laboratory and/or data processing protocols used in an microarray experiment.
@graph.rdfs:comment: This might describe e.g. the normalisation methods used to process the raw data.
@graph.rdfs:label: Microarray protocol annotation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Data concerning the hybridisations measured during a microarray experiment.
@graph.rdfs:label: Microarray hybridisation data

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A report of regions in a molecular sequence that are biased to certain characters.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence features (compositionally-biased regions)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A report on features in a nucleic acid sequence that indicate changes to or differences between sequences.
@graph.rdfs:label: Nucleic acid features (difference and change)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The report may be based on analysis of nucleic acid sequence or structural data, or any annotation or information about specific nucleic acid 3D structure(s) or such structures in general.
A human-readable collection of information about regions within a nucleic acid sequence which form secondary or tertiary (3D) structures.
Nucleic acid features (structure)
@graph.rdfs:label: Nucleic acid structure report

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: short repetitive subsequences (repeat sequences) in a protein sequence.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein features report (repeats)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Report on the location of matches to profiles, motifs (conserved or functional patterns) or other signatures in one or more protein sequences.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence motif matches (protein)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Report on the location of matches to profiles, motifs (conserved or functional patterns) or other signatures in one or more nucleic acid sequences.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence motif matches (nucleic acid)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A report on displacement loops in a mitochondrial DNA sequence.
@graph.rdfs:comment: A displacement loop is a region of mitochondrial DNA in which one of the strands is displaced by an RNA molecule.
@graph.rdfs:label: Nucleic acid features (d-loop)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A report on stem loops in a DNA sequence.
@graph.rdfs:comment: A stem loop is a hairpin structure; a double-helical structure formed when two complementary regions of a single strand of RNA or DNA molecule form base-pairs.
@graph.rdfs:label: Nucleic acid features (stem loop)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An informative report on features of a messenger RNA (mRNA) molecules including precursor RNA, primary (unprocessed) transcript and fully processed molecules. This includes reports on a specific gene transcript, clone or EST.
@graph.rdfs:comment: This includes 5'untranslated region (5'UTR), coding sequences (CDS), exons, intervening sequences (intron) and 3'untranslated regions (3'UTR).
@graph.rdfs:label: Gene transcript report

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: features of non-coding or functional RNA molecules, including tRNA and rRNA.
@graph.rdfs:label: Non-coding RNA

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Features concerning transcription of DNA into RNA including the regulation of transcription.
@graph.rdfs:comment: This includes promoters, CAAT signals, TATA signals, -35 signals, -10 signals, GC signals, primer binding sites for initiation of transcription or reverse transcription, enhancer, attenuator, terminators and ribosome binding sites.
@graph.rdfs:label: Transcriptional features (report)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A report on predicted or actual immunoglobulin gene structure including constant, switch and variable regions and diversity, joining and variable segments.
@graph.rdfs:label: Nucleic acid features (immunoglobulin gene structure)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Information on a 'class' node from the SCOP database.
@graph.rdfs:label: SCOP class

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Information on a 'fold' node from the SCOP database.
@graph.rdfs:label: SCOP fold

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Information on a 'superfamily' node from the SCOP database.
@graph.rdfs:label: SCOP superfamily

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Information on a 'family' node from the SCOP database.
@graph.rdfs:label: SCOP family

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Information on a 'protein' node from the SCOP database.
@graph.rdfs:label: SCOP protein

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Information on a 'species' node from the SCOP database.
@graph.rdfs:label: SCOP species

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: mass spectrometry experiments.
@graph.rdfs:label: Mass spectrometry experiment

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Nucleic acid classification

A human-readable collection of information about a particular family of genes, typically a set of genes with similar sequence that originate from duplication of a common ancestor gene, or any other classification of nucleic acid sequences or structures that reflects gene structure.
@graph.rdfs:comment: This includes reports on on gene homologues between species.
@graph.rdfs:label: Gene family report

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An image of a protein.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein image

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An alignment of protein sequences and/or structures.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein alignment

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: sequencing experiment, including samples, sampling, preparation, sequencing, and analysis.
@graph.rdfs:label: NGS experiment

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An informative report about a DNA sequence assembly.
Assembly report
@graph.rdfs:comment: This might include an overall quality assement of the assembly and summary statistics including counts, average length and number of bases for reads, matches and non-matches, contigs, reads in pairs etc.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence assembly report

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An index of a genome sequence.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Many sequence alignment tasks involving many or very large sequences rely on a precomputed index of the sequence to accelerate the alignment.
@graph.rdfs:label: Genome index

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Report concerning genome-wide association study experiments.
@graph.rdfs:label: GWAS report

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The position of a cytogenetic band in a genome.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Information might include start and end position in a chromosome sequence, chromosome identifier, name of band and so on.
@graph.rdfs:label: Cytoband position

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Cell type ontology concept ID.
CL ID
@graph.rdfs:label: Cell type ontology ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Mathematical model of a network, that contains biochemical kinetics.
@graph.rdfs:label: Kinetic model

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of a COSMIC database entry.
COSMIC identifier
@graph.rdfs:label: COSMIC ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of a HGMD database entry.
HGMD identifier
@graph.rdfs:label: HGMD ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Unique identifier of sequence assembly.
Sequence assembly version
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence assembly ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A label (text token) describing a type of sequence feature such as gene, transcript, cds, exon, repeat, simple, misc, variation, somatic variation, structural variation, somatic structural variation, constrained or regulatory.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence feature type

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An informative report on gene homologues between species.
@graph.rdfs:label: Gene homology (report)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Unique identifier for a gene tree from the Ensembl database.
Ensembl ID (gene tree)
@graph.rdfs:label: Ensembl gene tree ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A phylogenetic tree that is an estimate of the character's phylogeny.
@graph.rdfs:label: Gene tree

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A phylogenetic tree that reflects phylogeny of the taxa from which the characters (used in calculating the tree) were sampled.
@graph.rdfs:label: Species tree

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Name or other identifier of an entry from a biosample database.
Sample accession
@graph.rdfs:label: Sample ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of an object from the MGI database.
@graph.rdfs:label: MGI accession

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Name of a phenotype.
@graph.rdfs:label: Phenotype name

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A HMM transition matrix contains the probabilities of switching from one HMM state to another.
HMM transition matrix
@graph.rdfs:comment: Consider for example an HMM with two states (AT-rich and GC-rich).  The transition matrix will hold the probabilities of switching from the AT-rich to the GC-rich state, and vica versa.
@graph.rdfs:label: Transition matrix

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A HMM emission matrix holds the probabilities of choosing the four nucleotides (A, C, G and T) in each of the states of a HMM.
HMM emission matrix
@graph.rdfs:comment: Consider for example an HMM with two states (AT-rich and GC-rich).  The emission matrix holds the probabilities of choosing each of the four nucleotides (A, C, G and T) in the AT-rich state and in the GC-rich state.
@graph.rdfs:label: Emission matrix

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A statistical Markov model of a system which is assumed to be a Markov process with unobserved (hidden) states.
@graph.rdfs:label: Hidden Markov model

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An identifier of a data format.
@graph.rdfs:label: Format identifier

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Raw biological or biomedical image generated by some experimental technique.
@graph.rdfs:label: Raw image

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Data concerning the intrinsic physical (e.g. structural) or chemical properties of one, more or all carbohydrates.
Carbohydrate data
@graph.rdfs:label: Carbohydrate property

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Report concerning proteomics experiments.
@graph.rdfs:label: Proteomics experiment report

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: RNAi experiments.
@graph.rdfs:label: RNAi report

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: biological computational model experiments (simulation), for example the minimum information required in order to permit its correct interpretation and reproduction.
@graph.rdfs:label: Simulation experiment report

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An imaging technique that uses magnetic fields and radiowaves to form images, typically to investigate the anatomy and physiology of the human body.
@graph.rdfs:label: MRI image

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An image from a cell migration track assay.
@graph.rdfs:label: Cell migration track image

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Rate of association of a protein with another protein or some other molecule.
kon
@graph.rdfs:label: Rate of association

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Multiple gene identifiers in a specific order.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Such data are often used for genome rearrangement tools and phylogenetic tree labeling.
@graph.rdfs:label: Gene order

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The spectrum of frequencies of electromagnetic radiation emitted from a molecule as a result of some spectroscopy experiment.
Spectra
@graph.rdfs:label: Spectrum

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Spectral information for a molecule from a nuclear magnetic resonance experiment.
NMR spectra
@graph.rdfs:label: NMR spectrum

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A sketch of a small molecule made with some specialised drawing package.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Chemical structure sketches are used for presentational purposes but also as inputs to various analysis software.
@graph.rdfs:label: Chemical structure sketch

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An informative report about a specific or conserved nucleic acid sequence pattern.
@graph.rdfs:label: Nucleic acid signature

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A DNA sequence.
DNA sequences
@graph.rdfs:label: DNA sequence

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An RNA sequence.
RNA sequences
@graph.rdfs:label: RNA sequence

@graph.http://edamontology.org/deprecation_comm: Deprecated because this is bloat / confusing & better handled as an EDAM Format concept - "raw" sequences just imply a particular format (i.e. one with a vanilla string, possible in a particular alphabet, with no metadata).
@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A raw RNA sequence.
@graph.rdfs:label: RNA sequence (raw)

@graph.http://edamontology.org/deprecation_comm: Deprecated because this is bloat / confusing & better handled as an EDAM Format concept - "raw" sequences just imply a particular format (i.e. one with a vanilla string, possible in a particular alphabet, with no metadata).
@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A raw DNA sequence.
@graph.rdfs:label: DNA sequence (raw)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Data on gene sequence variations resulting large-scale genotyping and DNA sequencing projects.
Gene sequence variations
@graph.rdfs:comment: Variations are stored along with a reference genome.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence variations

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A list of publications such as scientic papers or books.
@graph.rdfs:label: Bibliography

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A mapping of supplied textual terms or phrases to ontology concepts (URIs).
@graph.rdfs:label: Ontology mapping

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Any data concerning a specific biological or biomedical image.
@graph.rdfs:comment: This can include basic provenance and technical information about the image, scientific annotation and so on.
@graph.rdfs:label: Image metadata

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A human-readable collection of information concerning a clinical trial.
Clinical trial information
@graph.rdfs:label: Clinical trial report

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A report about a biosample.
Biosample report
@graph.rdfs:label: Reference sample report

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Accession number of an entry from the Gene Expression Atlas.
@graph.rdfs:label: Gene Expression Atlas Experiment ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of an entry from a database of disease.
@graph.rdfs:label: Disease identifier

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The name of some disease.
@graph.rdfs:label: Disease name

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Some material that is used for educational (training) purposes.
@graph.rdfs:label: Training material

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A training course available for use on the Web.
On-line course
@graph.rdfs:label: Online course

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Any free or plain text, typically for human consumption and in English. Can instantiate also as a textual search query.
Free text
@graph.rdfs:label: Text

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Machine-readable biodiversity data.
Biodiversity information
OTU table
@graph.rdfs:label: Biodiversity data

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A human-readable collection of information concerning biosafety data.
Biosafety information
@graph.rdfs:label: Biosafety report

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A report about any kind of isolation of biological material.
@graph.rdfs:label: Isolation report

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Information about the ability of an organism to cause disease in a corresponding host.
Pathogenicity
@graph.rdfs:label: Pathogenicity report

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Information about the biosafety classification of an organism according to corresponding law.
Biosafety level
@graph.rdfs:label: Biosafety classification

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A report about localisation of the isolaton of biological material e.g. country or coordinates.
@graph.rdfs:label: Geographic location

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A report about any kind of isolation source of biological material e.g. blood, water, soil.
@graph.rdfs:label: Isolation source

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Experimentally determined parameter of the physiology of an organism, e.g. substrate spectrum.
@graph.rdfs:label: Physiology parameter

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Experimentally determined parameter of the morphology of an organism, e.g. size & shape.
@graph.rdfs:label: Morphology parameter

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Experimental determined parameter for the cultivation of an organism.
Cultivation conditions
@graph.rdfs:label: Cultivation parameter

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Data concerning a sequencing experiment, that may be specified as an input to some tool.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequencing metadata name

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An identifier of a flow cell of a sequencing machine.
@graph.rdfs:comment: A flow cell is used to immobilise, amplify and sequence millions of molecules at once.  In Illumina machines, a flowcell is composed of  8 "lanes" which allows 8 experiments in a single analysis.
@graph.rdfs:label: Flow cell identifier

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An identifier of a lane within a flow cell of a sequencing machine, within which millions of sequences are immobilised, amplified and sequenced.
@graph.rdfs:label: Lane identifier

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A number corresponding to the number of an analysis performed by a sequencing machine.  For example, if it's the 13th analysis, the run is 13.
@graph.rdfs:label: Run number

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Data concerning ecology; for example measurements and reports from the study of interactions among organisms and their environment.
@graph.rdfs:comment: This is a broad data type and is used a placeholder for other, more specific types.
@graph.rdfs:label: Ecological data

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The mean species diversity in sites or habitats at a local scale.
Î±-diversity
@graph.rdfs:label: Alpha diversity data

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The ratio between regional and local species diversity.
@graph.rdfs:label: Beta diversity data

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The total species diversity in a landscape.
Î³-diversity
@graph.rdfs:label: Gamma diversity data

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A plot in which community data (e.g. species abundance data) is summarised.  Similar species and samples are plotted close together, and dissimilar species and samples are plotted placed far apart.
@graph.rdfs:label: Ordination plot

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A ranked list of categories (usually ontology concepts), each associated with a statistical metric of over-/under-representation within the studied data.
Functional enrichment report
@graph.rdfs:label: Over-representation data

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: GO-term report
A ranked list of Gene Ontology concepts, each associated with a p-value, concerning or derived from the analysis of e.g. a set of genes or proteins.
@graph.rdfs:label: GO-term enrichment data

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Score for localization of one or more post-translational modifications in peptide sequence measured by mass spectrometry.
@graph.rdfs:label: Localisation score

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of a protein modification catalogued in the Unimod database.
@graph.rdfs:label: Unimod ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier for mass spectrometry proteomics data in the proteomexchange.org repository.
@graph.rdfs:label: ProteomeXchange ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Groupings of expression profiles according to a clustering algorithm.
Clustered gene expression profiles
@graph.rdfs:label: Clustered expression profiles

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An identifier of a concept from the BRENDA ontology.
@graph.rdfs:label: BRENDA ontology concept ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A text (such as a scientific article), annotated with notes, data and metadata, such as recognised entities, concepts, and their relations.
@graph.rdfs:label: Annotated text

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A structured query, in form of a script, that defines a database search task.
@graph.rdfs:label: Query script

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Structural 3D model (volume map) from electron microscopy.
@graph.rdfs:label: 3D EM Map

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Annotation on a structural 3D EM Map from electron microscopy. This might include one or several locations in the map of the known features of a particular macromolecule.
@graph.rdfs:label: 3D EM Mask

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Raw DDD movie acquisition from electron microscopy.
@graph.rdfs:label: EM Movie

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Raw acquistion from electron microscopy or average of an aligned DDD movie.
@graph.rdfs:label: EM Micrograph

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Data coming from molecular simulations, computer "experiments" on model molecules.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Typically formed by two separated but indivisible pieces of information: topology data (static) and trajectory data (dynamic).
@graph.rdfs:label: Molecular simulation data

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of an entry from the RNA central database of annotated human miRNAs.
@graph.rdfs:comment: There are canonical and taxon-specific forms of RNAcentral ID. Canonical form e.g. urs_9or10digits identifies an RNA sequence (within the RNA central database) which may appear in multiple sequences. Taxon-specific form identifies a sequence in the specific taxon (e.g. urs_9or10digits_taxonID).
@graph.rdfs:label: RNA central ID

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A human-readable systematic collection of patient (or population) health information in a digital format.
@graph.rdfs:label: Electronic health record

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Data coming from molecular simulations, computer "experiments" on model molecules. Tipically formed by two separated but indivisible pieces of information: topology data (static) and trajectory data (dynamic).
@graph.rdfs:label: Simulation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Dynamic information of a structure molecular system coming from a molecular simulation: XYZ 3D coordinates (sometimes with their associated velocities) for every atom along time.
@graph.rdfs:label: Trajectory data

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Force field parameters: charges, masses, radii, bond lengths, bond dihedrals, etc. define the structural molecular system, and are essential for the proper description and simulation of a molecular system.
@graph.rdfs:label: Forcefield parameters

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Static information of a structure molecular system that is needed for a molecular simulation: the list of atoms, their non-bonded parameters for Van der Waals and electrostatic interactions, and the complete connectivity in terms of bonds, angles and dihedrals.
@graph.rdfs:label: Topology data

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Visualization of distribution of quantitative data, e.g. expression data, by histograms, violin plots and density plots.
Density plot
@graph.rdfs:label: Histogram

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A human-readable collection of information about about how a scientific experiment or analysis was carried out that results in a specific set of data or results used for further analysis or to test a specific hypothesis.
@graph.rdfs:label: Quality control report

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A table of unnormalized values representing summarised read counts per genomic region (e.g. gene, transcript, peak).
Read count matrix
@graph.rdfs:label: Count matrix

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Alignment (superimposition) of DNA tertiary (3D) structures.
Structure alignment (DNA)
@graph.rdfs:label: DNA structure alignment

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A score derived from the P-value to ensure correction for multiple tests. The Q-value provides an estimate of the positive False Discovery Rate (pFDR), i.e. the rate of false positives among all the cases reported positive: pFDR = FP / (FP + TP).
@graph.rdfs:comment: Q-values are widely used in high-throughput data analysis (e.g. detection of differentially expressed genes from transcriptome data).
@graph.rdfs:label: Q-value

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A profile HMM is a variant of a Hidden Markov model that is derived specifically from a set of (aligned) biological sequences. Profile HMMs provide the basis for a position-specific scoring system, which can be used to align sequences and search databases for related sequences.
@graph.rdfs:label: Profile HMM

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identifier of a pathway from the WikiPathways pathway database.
@graph.rdfs:label: Pathway ID (WikiPathways)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A ranked list of pathways, each associated with z-score, p-value or similar, concerning or derived from the analysis of e.g. a set of genes or proteins.
@graph.rdfs:label: Pathway overrepresentation data

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A comment explaining why the comment should be or was deprecated, including name of person commenting (jison, mkalas etc.)
concept_properties
@graph.rdfs:label: deprecation_comment

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: 'Documentation' trailing modifier (qualifier, 'documentation') of 'xref' links of 'Format' concepts. When 'true', the link is pointing to a page with explanation, description, documentation, or specification of the given data format.
Specification
concept_properties
@graph.rdfs:label: Documentation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: 'Example' concept property ('example' metadata tag) lists examples of valid values of types of identifiers (accessions). Applicable to some other types of data, too.
concept_properties
@graph.rdfs:comment: Separated by bar ('|'). For more complex data and data formats, it can be a link to a website with examples, instead.
@graph.rdfs:label: Example

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: 'File extension' concept property ('file_extension' metadata tag) lists examples of usual file extensions of formats.
concept_properties
rdfs:comment: N.B.: File extensions that are not correspondigly defined at http://filext.com are recorded in EDAM only if not in conflict with http://filext.com, and/or unique and usual within life-science computing.
Separated by bar ('|'), without a dot ('.') prefix, preferrably not all capital characters.
@graph.rdfs:label: File extension

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Chemical structure specified in Simplified Molecular Input Line Entry System (SMILES) line notation.
@graph.rdfs:label: SMILES

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Chemical structure specified in IUPAC International Chemical Identifier (InChI) line notation.
@graph.rdfs:label: InChI

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Chemical structure specified by Molecular Formula (MF), including a count of each element in a compound.
@graph.rdfs:comment: The general MF query format consists of a series of valid atomic symbols, with an optional number or range.
@graph.rdfs:label: mf

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The InChIKey (hashed InChI) is a fixed length (25 character) condensed digital representation of an InChI chemical structure specification. It uniquely identifies a chemical compound.
@graph.rdfs:comment: An InChIKey identifier is not human- nor machine-readable but is more suitable for web searches than an InChI chemical structure specification.
@graph.rdfs:label: InChIKey

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: SMILES ARbitrary Target Specification (SMARTS) format for chemical structure specification, which is a subset of the SMILES line notation.
@graph.rdfs:label: smarts

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Alphabet for a molecular sequence with possible unknown positions but without ambiguity or non-sequence characters.
@graph.rdfs:label: unambiguous pure

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Alphabet for a nucleotide sequence with possible ambiguity, unknown positions and non-sequence characters.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Non-sequence characters may be used for example for gaps.
@graph.rdfs:label: nucleotide

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Alphabet for a protein sequence with possible ambiguity, unknown positions and non-sequence characters.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Non-sequence characters may be used for gaps and translation stop.
@graph.rdfs:label: protein

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Alphabet for the consensus of two or more molecular sequences.
@graph.rdfs:label: consensus

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Alphabet for a nucleotide sequence with possible ambiguity and unknown positions but without non-sequence characters.
@graph.rdfs:label: pure nucleotide

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Alphabet for a nucleotide sequence (characters ACGTU only) with possible unknown positions but without ambiguity or non-sequence characters .
@graph.rdfs:label: unambiguous pure nucleotide

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Alphabet for a DNA sequence with possible ambiguity, unknown positions and non-sequence characters.
@graph.rdfs:label: dna

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Alphabet for an RNA sequence with possible ambiguity, unknown positions and non-sequence characters.
@graph.rdfs:label: rna

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Alphabet for a DNA sequence (characters ACGT only) with possible unknown positions but without ambiguity or non-sequence characters.
@graph.rdfs:label: unambiguous pure dna

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Alphabet for a DNA sequence with possible ambiguity and unknown positions but without non-sequence characters.
@graph.rdfs:label: pure dna

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Alphabet for an RNA sequence (characters ACGU only) with possible unknown positions but without ambiguity or non-sequence characters.
@graph.rdfs:label: unambiguous pure rna sequence

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Alphabet for an RNA sequence with possible ambiguity and unknown positions but without non-sequence characters.
@graph.rdfs:label: pure rna

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Alphabet for any protein sequence with possible unknown positions but without ambiguity or non-sequence characters.
@graph.rdfs:label: unambiguous pure protein

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Alphabet for any protein sequence with possible ambiguity and unknown positions but without non-sequence characters.
@graph.rdfs:label: pure protein

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Format of an entry from UniGene.
@graph.rdfs:comment: A UniGene entry includes a set of transcript sequences assigned to the same transcription locus (gene or expressed pseudogene), with information on protein similarities, gene expression, cDNA clone reagents, and genomic location.
@graph.rdfs:label: UniGene entry format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Format of an entry from the COG database of clusters of (related) protein sequences.
@graph.rdfs:label: COG sequence cluster format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Format for sequence positions (feature location) as used in DDBJ/EMBL/GenBank database.
Feature location
@graph.rdfs:label: EMBL feature location

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Report format for tandem repeats in a nucleotide sequence (format generated by the Sanger Centre quicktandem program).
@graph.rdfs:label: quicktandem

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Report format for inverted repeats in a nucleotide sequence (format generated by the Sanger Centre inverted program).
@graph.rdfs:label: Sanger inverted repeats

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Report format for tandem repeats in a sequence (an EMBOSS report format).
@graph.rdfs:label: EMBOSS repeat

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Format of a report on exon-intron structure generated by EMBOSS est2genome.
@graph.rdfs:label: est2genome format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Report format for restriction enzyme recognition sites used by EMBOSS restrict program.
@graph.rdfs:label: restrict format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Report format for restriction enzyme recognition sites used by EMBOSS restover program.
@graph.rdfs:label: restover format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Report format for restriction enzyme recognition sites used by REBASE database.
@graph.rdfs:label: REBASE restriction sites

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Format of results of a sequence database search using FASTA.
@graph.rdfs:comment: This includes (typically) score data, alignment data and a histogram (of observed and expected distribution of E values.)
@graph.rdfs:label: FASTA search results format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Format of results of a sequence database search using some variant of BLAST.
@graph.rdfs:comment: This includes score data, alignment data and summary table.
@graph.rdfs:label: BLAST results

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Format of results of a sequence database search using some variant of MSPCrunch.
@graph.rdfs:label: mspcrunch

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Format of results of a sequence database search using some variant of Smith Waterman.
@graph.rdfs:label: Smith-Waterman format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Format of EMBASSY domain hits file (DHF) of hits (sequences) with domain classification information.
@graph.rdfs:comment: The hits are relatives to a SCOP or CATH family and are found from a search of a sequence database.
@graph.rdfs:label: dhf

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Format of EMBASSY ligand hits file (LHF) of database hits (sequences) with ligand classification information.
@graph.rdfs:comment: The hits are putative ligand-binding sequences and are found from a search of a sequence database.
@graph.rdfs:label: lhf

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Results format for searches of the InterPro database.
@graph.rdfs:label: InterPro hits format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Format of results of a search of the InterPro database showing matches of query protein sequence(s) to InterPro entries.
@graph.rdfs:comment: The report includes a classification of regions in a query protein sequence which are assigned to a known InterPro protein family or group.
@graph.rdfs:label: InterPro protein view report format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Format of results of a search of the InterPro database showing matches between protein sequence(s) and signatures for an InterPro entry.
@graph.rdfs:comment: The table presents matches between query proteins (rows) and signature methods (columns) for this entry. Alternatively the sequence(s) might be from from the InterPro entry itself. The match position in the protein sequence and match status (true positive, false positive etc) are indicated.
@graph.rdfs:label: InterPro match table format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Dirichlet distribution HMMER format.
@graph.rdfs:label: HMMER Dirichlet prior

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Dirichlet distribution MEME format.
@graph.rdfs:label: MEME Dirichlet prior

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Format of a report from the HMMER package on the emission and transition counts of a hidden Markov model.
@graph.rdfs:label: HMMER emission and transition

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Format of a regular expression pattern from the Prosite database.
@graph.rdfs:label: prosite-pattern

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Format of an EMBOSS sequence pattern.
@graph.rdfs:label: EMBOSS sequence pattern

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A motif in the format generated by the MEME program.
@graph.rdfs:label: meme-motif

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Sequence profile (sequence classifier) format used in the PROSITE database.
@graph.rdfs:label: prosite-profile

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A profile (sequence classifier) in the format used in the JASPAR database.
@graph.rdfs:label: JASPAR format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Format of the model of random sequences used by MEME.
@graph.rdfs:label: MEME background Markov model

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Format of a hidden Markov model representation used by the HMMER package.
@graph.rdfs:label: HMMER format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: FASTA-style format for multiple sequences aligned by HMMER package to an HMM.
@graph.rdfs:label: HMMER-aln

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Format of multiple sequences aligned by DIALIGN package.
@graph.rdfs:label: DIALIGN format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: EMBASSY 'domain alignment file' (DAF) format, containing a sequence alignment of protein domains belonging to the same SCOP or CATH family.
@graph.rdfs:comment: The format is clustal-like and includes annotation of domain family classification information.
@graph.rdfs:label: daf

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Format for alignment of molecular sequences to MEME profiles (position-dependent scoring matrices) as generated by the MAST tool from the MEME package.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence-MEME profile alignment

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Format used by the HMMER package for an alignment of a sequence against a hidden Markov model database.
@graph.rdfs:label: HMMER profile alignment (sequences versus HMMs)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Format used by the HMMER package for of an alignment of a hidden Markov model against a sequence database.
@graph.rdfs:label: HMMER profile alignment (HMM versus sequences)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Format of PHYLIP phylogenetic distance matrix data.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Data Type must include the distance matrix, probably as pairs of sequence identifiers with a distance (integer or float).
@graph.rdfs:label: Phylip distance matrix

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Dendrogram (tree file) format generated by ClustalW.
@graph.rdfs:label: ClustalW dendrogram

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Raw data file format used by Phylip from which a phylogenetic tree is directly generated or plotted.
@graph.rdfs:label: Phylip tree raw

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: PHYLIP file format for continuous quantitative character data.
@graph.rdfs:label: Phylip continuous quantitative characters

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Format of phylogenetic property data.
@graph.rdfs:label: Phylogenetic property values format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: PHYLIP file format for phylogenetics character frequency data.
@graph.rdfs:label: Phylip character frequencies format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Format of PHYLIP discrete states data.
@graph.rdfs:label: Phylip discrete states format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Format of PHYLIP cliques data.
@graph.rdfs:label: Phylip cliques format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Phylogenetic tree data format used by the PHYLIP program.
@graph.rdfs:label: Phylip tree format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The format of an entry from the TreeBASE database of phylogenetic data.
@graph.rdfs:label: TreeBASE format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The format of an entry from the TreeFam database of phylogenetic data.
@graph.rdfs:label: TreeFam format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Format for distances, such as Branch Score distance, between two or more phylogenetic trees as used by the Phylip package.
@graph.rdfs:label: Phylip tree distance format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Format of an entry from the DSSP database (Dictionary of Secondary Structure in Proteins).
@graph.rdfs:comment: The DSSP database is built using the DSSP application which defines secondary structure, geometrical features and solvent exposure of proteins, given atomic coordinates in PDB format.
@graph.rdfs:label: dssp

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Entry format of the HSSP database (Homology-derived Secondary Structure in Proteins).
@graph.rdfs:label: hssp

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Format of RNA secondary structure in dot-bracket notation, originally generated by the Vienna RNA package/server.
@graph.rdfs:label: Dot-bracket format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Format of local RNA secondary structure components with free energy values, generated by the Vienna RNA package/server.
@graph.rdfs:label: Vienna local RNA secondary structure format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Format of an entry (or part of an entry) from the PDB database.
PDB entry format
@graph.rdfs:label: PDB database entry format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Entry format of PDB database in PDB format.
PDB format
@graph.rdfs:label: PDB

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Entry format of PDB database in mmCIF format.
@graph.rdfs:label: mmCIF

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Entry format of PDB database in PDBML (XML) format.
@graph.rdfs:label: PDBML

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Format of a matrix of 3D-1D scores used by the EMBOSS Domainatrix applications.
@graph.rdfs:label: Domainatrix 3D-1D scoring matrix format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Amino acid index format used by the AAindex database.
@graph.rdfs:label: aaindex

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Format of an entry from IntEnz (The Integrated Relational Enzyme Database).
@graph.rdfs:comment: IntEnz is the master copy of the Enzyme Nomenclature, the recommendations of the NC-IUBMB on the Nomenclature and Classification of Enzyme-Catalysed Reactions.
@graph.rdfs:label: IntEnz enzyme report format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Format of an entry from the BRENDA enzyme database.
@graph.rdfs:label: BRENDA enzyme report format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Format of an entry from the KEGG REACTION database of biochemical reactions.
@graph.rdfs:label: KEGG REACTION enzyme report format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Format of an entry from the KEGG ENZYME database.
@graph.rdfs:label: KEGG ENZYME enzyme report format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Format of an entry from the proto section of the REBASE enzyme database.
@graph.rdfs:label: REBASE proto enzyme report format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Format of an entry from the withrefm section of the REBASE enzyme database.
@graph.rdfs:label: REBASE withrefm enzyme report format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Format of output of the Pcons Model Quality Assessment Program (MQAP).
@graph.rdfs:comment: Pcons ranks protein models by assessing their quality based on the occurrence of recurring common three-dimensional structural patterns. Pcons returns a score reflecting the overall global quality and a score for each individual residue in the protein reflecting the local residue quality.
@graph.rdfs:label: Pcons report format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Format of output of the ProQ protein model quality predictor.
@graph.rdfs:comment: ProQ is a neural network-based predictor that predicts the quality of a protein model based on the number of structural features.
@graph.rdfs:label: ProQ report format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Format of SMART domain assignment data.
@graph.rdfs:comment: The SMART output file includes data on genetically mobile domains / analysis of domain architectures, including phyletic distributions, functional class, tertiary structures and functionally important residues.
@graph.rdfs:label: SMART domain assignment report format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Entry format for the BIND database of protein interaction.
@graph.rdfs:label: BIND entry format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Entry format for the IntAct database of protein interaction.
@graph.rdfs:label: IntAct entry format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Entry format for the InterPro database of protein signatures (sequence classifiers) and classified sequences.
@graph.rdfs:comment: This includes signature metadata, sequence references and a reference to the signature itself. There is normally a header (entry accession numbers and name), abstract, taxonomy information, example proteins etc. Each entry also includes a match list which give a number of different views of the signature matches for the sequences in each InterPro entry.
@graph.rdfs:label: InterPro entry format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Entry format for the textual abstract of signatures in an InterPro entry and its protein matches.
@graph.rdfs:comment: References are included and a functional inference is made where possible.
@graph.rdfs:label: InterPro entry abstract format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Wiggle format (WIG) of a sequence annotation track that consists of a value for each sequence position. Typically to be displayed in a genome browser.
@graph.rdfs:label: WIG

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: bigWig format for large sequence annotation tracks that consist of a value for each sequence position. Similar to textual WIG format.
@graph.rdfs:label: bigWig

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: PSL format of alignments, typically generated by BLAT or psLayout. Can be displayed in a genome browser like a sequence annotation track.
@graph.rdfs:label: PSL

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Multiple Alignment Format (MAF) supporting alignments of whole genomes with rearrangements, directions, multiple pieces to the alignment, and so forth.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Typically generated by Multiz and TBA aligners; can be displayed in a genome browser like a sequence annotation track. This should not be confused with MIRA Assembly Format or Mutation Annotation Format.
@graph.rdfs:label: MAF

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: 2bit binary format of nucleotide sequences using 2 bits per nucleotide. In addition encodes unknown nucleotides and lower-case 'masking'.
@graph.rdfs:label: 2bit

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: .nib (nibble) binary format of a nucleotide sequence using 4 bits per nucleotide (including unknown) and its lower-case 'masking'.
@graph.rdfs:label: .nib

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: genePred table format for gene prediction tracks.
@graph.rdfs:comment: genePred format has 3 main variations (http://genome.ucsc.edu/FAQ/FAQformat#format9 http://www.broadinstitute.org/software/igv/genePred). They reflect UCSC Browser DB tables.
@graph.rdfs:label: genePred

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Personal Genome SNP (pgSnp) format for sequence variation tracks (indels and polymorphisms), supported by the UCSC Genome Browser.
@graph.rdfs:label: pgSnp

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: axt format of alignments, typically produced from BLASTZ.
@graph.rdfs:label: axt

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: LAV format of alignments generated by BLASTZ and LASTZ.
@graph.rdfs:label: LAV

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Pileup format of alignment of sequences (e.g. sequencing reads) to (a) reference sequence(s). Contains aligned bases per base of the reference sequence(s).
@graph.rdfs:label: Pileup

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Variant Call Format (VCF) for sequence variation (indels, polymorphisms, structural variation).
@graph.rdfs:label: VCF

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Sequence Read Format (SRF) of sequence trace data. Supports submission to the NCBI Short Read Archive.
@graph.rdfs:label: SRF

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: ZTR format for storing chromatogram data from DNA sequencing instruments.
@graph.rdfs:label: ZTR

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Genome Variation Format (GVF). A GFF3-compatible format with defined header and attribute tags for sequence variation.
@graph.rdfs:label: GVF

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: BCF, the binary version of Variant Call Format (VCF) for sequence variation (indels, polymorphisms, structural variation).
@graph.rdfs:label: BCF

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Format of a matrix (array) of numerical values.
@graph.rdfs:label: Matrix format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Format of data concerning the classification of the sequences and/or structures of protein structural domain(s).
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein domain classification format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Format of raw SCOP domain classification data files.
@graph.rdfs:comment: These are the parsable data files provided by SCOP.
@graph.rdfs:label: Raw SCOP domain classification format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Format of raw CATH domain classification data files.
@graph.rdfs:comment: These are the parsable data files provided by CATH.
@graph.rdfs:label: Raw CATH domain classification format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Format of summary of domain classification information for a CATH domain.
@graph.rdfs:comment: The report (for example http://www.cathdb.info/domain/1cukA01) includes CATH codes for levels in the hierarchy for the domain, level descriptions and relevant data and links.
@graph.rdfs:label: CATH domain report format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Systems Biology Result Markup Language (SBRML), the standard XML format for simulated or calculated results (e.g. trajectories) of systems biology models.
@graph.rdfs:label: SBRML

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: BioPAX is an exchange format for pathway data, with its data model defined in OWL.
@graph.rdfs:label: BioPAX

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: EBI Application Result XML is a format returned by sequence similarity search Web services at EBI.
@graph.rdfs:label: EBI Application Result XML

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: XML Molecular Interaction Format (MIF), standardised by HUPO PSI MI.
MIF
@graph.rdfs:label: PSI MI XML (MIF)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: phyloXML is a standardised XML format for phylogenetic trees, networks, and associated data.
@graph.rdfs:label: phyloXML

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: NeXML is a standardised XML format for rich phyloinformatic data.
@graph.rdfs:label: NeXML

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: MAGE-ML XML format for microarray expression data, standardised by MGED (now FGED).
@graph.rdfs:label: MAGE-ML

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: MAGE-TAB textual format for microarray expression data, standardised by MGED (now FGED).
@graph.rdfs:label: MAGE-TAB

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: GCDML XML format for genome and metagenome metadata according to MIGS/MIMS/MIMARKS information standards, standardised by the Genomic Standards Consortium (GSC).
@graph.rdfs:label: GCDML

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: 'GTrack' belongs to the 'BioXSD|GTrack' ecosystem of generic formats, and particular to its subset, the 'GTrack ecosystem' (GTrack, GSuite, BTrack). 'GTrack' is the tabular format for representing features of sequences and genomes.
GTrack ecosystem of formats

GTrack is a generic and optimised tabular format for genome or sequence feature tracks. GTrack unifies the power of other track formats (e.g. GFF3, BED, WIG), and while optimised in size, adds more flexibility, customisation, and automation ("machine understandability").
@graph.rdfs:label: GTrack

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Data format for a report of information derived from a biological pathway or network.
@graph.rdfs:label: Biological pathway or network report format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Data format for annotation on a laboratory experiment.
@graph.rdfs:label: Experiment annotation format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Cytoband format for chromosome cytobands.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Reflects a UCSC Browser DB table.
@graph.rdfs:label: Cytoband format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: CopasiML, the native format of COPASI.
@graph.rdfs:label: CopasiML

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: CellML, the format for mathematical models of biological and other networks.
@graph.rdfs:label: CellML

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Tabular Molecular Interaction format (MITAB), standardised by HUPO PSI MI.
@graph.rdfs:label: PSI MI TAB (MITAB)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Protein affinity format (PSI-PAR), standardised by HUPO PSI MI. It is compatible with PSI MI XML (MIF) and uses the same XML Schema.
@graph.rdfs:label: PSI-PAR

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: mzML format for raw spectrometer output data, standardised by HUPO PSI MSS.
@graph.rdfs:comment: mzML is the successor and unifier of the mzData format developed by PSI and mzXML developed at the Seattle Proteome Center.
@graph.rdfs:label: mzML

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Format for mass pectra and derived data, include peptide sequences etc.
@graph.rdfs:label: Mass spectrometry data format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: TraML (Transition Markup Language) is the format for mass spectrometry transitions, standardised by HUPO PSI MSS.
@graph.rdfs:label: TraML

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: mzIdentML is the exchange format for peptides and proteins identified from mass spectra, standardised by HUPO PSI PI. It can be used for outputs of proteomics search engines.
@graph.rdfs:label: mzIdentML

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: mzQuantML is the format for quantitation values associated with peptides, proteins and small molecules from mass spectra, standardised by HUPO PSI PI. It can be used for outputs of quantitation software for proteomics.
@graph.rdfs:label: mzQuantML

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: GelML is the format for describing the process of gel electrophoresis, standardised by HUPO PSI PS.
@graph.rdfs:label: GelML

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: spML is the format for describing proteomics sample processing, other than using gels, prior to mass spectrometric protein identification, standardised by HUPO PSI PS. It may also be applicable for metabolomics.
@graph.rdfs:label: spML

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A human-readable encoding for the Web Ontology Language (OWL).
@graph.rdfs:label: OWL Functional Syntax

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A syntax for writing OWL class expressions.
@graph.rdfs:comment: This format was influenced by the OWL Abstract Syntax and the DL style syntax.
@graph.rdfs:label: Manchester OWL Syntax

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A superset of the "Description-Logic Knowledge Representation System Specification from the KRSS Group of the ARPA Knowledge Sharing Effort".
@graph.rdfs:comment: This format is used in Protege 4.
@graph.rdfs:label: KRSS2 Syntax

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The Terse RDF Triple Language (Turtle) is a human-friendly serialisation format for RDF (Resource Description Framework) graphs.
@graph.rdfs:comment: The SPARQL Query Language incorporates a very similar syntax.
@graph.rdfs:label: Turtle

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A plain text serialisation format for RDF (Resource Description Framework) graphs, and a subset of the Turtle (Terse RDF Triple Language) format.
@graph.rdfs:comment: N-Triples should not be confused with Notation 3 which is a superset of Turtle.
@graph.rdfs:label: N-Triples

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A shorthand non-XML serialisation of Resource Description Framework model, designed with human-readability in mind.
N3
@graph.rdfs:label: Notation3

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Resource Description Framework (RDF) XML format.
@graph.rdfs:comment: RDF/XML is a serialisation syntax for OWL DL, but not for OWL Full.
@graph.rdfs:label: RDF/XML

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: OWL ontology XML serialisation format.
OWL
@graph.rdfs:label: OWL/XML

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The A2M format is used as the primary format for multiple alignments of protein or nucleic-acid sequences in the SAM suite of tools. It is a small modification of FASTA format for sequences and is compatible with most tools that read FASTA.
@graph.rdfs:label: A2M

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Standard flowgram format (SFF) is a binary file format used to encode results of pyrosequencing from the 454 Life Sciences platform for high-throughput sequencing.
Standard flowgram format
@graph.rdfs:label: SFF

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The MAP file describes SNPs and is used by the Plink package.
Plink MAP
@graph.rdfs:label: MAP

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The PED file describes individuals and genetic data and is used by the Plink package.
Plink PED
@graph.rdfs:label: PED

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Data format for a metadata on an individual and their genetic data.
@graph.rdfs:label: Individual genetic data format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The PED/MAP file describes data used by the Plink package.
Plink PED/MAP
@graph.rdfs:label: PED/MAP

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: File format of a CT (Connectivity Table) file from the RNAstructure package.
@graph.rdfs:label: CT

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: XRNA old input style format.
@graph.rdfs:label: SS

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: RNA Markup Language.
@graph.rdfs:label: RNAML

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Format for the Genetic Data Environment (GDE).
@graph.rdfs:label: GDE

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A multiple alignment in vertical format, as used in the AMPS (Alignment of Multiple Protein Sequences) pacakge.
Block file format
@graph.rdfs:label: BLC

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Format of a data index of some type.
@graph.rdfs:label: Data index format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: BAM indexing format
@graph.rdfs:label: BAI

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: HMMER profile HMM file for HMMER versions 2.x
@graph.rdfs:label: HMMER2

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: HMMER profile HMM file for HMMER versions 3.x
@graph.rdfs:label: HMMER3

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: EMBOSS simple sequence pair alignment format.
@graph.rdfs:label: PO

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: XML format as produced by the NCBI Blast package
@graph.rdfs:label: BLAST XML results format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: http://www.ebi.ac.uk/ena/software/cram-usage#format_specification http://samtools.github.io/hts-specs/CRAMv2.1.pdf
Reference-based compression of alignment format
@graph.rdfs:label: CRAM

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: JavaScript Object Notation format; a lightweight, text-based format to represent tree-structured data using key-value pairs.
JavaScript Object Notation
@graph.rdfs:label: JSON

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Encapsulated PostScript format
@graph.rdfs:label: EPS

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Graphics Interchange Format.
@graph.rdfs:label: GIF

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Microsoft Excel spreadsheet format.
Microsoft Excel format
@graph.rdfs:label: xls

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Tabular data represented as tab-separated values in a text file.
@graph.rdfs:label: TSV

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Format of a file of gene expression data, e.g. a gene expression matrix or profile.
@graph.rdfs:label: Gene expression data format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Format of the cytoscape input file of gene expression ratios or values are specified over one or more experiments.
@graph.rdfs:label: Cytoscape input file format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Bowtie format for indexed reference genome for "small" genomes.
Bowtie index format
@graph.rdfs:label: ebwt

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Rich sequence format.
GCG RSF
@graph.rdfs:comment: RSF-format files contain one or more sequences that may or may not be related. In addition to the sequence data, each sequence can be annotated with descriptive sequence information (from the GCG manual).
@graph.rdfs:label: RSF

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Some format based on the GCG format.
@graph.rdfs:label: GCG format variant

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Bioinformatics Sequence Markup Language format.
@graph.rdfs:label: BSML

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Bowtie format for indexed reference genome for "large" genomes.
Bowtie long index format
@graph.rdfs:label: ebwtl

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Ensembl standard format for variation data.
@graph.rdfs:label: Ensembl variation file format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Microsoft Word format.
@graph.rdfs:label: docx

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Format of documents including word processor, spreadsheet and presentation.
@graph.rdfs:label: Document format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Portable Document Format
@graph.rdfs:label: PDF

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Format used for images and image metadata.
@graph.rdfs:label: Image format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Medical image format corresponding to the Digital Imaging and Communications in Medicine (DICOM) standard.
@graph.rdfs:label: DICOM format

NIfTI-1 format
@graph.rdfs:label: nii

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Text-based tagged file format for medical images generated using the MetaImage software package.
Metalmage format
@graph.rdfs:label: mhd

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: File format used for scripts for the Statistical Package for the Social Sciences.

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: MHTML is not strictly an HTML format, it is encoded as an HTML email message (although with multipart/related instead of multipart/alternative). It, however, contains the main HTML block as its core, and thus it is for practical reasons incuded in EDAM as a specialisation of 'HTML'.
MIME  HTML format for Web pages, which can include external resources, including images, Flash animations and so on.
@graph.rdfs:label: MHTML

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Proprietary file format for (raw) BeadArray data used by genomewide profiling platforms from Illumina Inc. This format is output directly from the scanner and stores summary intensities for each probe-type on an array.

@graph.rdfs:comment: This file format is for machine learning.
@graph.rdfs:label: arff

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: AFG is a single text-based file assembly format  that holds read and consensus information together
@graph.rdfs:label: afg

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The bedGraph format allows display of continuous-valued data in track format. This display type is useful for probability scores and transcriptome data
@graph.rdfs:comment: Holds a tab-delimited chromosome /start /end / datavalue dataset.
@graph.rdfs:label: bedgraph

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Browser Extensible Data (BED) format of sequence annotation track that strictly does not contain non-standard fields beyond the first 3 columns.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Galaxy allows BED files to contain non-standard fields beyond the first 3 columns, some other implementations do not.
@graph.rdfs:label: bedstrict

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: BED file format where each feature is described by chromosome, start, end, name, score, and strand.

@graph.rdfs:label: bed6

@graph.rdfs:comment: Galaxy allows BED files to contain non-standard fields beyond the first 3 columns, some other implementations do not.

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Custom Sequence annotation track format used by Galaxy.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Used for tracks/track views within galaxy.
@graph.rdfs:label: customtrack

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Color space FASTA format sequence variant.
@graph.rdfs:comment: FASTA format extended for color space information.
@graph.rdfs:label: csfasta

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: HDF5 is a data model, library, and file format for storing and managing data, based on Hierarchical Data Format (HDF).
h5
rdfs:comment: An HDF5 file appears to the user as a directed graph. The nodes of this graph are the higher-level HDF5 objects that are exposed by the HDF5 APIs: Groups, Datasets, Named datatypes. Currently supported by the Python MDTraj package.
HDF5 is the new version, according to the HDF group, a completely different technology (https://support.hdfgroup.org/products/hdf4/ compared to HDF.
@graph.rdfs:label: HDF5

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A versatile bitmap format.
tiff
@graph.rdfs:comment: The TIFF format is perhaps the most versatile and diverse bitmap format in existence. Its extensible nature and support for numerous data compression schemes allow developers to customize the TIFF format to fit any peculiar data storage needs.
@graph.rdfs:label: TIFF

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Standard bitmap storage format in the Microsoft Windows environment.
bmp
@graph.rdfs:comment: Although it is based on Windows internal bitmap data structures, it is supported by many non-Windows and non-PC applications.
@graph.rdfs:label: BMP

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: IM is a format used by LabEye and other applications based on the IFUNC image processing library.
@graph.rdfs:comment: IFUNC library reads and writes most uncompressed interchange versions of this format.
@graph.rdfs:label: im

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Photo CD format, which is the highest resolution format for images on a CD.
@graph.rdfs:comment: PCD was developed by Kodak. A PCD file contains five different resolution (ranging from low to high) of a slide or film negative. Due to it PCD is often used by many photographers and graphics professionals for high-end printed applications.
@graph.rdfs:label: pcd

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: PCX is an image file format that uses a simple form of run-length encoding. It is lossless.
@graph.rdfs:label: pcx

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The PPM format is a lowest common denominator color image file format.
@graph.rdfs:label: ppm

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: PSD (Photoshop Document) is a proprietary file that allows the user to work with the imagesâ individual layers even after the file has been saved.
@graph.rdfs:label: psd

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: X BitMap is a plain text binary image format used by the X Window System used for storing cursor and icon bitmaps used in the X GUI.
@graph.rdfs:comment: The XBM format was replaced by XPM for X11 in 1989.
