@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: X PixMap (XPM) is an image file format used by the X Window System, it is intended primarily for creating icon pixmaps, and supports transparent pixels.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Sequence of segments with markers. Begins with byte of 0xFF and follows by marker type.
@graph.rdfs:label: xpm

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: RGB file format is the native raster graphics file format for Silicon Graphics workstations.
@graph.rdfs:label: rgb

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The PBM format is a lowest common denominator monochrome file format. It serves as the common language of a large family of bitmap image conversion filters.
@graph.rdfs:label: pbm

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The PGM format is a lowest common denominator grayscale file format.
@graph.rdfs:comment: It is designed to be extremely easy to learn and write programs for.
@graph.rdfs:label: pgm

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: PNG is a file format for image compression.
@graph.rdfs:comment: It iis expected to replace the Graphics Interchange Format (GIF).
@graph.rdfs:label: PNG

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Scalable Vector Graphics (SVG) is an XML-based vector image format for two-dimensional graphics with support for interactivity and animation.
Scalable Vector Graphics
@graph.rdfs:comment: The SVG specification is an open standard developed by the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) since 1999.
@graph.rdfs:label: SVG

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Sun Raster is a raster graphics file format used on SunOS by Sun Microsystems
@graph.rdfs:comment: The SVG specification is an open standard developed by the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) since 1999.
@graph.rdfs:label: rast

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Textual report format for sequence quality for reports from sequencing machines.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence quality report format (text)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: FASTQ format subset for Phred sequencing quality score data only (no sequences).
@graph.rdfs:comment: Phred quality scores  are defined as a property which is logarithmically related to the base-calling error probabilities.
@graph.rdfs:label: qual

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: FASTQ format subset for Phred sequencing quality score data only (no sequences) for Solexa/Illumina 1.0 format.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Solexa/Illumina 1.0 format can encode a Solexa/Illumina quality score from -5 to 62 using ASCII 59 to 126 (although in raw read data Solexa scores from -5 to 40 only are expected)
@graph.rdfs:label: qualsolexa

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: FASTQ format subset for Phred sequencing quality score data only (no sequences) from Illumina 1.5 and before Illumina 1.8.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Starting in Illumina 1.5 and before Illumina 1.8, the Phred scores 0 to 2 have a slightly different meaning. The values 0 and 1 are no longer used and the value 2, encoded by ASCII 66 "B", is used also at the end of reads as a Read Segment Quality Control Indicator.
@graph.rdfs:label: qualillumina

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: FASTQ format subset for Phred sequencing quality score data only (no sequences) for SOLiD data.
@graph.rdfs:comment: For SOLiD data, the sequence is in color space, except the first position. The quality values are those of the Sanger format.
@graph.rdfs:label: qualsolid

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: FASTQ format subset for Phred sequencing quality score data only (no sequences) from 454 sequencers.
@graph.rdfs:label: qual454

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Human ENCODE peak format.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Format that covers both the broad peak format and narrow peak format from ENCODE.
@graph.rdfs:label: ENCODE peak format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Human ENCODE narrow peak format.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Format that covers both the broad peak format and narrow peak format from ENCODE.
@graph.rdfs:label: ENCODE narrow peak format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Human ENCODE broad peak format.
@graph.rdfs:label: ENCODE broad peak format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Blocked GNU Zip format.
@graph.rdfs:comment: BAM files are compressed using a variant of GZIP (GNU ZIP), into a format called BGZF (Blocked GNU Zip Format).
@graph.rdfs:label: bgzip

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: TAB-delimited genome position file index format.
@graph.rdfs:label: tabix

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Data format for graph data.
@graph.rdfs:label: Graph format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: XML-based format used to store graph descriptions within Galaxy.
@graph.rdfs:label: xgmml

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: SIF (simple interaction file) Format - a network/pathway format used for instance in cytoscape.
@graph.rdfs:label: sif

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: MS Excel spreadsheet format consisting of a set of XML documents stored in a ZIP-compressed file.
@graph.rdfs:label: xlsx

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Data format used by the SQLite database.
@graph.rdfs:label: SQLite format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Data format used by the SQLite database conformant to the Gemini schema.
@graph.rdfs:label: Gemini SQLite format

@graph.http://edamontology.org/deprecation_comm: Duplicate of http://edamontology.org/format_3326
@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Format of a data index of some type.
@graph.rdfs:label: Index format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An index of a genome database, indexed for use by the snpeff tool.
@graph.rdfs:label: snpeffdb

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Binary format used by MATLAB files to store workspace variables.
@graph.rdfs:label: MAT

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Network Common Data Form (NetCDF) library is supported by AMBER MD package from version 9.

Format used by netCDF software  library for writing and reading chromatography-MS data files.  Also used to store trajectory atom coordinates information, such as the ones obtained by Molecular Dynamics simulations.
ANDI-MS
@graph.rdfs:label: netCDF

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Mascot Generic Format.  Encodes multiple MS/MS spectra in a single file.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Files includes *m*/*z*, intensity pairs separated by headers; headers can contain a bit more information, including search engine instructions.
@graph.rdfs:label: MGF

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Spectral data format file where each spectrum is written to a separate file.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Each file contains one header line for the known or assumed charge and the mass of the precursor peptide ion, calculated from the measured *m*/*z* and the charge. This one line was then followed by all the *m*/*z*, intensity pairs that represent the spectrum.
@graph.rdfs:label: dta

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Spectral data file similar to dta.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Differ from .dta only in subtleties of the header line format and content and support the added feature of being able to.
@graph.rdfs:label: pkl

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Common file format for proteomics mass spectrometric data developed at the Seattle Proteome Center/Institute for Systems Biology.
@graph.rdfs:label: mzXML

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Open data format for the storage, exchange, and processing of peptide sequence assignments of MS/MS scans, intended to provide a common data output format for many different MS/MS search engines and subsequent peptide-level analyses.
@graph.rdfs:label: pepXML

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Graphical Pathway Markup Language (GPML) is an XML format used for exchanging biological pathways.
@graph.rdfs:label: GPML

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A list of k-mers and their occurences in a dataset. Can also be used as an implicit De Bruijn graph.
@graph.rdfs:label: K-mer countgraph

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: mzTab is a tab-delimited format for mass spectrometry-based proteomics and metabolomics results.
@graph.rdfs:label: mzTab

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: imzML metadata is a data format for mass spectrometry imaging metadata.
@graph.rdfs:comment: imzML data are recorded in 2 files: '.imzXML' is a metadata XML file based on mzML by HUPO-PSI, and '.ibd' is a binary file containing the mass spectra. This entry is for the metadata XML file
@graph.rdfs:label: imzML metadata file

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: qcML is an XML format for quality-related data of mass spectrometry and other high-throughput measurements.
@graph.rdfs:comment: The focus of qcML is towards mass spectrometry based proteomics, but the format is suitable for metabolomics and sequencing as well.
@graph.rdfs:label: qcML

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: PRIDE XML is an XML format for mass spectra, peptide and protein identifications, and metadata about a corresponding measurement, sample, experiment.
@graph.rdfs:label: PRIDE XML

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Simulation Experiment Description Markup Language (SED-ML) is an XML format for encoding simulation setups, according to the MIASE (Minimum Information About a Simulation Experiment) requirements.
@graph.rdfs:label: SED-ML

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Open Modeling EXchange format (OMEX) is a ZIPped format for encapsulating all information necessary for a modeling and simulation project in systems biology.
@graph.rdfs:comment: An OMEX file is a ZIP container that includes a manifest file, listing the content of the archive, an optional metadata file adding information about the archive and its content, and the files describing the model. OMEX is one of the standardised formats within COMBINE (Computational Modeling in Biology Network).
@graph.rdfs:label: COMBINE OMEX

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI:
The Investigation / Study / Assay (ISA) tab-delimited (TAB) format incorporates metadata from 
experiments employing a combination of technologies.
@graph.rdfs:comment: ISA-TAB is based on MAGE-TAB. Other than tabular, the ISA model can also be represented in RDF, and in JSON (compliable with a set of defined JSON Schemata).
@graph.rdfs:label: ISA-TAB

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: SBtab is a tabular format for biochemical network models.
@graph.rdfs:label: SBtab

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Biological Connection Markup Language (BCML) is an XML format for biological pathways.
@graph.rdfs:label: BCML

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Biological Dynamics Markup Language (BDML) is an XML format for quantitative data describing biological dynamics.
@graph.rdfs:label: BDML

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Biological Expression Language (BEL) is a textual format for representing scientific findings in life sciences in a computable form.
@graph.rdfs:label: BEL

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: SBGN-ML is an XML format for Systems Biology Graphical Notation (SBGN) diagrams of biological pathways or networks.
@graph.rdfs:label: SBGN-ML

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: AGP is a tabular format for a sequence assembly (a contig, a scaffold/supercontig, or a chromosome).
@graph.rdfs:label: AGP

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: PostScript format
PostScript
@graph.rdfs:label: PS

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: SRA archive format (SRA) is the archive format used for input to the NCBI Sequence Read Archive.
@graph.rdfs:label: SRA format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: VDB ('vertical database') is the native format used for export from the NCBI Sequence Read Archive.
SRA native format
@graph.rdfs:label: VDB

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Index file format used by the samtools package to index TAB-delimited genome position files.
@graph.rdfs:label: Tabix index file format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A five-column, tab-delimited table of feature locations and qualifiers for importing annotation into an existing Sequin submission (an NCBI tool for submitting and updating GenBank entries).
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequin format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Proprietary mass-spectrometry format of Thermo Scientific's ProteomeDiscoverer software.
Magellan storage file format
@graph.rdfs:comment: This format corresponds to an SQLite database, and you can look into the files with e.g. SQLiteStudio3. There are also some readers (http://doi.org/10.1021/pr2005154) and converters (http://doi.org/10.1016/j.jprot.2015.06.015) for this format available, which re-engineered the database schema, but there is no official DB schema specification of Thermo Scientific for the format.
@graph.rdfs:label: MSF

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Data format for biodiversity data.
@graph.rdfs:label: Biodiversity data format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Exchange format of the Access to Biological Collections Data (ABCD) Schema; a standard for the access to and exchange of data about specimens and observations (primary biodiversity data).
ABCD
@graph.rdfs:label: ABCD format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Tab-delimited text files of GenePattern that contain a column for each sample, a row for each gene, and an expression value for each gene in each sample.
@graph.rdfs:label: GCT/Res format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Mass spectrum file format from QSTAR and QTRAP instruments (ABI/Sciex).
wiff
@graph.rdfs:label: WIFF format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Output format used by X! series search engines that is based on the XML language BIOML.
@graph.rdfs:label: X!Tandem XML

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Proprietary file format for mass spectrometry data from Thermo Scientific.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Proprietary format for which documentation is not available.
@graph.rdfs:label: Thermo RAW

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: "Raw" result file from Mascot database search.
@graph.rdfs:label: Mascot .dat file

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Format of peak list files from Andromeda search engine (MaxQuant) that consist of arbitrarily many spectra.
MaxQuant APL
@graph.rdfs:label: MaxQuant APL peaklist format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Synthetic Biology Open Language (SBOL) is an XML format for the specification and exchange of biological design information in synthetic biology.
@graph.rdfs:comment: SBOL introduces a standardised format for the electronic exchange of information on the structural and functional aspects of biological designs.
@graph.rdfs:label: SBOL

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: PMML uses XML to represent mining models. The structure of the models is described by an XML Schema.
@graph.rdfs:comment: One or more mining models can be contained in a PMML document.
@graph.rdfs:label: PMML

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Image file format used by the Open Microscopy Environment (OME).
rdfs:comment: An OME-TIFF dataset consists of one or more files in standard TIFF or BigTIFF format, with the file extension .ome.tif or .ome.tiff, and an identical (or in the case of multiple files, nearly identical) string of OME-XML metadata embedded in the ImageDescription tag of each fileâs first IFD (Image File Directory). BigTIFF file extensions are also permitted, with the file extension .ome.tf2, .ome.tf8 or .ome.btf, but note these file extensions are an addition to the original specification, and software using an older version of the specification may not be able to handle these file extensions.

OME develops open-source software and data format standards for the storage and manipulation of biological microscopy data. It is a joint project between universities, research establishments, industry and the software development community.
@graph.rdfs:label: OME-TIFF

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The LocARNA PP format combines sequence or alignment information and (respectively, single or consensus) ensemble probabilities into an PP 2.0 record.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Format for multiple aligned or single sequences together with the probabilistic description of the (consensus) RNA secondary structure ensemble by probabilities of base pairs, base pair stackings, and base pairs and unpaired bases in the loop of base pairs.
@graph.rdfs:label: LocARNA PP

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Input format used by the Database of Genotypes and Phenotypes (dbGaP).
@graph.rdfs:comment: The Database of Genotypes and Phenotypes (dbGaP) is a National Institutes of Health (NIH) sponsored repository charged to archive, curate and distribute information produced by studies investigating the interaction of genotype and phenotype.
@graph.rdfs:label: dbGaP format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The BIological Observation Matrix (BIOM) is a format for representing biological sample by observation contingency tables in broad areas of comparative omics. The primary use of this format is to represent OTU tables and metagenome tables.
BIological Observation Matrix format
@graph.rdfs:comment: BIOM is a recognised standard for the Earth Microbiome Project, and is a project supported by Genomics Standards Consortium. Supported in QIIME, Mothur, MEGAN, etc.
@graph.rdfs:label: BIOM format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A format for storage, exchange, and processing of protein identifications created from ms/ms-derived peptide sequence data.
@graph.rdfs:comment: No human-consumable information about this format is available (see http://tools.proteomecenter.org/wiki/index.php?title=Formats:protXML).
@graph.rdfs:label: protXML

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A linked data format enables publishing structured data as linked data (Linked Data), so that the data can be interlinked and become more useful through semantic queries.
Semantic Web format
@graph.rdfs:label: Linked data format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: JSON-LD, or JavaScript Object Notation for Linked Data, is a method of encoding Linked Data using JSON.
JavaScript Object Notation for Linked Data
@graph.rdfs:label: JSON-LD

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: YAML (YAML Ain't Markup Language) is a human-readable tree-structured data serialisation language.
YAML Ain't Markup Language
rdfs:comment: Data in YAML format can be serialised into text, or binary format.
YAML version 1.2 is a superset of JSON; prior versions were "not strictly compatible".
@graph.rdfs:label: YAML

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Tabular format
Tabular data represented as values in a text file delimited by some character.
Delimiter-separated values
@graph.rdfs:label: DSV

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Tabular data represented as comma-separated values in a text file.
Comma-separated values
@graph.rdfs:label: CSV

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: "Raw" result file from SEQUEST database search.
@graph.rdfs:label: SEQUEST .out file

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: XML file format for files containing information about peptide identifications from mass spectrometry data analysis carried out with OpenMS.
@graph.rdfs:label: idXML

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Data table formatted such that it can be passed/streamed within the KNIME platform.
@graph.rdfs:label: KNIME datatable format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: UniProtKB XML sequence features format is an XML format available for downloading UniProt entries.
@graph.rdfs:label: UniProtKB XML

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: UniProtKB RDF sequence features format is an RDF format available for downloading UniProt entries (in RDF/XML).
@graph.rdfs:label: UniProtKB RDF

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Work in progress. 'BioXSD' belongs to the 'BioXSD|GTrack' ecosystem of generic formats. 'BioJSON' is the JSON format based on the common, unified 'BioXSD data model', a.k.a. 'BioXSD|BioJSON|BioYAML'.

BioJSON is a BioXSD-schema-based JSON format of sequence-based data and some other common data - sequence records, alignments, feature records, references to resources, and more - optimised for integrative bioinformatics, web applications and APIs, and object-oriented programming.
@graph.rdfs:label: BioJSON (BioXSD)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Work in progress. 'BioXSD' belongs to the 'BioXSD|GTrack' ecosystem of generic formats. 'BioYAML' is the YAML format based on the common, unified 'BioXSD data model', a.k.a. 'BioXSD|BioJSON|BioYAML'.

BioYAML is a BioXSD-schema-based YAML format of sequence-based data and some other common data - sequence records, alignments, feature records, references to resources, and more - optimised for integrative bioinformatics, web APIs, human readability and editting, and object-oriented programming.
@graph.rdfs:label: BioYAML

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: BioJSON is a JSON format of single multiple sequence alignments, with their annotations, features, and custom visualisation and application settings for the Jalview workbench.
@graph.rdfs:label: BioJSON (Jalview)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: 'GSuite' belongs to the 'BioXSD|GTrack' ecosystem of generic formats, and particular to its subset, the 'GTrack ecosystem' (GTrack, GSuite, BTrack). 'GSuite' is the tabular format for an annotated collection of individual GTrack files.

GSuite is a tabular format for collections of genome or sequence feature tracks, suitable for integrative multi-track analysis. GSuite contains links to genome/sequence tracks, with additional metadata.
@graph.rdfs:label: GSuite

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: 'BTrack' belongs to the 'BioXSD|GTrack' ecosystem of generic formats, and particular to its subset, the 'GTrack ecosystem' (GTrack, GSuite, BTrack). 'BTrack' is the binary, optionally compressed HDF5-based version of the GTrack and GSuite formats.

BTrack is an HDF5-based binary format for genome or sequence feature tracks and their collections, suitable for integrative multi-track analysis. BTrack is a binary, compressed alternative to the GTrack and GSuite formats.
@graph.rdfs:label: BTrack

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Multi-Crop Passport Descriptors is a format available in 2 successive versions, V.1 (FAO/IPGRI 2001) and V.2 (FAO/Bioversity 2012).
The FAO/Bioversity/IPGRI Multi-Crop Passport Descriptors (MCPD) is an international standard format for exchange of germplasm information.
@graph.rdfs:label: MCPD

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Data format of an annotated text, e.g. with recognised entities, concepts, and relations.
@graph.rdfs:label: Annotated text format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: JSON format of annotated scientific text used by PubAnnotations and other tools.
@graph.rdfs:label: PubAnnotation format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: BioC is a standardised XML format for sharing and integrating text data and annotations.
@graph.rdfs:label: BioC

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Native textual export format of annotated scientific text from PubTator.
@graph.rdfs:label: PubTator format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A format of text annotation using the linked-data Open Annotation Data Model, serialised typically in RDF or JSON-LD.
@graph.rdfs:label: Open Annotation format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A family of similar formats of text annotation, used by BRAT and other tools, known as BioNLP Shared Task format (BioNLP 2009 Shared Task on Event Extraction, BioNLP Shared Task 2011, BioNLP Shared Task 2013), BRAT format, BRAT standoff format, and similar.
@graph.rdfs:label: BioNLP Shared Task format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A query language (format) for structured database queries.
Query format
@graph.rdfs:label: Query language

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: SQL (Structured Query Language) is the de-facto standard query language (format of queries) for querying and manipulating data in relational databases.
Structured Query Language
@graph.rdfs:label: SQL

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: XQuery (XML Query) is a query language (format of queries) for querying and manipulating structured and unstructured data, usually in the form of XML, text, and with vendor-specific extensions for other data formats (JSON, binary, etc.).
XML Query
@graph.rdfs:label: XQuery

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: SPARQL (SPARQL Protocol and RDF Query Language) is a semantic query language for querying and manipulating data stored in Resource Description Framework (RDF) format.
SPARQL Protocol and RDF Query Language
@graph.rdfs:label: SPARQL

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: XML format for XML Schema.
@graph.rdfs:label: xsd

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The A2M format is used as the primary format for multiple alignments of protein or nucleic-acid sequences in the SAM suite of tools. It is a small modification of FASTA format for sequences and is compatible with most tools that read FASTA.
@graph.rdfs:label: XMFA

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The GEN file format contains genetic data and describes SNPs.
Genotype file format
@graph.rdfs:label: GEN

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The SAMPLE file format contains information about each individual i.e. individual IDs, covariates, phenotypes and missing data proportions, from a GWAS study.
@graph.rdfs:label: SAMPLE file format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: SDF is one of a family of chemical-data file formats developed by MDL Information Systems; it is intended especially for structural information.
@graph.rdfs:label: SDF

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An MDL Molfile is a file format for holding information about the atoms, bonds, connectivity and coordinates of a molecule.
@graph.rdfs:label: Molfile

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Complete, portable representation of a SYBYL molecule. ASCII file which contains all the information needed to reconstruct a SYBYL molecule.
@graph.rdfs:label: Mol2

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: format for the LaTeX document preparation system
LaTeX format
@graph.rdfs:comment: uses the TeX typesetting program format
@graph.rdfs:label: latex

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Tab-delimited text file format used by Eland - the read-mapping program distributed by Illumina with its sequencing analysis pipeline - which maps short Solexa sequence reads to the human reference genome.
@graph.rdfs:label: ELAND format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Phylip multiple alignment sequence format, less stringent than PHYLIP format.
PHYLIP Interleaved format
@graph.rdfs:comment: It differs from Phylip Format (format_1997) on length of the ID sequence. There no length restrictions on the ID, but whitespaces aren't allowed in the sequence ID/Name because one space separates the longest ID and the beginning of the sequence. Sequences IDs must be padded to the longest ID length.

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Phylip multiple alignment sequence format, less stringent than PHYLIP sequential format (format_1998).
@graph.rdfs:comment: It differs from Phylip sequential format (format_1997) on length of the ID sequence. There no length restrictions on the ID, but whitespaces aren't allowed in the sequence ID/Name because one space separates the longest ID and the beginning of the sequence. Sequences IDs must be padded to the longest ID length.
@graph.rdfs:label: Relaxed PHYLIP Sequential

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Default XML format of VisANT, containing all the network information.
@graph.rdfs:label: VisML

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: GML (Graph Modeling Language) is a text file format supporting network data with a very easy syntax. It is used by Graphlet, Pajek, yEd, LEDA and NetworkX.
GML format
@graph.rdfs:label: GML

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: FASTG is a format for faithfully representing genome assemblies in the face of allelic polymorphism and assembly uncertainty.
FASTG assembly graph format
@graph.rdfs:comment: It is called FASTG, like FASTA, but the G stands for âgraphâ.
@graph.rdfs:label: FASTG

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Data format for raw data from a nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) spectroscopy experiment.
Nuclear magnetic resonance spectroscopy data format
@graph.rdfs:label: NMR data format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: nmrML is an MSI supported XML-based open access format for metabolomics NMR raw and processed spectral data. It is accompanies by an nmrCV (controlled vocabulary) to allow ontology-based annotations.
@graph.rdfs:label: nmrML

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: . proBAM is an adaptation of BAM (format_2572), which was extended to meet specific requirements entailed by proteomics data.
@graph.rdfs:label: proBAM

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: . proBED is an adaptation of BED (format_3003), which was extended to meet specific requirements entailed by proteomics data.
@graph.rdfs:label: proBED

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Data format for raw microarray data.
Microarray data format
@graph.rdfs:label: Raw microarray data format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: GenePix Results (GPR) text file format developed by Axon Instruments that is used to save GenePix Results data.
@graph.rdfs:label: GPR

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Binary format used by the ARB software suite
ARB binary format
@graph.rdfs:label: ARB

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: OpenMS format for grouping features in one map or across several maps.
@graph.rdfs:label: consensusXML

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: OpenMS format for quantitation results (LC/MS features).
@graph.rdfs:label: featureXML

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Now deprecated data format of the HUPO Proteomics Standards Initiative.  Replaced by mzML (format_3244).
@graph.rdfs:label: mzData

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Format supported by the Tide tool for identifying peptides from tandem mass spectra.
@graph.rdfs:label: TIDE TXT

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: XML format as produced by the NCBI Blast package v2.
@graph.rdfs:label: BLAST XML v2 results format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Microsoft Powerpoint format.
@graph.rdfs:label: pptx

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: ibd is a data format for mass spectrometry imaging data.
@graph.rdfs:comment: imzML data is recorded in 2 files: '.imzXML' is a metadata XML file based on mzML by HUPO-PSI, and '.ibd' is a binary file containing the mass spectra.
@graph.rdfs:label: ibd

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Data format used in Natural Language Processing.
Natural Language Processing format
@graph.rdfs:label: NLP format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: XML input file format for BEAST Software (Bayesian Evolutionary Analysis Sampling Trees).
@graph.rdfs:label: BEAST

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Chado-XML format is a direct mapping of the Chado relational schema into XML.
@graph.rdfs:label: Chado-XML

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An alignment format generated by PRANK/PRANKSTER consisting of four elements: newick, nodes, selection and model.
@graph.rdfs:label: HSAML

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Output xml file from the InterProScan sequence analysis application.
@graph.rdfs:label: InterProScan XML

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The KEGG Markup Language (KGML) is an exchange format of the KEGG pathway maps, which is converted from internally used KGML+ (KGML+SVG) format.
KEGG Markup Language
@graph.rdfs:label: KGML

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: XML format for collected entries from biobliographic databases MEDLINE and PubMed.
MEDLINE XML
@graph.rdfs:label: PubMed XML

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A set of XML compliant markup components for describing multiple sequence alignments.
@graph.rdfs:label: MSAML

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: OrthoXML is designed broadly to allow the storage and comparison of orthology data from any ortholog database. It establishes a structure for describing orthology relationships while still allowing flexibility for database-specific information to be encapsulated in the same format.
@graph.rdfs:label: OrthoXML

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Tree structure of Protein Sequence Database Markup Language generated using Matra software.
@graph.rdfs:label: PSDML

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: SeqXML is an XML Schema to describe biological sequences, developed by the Stockholm Bioinformatics Centre.
@graph.rdfs:label: SeqXML

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: XML format for the UniParc database.
@graph.rdfs:label: UniParc XML

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: XML format for the UniRef reference clusters.
@graph.rdfs:label: UniRef XML

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Common Workflow Language (CWL) format for description of command-line tools and workflows.
@graph.rdfs:label: CWL

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Proprietary file format for mass spectrometry data from Waters.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Proprietary format for which documentation is not available, but used by multiple tools.
@graph.rdfs:label: Waters RAW

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A standardized file format for data exchange in mass spectrometry, initially developed for infrared spectrometry.
@graph.rdfs:comment: JCAMP-DX is an ASCII based format and therefore not very compact even though it includes standards for file compression.
@graph.rdfs:label: JCAMP-DX

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An NLP format used for annotated textual documents.
@graph.rdfs:label: NLP annotation format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: NLP format used by a specific type of corpus (collection of texts).
@graph.rdfs:label: NLP corpus format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: mirGFF3 is a common format for microRNA data resulting from small-RNA RNA-Seq workflows.
miRTop format
@graph.rdfs:comment: mirGFF3 is a specialisation of GFF3; produced by small-RNA-Seq analysis workflows, usable and convertible with the miRTop API (https://mirtop.readthedocs.io/en/latest/), and consumable by tools for downstream analysis.
@graph.rdfs:label: mirGFF3

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: RNA data format
A "placeholder" concept for formats of annotated RNA data, including e.g. microRNA and RNA-Seq data.
@graph.rdfs:label: RNA annotation format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: File format to store trajectory information for a 3D structure .
@graph.rdfs:comment: Formats differ on what they are able to store (coordinates, velocities, topologies) and how they are storing it (raw, compressed, textual, binary).
@graph.rdfs:label: Trajectory format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Binary file format to store trajectory information for a 3D structure .
@graph.rdfs:label: Trajectory format (binary)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Textual file format to store trajectory information for a 3D structure .
@graph.rdfs:label: Trajectory format (text)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: HDF is the name of a set of file formats and libraries designed to store and organize large amounts of numerical data, originally developed at the National Center for Supercomputing Applications at the University of Illinois.
@graph.rdfs:comment: HDF is currently supported by many commercial and non-commercial software platforms such as Java, MATLAB/Scilab, Octave, Python and R.
@graph.rdfs:label: HDF

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: PCAZip format is a binary compressed file to store atom coordinates based on Essential Dynamics (ED) and Principal Component Analysis (PCA).
@graph.rdfs:comment: The compression is made projecting the Cartesian snapshots collected along the trajectory into an orthogonal space defined by the most relevant eigenvectors obtained by diagonalization of the covariance matrix (PCA). In the compression/decompression process, part of the original information is lost, depending on the final number of eigenvectors chosen. However, with a reasonable choice of the set of eigenvectors the compression typically reduces the trajectory file to less than one tenth of their original size with very acceptable loss of information. Compression with PCAZip can only be applied to unsolvated structures.
@graph.rdfs:label: PCAzip

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Portable binary format for trajectories produced by GROMACS package.
@graph.rdfs:comment: XTC uses the External Data Representation (xdr) routines for writing and reading data which were created for the Unix Network File System (NFS). XTC files use a reduced precision (lossy) algorithm which works multiplying the coordinates by a scaling factor (typically 1000), so converting them to pm (GROMACS standard distance unit is nm). This allows an integer rounding of the values. Several other tricks are performed, such as making use of atom proximity information: atoms close in sequence are usually close in space (e.g. water molecules). That makes XTC format the most efficient in terms of disk usage, in most cases reducing by a factor of 2 the size of any other binary trajectory format.
@graph.rdfs:label: XTC

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Trajectory Next Generation (TNG) is a format for storage of molecular simulation data. It is designed and implemented by the GROMACS development group, and it is called to be the substitute of the XTC format.
Trajectory Next Generation format
@graph.rdfs:comment: Fully architecture-independent format, regarding both endianness and the ability to mix single/double precision trajectories and I/O libraries. Self-sufficient, it should not require any other files for reading, and all the data should be contained in a single file for easy transport. Temporal compression of data, improving the compression rate of the previous XTC format. Possibility to store meta-data with information about the simulation. Direct access to a particular frame. Efficient parallel I/O.
@graph.rdfs:label: TNG

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The XYZ chemical file format is widely supported by many programs, although many slightly different XYZ file formats coexist (Tinker XYZ, UniChem XYZ, etc.). Basic information stored for each atom in the system are x, y and z coordinates and atom element/atomic number.
@graph.rdfs:comment: XYZ files are structured in this way:  First line contains the number of atoms in the file.  Second line contains a title, comment, or filename. Remaining lines contain atom information. Each line starts with the element symbol, followed by x, y and z coordinates in angstroms separated by whitespace. Multiple molecules or frames can be contained within one file, so it supports trajectory storage. XYZ files can be directly represented by a molecular viewer, as they contain all the basic information needed to build the 3D model.
@graph.rdfs:label: XYZ

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: AMBER trajectory (also called mdcrd), with 10 coordinates per line and format F8.3 (fixed point notation with field width 8 and 3 decimal places).
@graph.rdfs:label: mdcrd

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Format of topology files; containing the static information of a structure molecular system that is needed for a molecular simulation.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Many different file formats exist describing structural molecular topology. Tipically, each MD package or simulation software works with their own implementation (e.g. GROMACS top, CHARMM psf, AMBER prmtop).
@graph.rdfs:label: Topology format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: GROMACS MD package top textual files define an entire structure system topology, either directly, or by including itp files.
@graph.rdfs:comment: There is currently no tool available for conversion between GROMACS topology format and other formats, due to the internal differences in both approaches. There is, however, a method to convert small molecules parameterized with AMBER force-field into GROMACS format, allowing simulations of these systems with GROMACS MD package.
@graph.rdfs:label: GROMACS top

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: AMBER Prmtop file (version 7) is a structure topology text file divided in several sections designed to be parsed easily using simple Fortran code. Each section contains particular topology information, such as atom name, charge, mass, angles, dihedrals, etc.
rdfs:comment: It can be modified manually, but as the size of the system increases, the hand-editing becomes increasingly complex. AMBER Parameter-Topology file format is used extensively by the AMBER software suite and is referred to as the Prmtop file for short.

version 7 is written to distinguish it from old versions of AMBER Prmtop. Similarly to HDF5, it is a completely different format, according to AMBER group: a drastic change to the file format occurred with the 2004 release of Amber 7 (http://ambermd.org/prmtop.pdf)
@graph.rdfs:label: AMBER top

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: X-Plor Protein Structure Files (PSF) are structure topology files used by NAMD and CHARMM molecular simulations programs. PSF files contain six main sections of interest: atoms, bonds, angles, dihedrals, improper dihedrals (force terms used to maintain planarity) and cross-terms.
@graph.rdfs:comment: The high similarity in the functional form of the two potential energy functions used by AMBER and CHARMM force-fields gives rise to the possible use of one force-field within the other MD engine. Therefore, the conversion of PSF files to AMBER Prmtop format is possible with the use of AMBER chamber (CHARMM - AMBER) program.
@graph.rdfs:label: PSF

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: GROMACS itp files (include topology) contain structure topology information, and are tipically included in GROMACS topology files (GROMACS top). Itp files are used to define individual (or multiple) components of a topology as a separate file. This is particularly useful if there is a molecule that is used frequently, and also reduces the size of the system topology file, splitting it in different parts.
@graph.rdfs:comment: GROMACS itp files are used also to define position restrictions on the molecule, or to define the force field parameters for a particular ligand.
@graph.rdfs:label: GROMACS itp

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Format of force field parameter files, which store the set of parameters (charges, masses, radii, bond lengths, bond dihedrals, etc.) that are essential for the proper description and simulation of a molecular system.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Many different file formats exist describing force field parameters. Tipically, each MD package or simulation software works with their own implementation (e.g. GROMACS itp, CHARMM rtf, AMBER off / frcmod).
@graph.rdfs:label: FF parameter format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Scripps Research Institute BinPos format is a binary formatted file to store atom coordinates.
Scripps Research Institute BinPos
@graph.rdfs:comment: It is basically a translation of the ASCII atom coordinate format to binary code. The only additional information stored is a magic number that identifies the BinPos format and the number of atoms per snapshot. The remainder is the chain of coordinates binary encoded. A drawback of this format is its architecture dependency. Integers and floats codification depends on the architecture, thus it needs to be converted if working in different platforms (little endian, big endian).
@graph.rdfs:label: BinPos

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: AMBER coordinate/restart file with 6 coordinates per line and decimal format F12.7 (fixed point notation with field width 12 and 7 decimal places)
@graph.rdfs:label: RST

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Format of CHARMM Residue Topology Files (RTF), which define groups by including the atoms, the properties of the group, and bond and charge information.
@graph.rdfs:comment: There is currently no tool available for conversion between GROMACS topology format and other formats, due to the internal differences in both approaches. There is, however, a method to convert small molecules parameterized with AMBER force-field into GROMACS format, allowing simulations of these systems with GROMACS MD package.
@graph.rdfs:label: CHARMM rtf

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: AMBER frcmod (Force field Modification) is a file format to store any modification to the standard force field needed for a particular molecule to be properly represented in the simulation.
@graph.rdfs:label: AMBER frcmod

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: AMBER Object File Format library files (OFF library files) store residue libraries (forcefield residue parameters).
@graph.rdfs:label: AMBER off

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: MReData is a text based data standard for processed NMR data. It is relying on SDF molecule data and allows to store assignments of NMR peaks to molecule features.  The NMR-extracted data (or âNMReDATAâ) includes: Chemical shift,scalar coupling, 2D correlation, assignment, etc.
@graph.rdfs:comment: NMReData is a text based data standard for processed NMR data. It is relying on SDF molecule data and allows to store assignments of NMR peaks to molecule features. The NMR-extracted data (or âNMReDATAâ) includes: Chemical shift,scalar coupling, 2D correlation, assignment, etc. Find more in the paper at D. Jeannerat, Magn. Reson. in Chem., 2017, 55, 7-14.
@graph.rdfs:label: NMReDATA

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: BpForms is a string format for concretely representing the primary structures of biopolymers, including DNA, RNA, and proteins that include non-canonical nucleic and amino acids. See https://www.bpforms.org for more information.
@graph.rdfs:label: BpForms

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The first 4 bytes of any trr file containing 1993. See https://github.com/galaxyproject/galaxy/pull/6597/files#diff-409951594551183dbf886e24de6cb129R760
Format of trr files that contain the trajectory of a simulation experiment used by GROMACS.
@graph.rdfs:label: trr

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Mash sketch is a format for sequence / sequence checksum information. To make a sketch, each k-mer in a sequence is hashed, which creates a pseudo-random identifier. By sorting these hashes, a small subset from the top of the sorted list can represent the entire sequence.
@graph.rdfs:label: msh

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The Loom file format is based on HDF5, a standard for storing large numerical datasets. The Loom format is designed to efficiently hold large omics datasets. Typically, such data takes the form of a large matrix of numbers, along with metadata for the rows and columns.
@graph.rdfs:label: Loom

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The Zarr format is an implementation of chunked, compressed, N-dimensional arrays for storing data.
@graph.rdfs:label: Zarr

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The Matrix Market matrix (MTX) format stores numerical or pattern matrices in a dense (array format) or sparse (coordinate format) representation.
@graph.rdfs:label: MTX

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: BcForms is a format for abstractly describing the molecular structure (atoms and bonds) of macromolecular complexes as a collection of subunits and crosslinks. Each subunit can be described with BpForms (http://edamontology.org/format_3909) or SMILES (http://edamontology.org/data_2301). BcForms uses an ontology of crosslinks to abstract the chemical details of crosslinks from the descriptions of complexes (see https://bpforms.org/crosslink.html).
@graph.rdfs:comment: BcForms is related to http://edamontology.org/format_3909. (BcForms uses BpForms to describe subunits which are DNA, RNA, or protein polymers.) However, that format isn't the parent of BcForms. BcForms is similarly related to SMILES (http://edamontology.org/data_2301).
@graph.rdfs:label: BcForms

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: N-Quads is a line-based, plain text format for encoding an RDF dataset. It includes information about the graph each triple belongs to.
@graph.rdfs:comment: N-Quads should not be confused with N-Triples which does not contain graph information.
@graph.rdfs:label: N-Quads

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: 'A has_format B' defines for the subject A, that it has the object B as its data format.
false
@graph.rdfs:comment: Subject A can be any concept or entity outside of an ontology (or an ontology concept in a role of an entity being semantically annotated) that is (or is in a role of) 'Data', or an input, output, input or output argument of an 'Operation'. Object B can either be a concept that is a 'Format', or in unexpected cases an entity outside of an ontology that is a 'Format' or is in the role of a 'Format'. In EDAM, 'has_format' is not explicitly defined between EDAM concepts, only the inverse 'is_format_of'.
@graph.rdfs:label: has format

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: 'A has_function B' defines for the subject A, that it has the object B as its function.
OBO_REL:bearer_of
true
@graph.rdfs:comment: Subject A can be any concept or entity outside of an ontology (or an ontology concept in a role of an entity being semantically annotated). Object B can either be a concept that is (or is in a role of) a function, or an entity outside of an ontology that is (or is in a role of) a function specification. In the scope of EDAM, 'has_function' serves only for relating annotated entities outside of EDAM with 'Operation' concepts.
@graph.rdfs:label: has function

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: 'A has_identifier B' defines for the subject A, that it has the object B as its identifier.
false
@graph.rdfs:comment: Subject A can be any concept or entity outside of an ontology (or an ontology concept in a role of an entity being semantically annotated). Object B can either be a concept that is an 'Identifier', or an entity outside of an ontology that is an 'Identifier' or is in the role of an 'Identifier'. In EDAM, 'has_identifier' is not explicitly defined between EDAM concepts, only the inverse 'is_identifier_of'.
@graph.rdfs:label: has identifier

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: 'A has_input B' defines for the subject A, that it has the object B as a necessary or actual input or input argument.
OBO_REL:has_participant
true
@graph.rdfs:comment: Subject A can either be concept that is or has an 'Operation' function, or an entity outside of an ontology (or an ontology concept in a role of an entity being semantically annotated) that has an 'Operation' function or is an 'Operation'. Object B can be any concept or entity. In EDAM, only 'has_input' is explicitly defined between EDAM concepts ('Operation' 'has_input' 'Data'). The inverse, 'is_input_of', is not explicitly defined.
@graph.rdfs:label: has input

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: 'A has_output B' defines for the subject A, that it has the object B as a necessary or actual output or output argument.
OBO_REL:has_participant
true
@graph.rdfs:comment: Subject A can either be concept that is or has an 'Operation' function, or an entity outside of an ontology (or an ontology concept in a role of an entity being semantically annotated) that has an 'Operation' function or is an 'Operation'. Object B can be any concept or entity. In EDAM, only 'has_output' is explicitly defined between EDAM concepts ('Operation' 'has_output' 'Data'). The inverse, 'is_output_of', is not explicitly defined.
@graph.rdfs:label: has output

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: 'A has_topic B' defines for the subject A, that it has the object B as its topic (A is in the scope of a topic B).
true
@graph.rdfs:comment: Subject A can be any concept or entity outside of an ontology (or an ontology concept in a role of an entity being semantically annotated). Object B can either be a concept that is a 'Topic', or in unexpected cases an entity outside of an ontology that is a 'Topic' or is in the role of a 'Topic'. In EDAM, only 'has_topic' is explicitly defined between EDAM concepts ('Operation' or 'Data' 'has_topic' 'Topic'). The inverse, 'is_topic_of', is not explicitly defined.
@graph.rdfs:label: has topic

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: "Supported by the given data format" here means, that the given format enables representation of data that satisfies the information standard.

'Information standard' trailing modifier (qualifier, 'information_standard') of 'xref' links of 'Format' concepts. When 'true', the link is pointing to an information standard supported by the given data format.
concept_properties
@graph.rdfs:label: Information standard

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: When 'true', the concept has been proposed to be deprecated.
concept_properties
@graph.rdfs:label: deprecation_candidate

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: 'A is_format_of B' defines for the subject A, that it is a data format of the object B.
OBO_REL:quality_of
false
@graph.rdfs:comment: Subject A can either be a concept that is a 'Format', or in unexpected cases an entity outside of an ontology (or an ontology concept in a role of an entity being semantically annotated) that is a 'Format' or is in the role of a 'Format'. Object B can be any concept or entity outside of an ontology that is (or is in a role of) 'Data', or  an input, output, input or output argument of an 'Operation'. In EDAM, only 'is_format_of' is explicitly defined between EDAM concepts ('Format' 'is_format_of' 'Data'). The inverse, 'has_format', is not explicitly defined.
@graph.rdfs:label: is format of

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: 'A is_function_of B' defines for the subject A, that it is a function of the object B.
OBO_REL:function_of
OBO_REL:inheres_in
true
@graph.rdfs:comment: Subject A can either be concept that is (or is in a role of) a function, or an entity outside of an ontology (or an ontology concept in a role of an entity being semantically annotated) that is (or is in a role of) a function specification. Object B can be any concept or entity. Within EDAM itself, 'is_function_of' is not used.
@graph.rdfs:label: is function of

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: 'A is_identifier_of B' defines for the subject A, that it is an identifier of the object B.
false
@graph.rdfs:comment: Subject A can either be a concept that is an 'Identifier', or an entity outside of an ontology (or an ontology concept in a role of an entity being semantically annotated) that is an 'Identifier' or is in the role of an 'Identifier'. Object B can be any concept or entity outside of an ontology. In EDAM, only 'is_identifier_of' is explicitly defined between EDAM concepts (only 'Identifier' 'is_identifier_of' 'Data'). The inverse, 'has_identifier', is not explicitly defined.
@graph.rdfs:label: is identifier of

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: 'A is_input_of B' defines for the subject A, that it as a necessary or actual input or input argument of the object B.
OBO_REL:participates_in
true
@graph.rdfs:comment: Subject A can be any concept or entity outside of an ontology (or an ontology concept in a role of an entity being semantically annotated). Object B can either be a concept that is or has an 'Operation' function, or an entity outside of an ontology that has an 'Operation' function or is an 'Operation'. In EDAM, 'is_input_of' is not explicitly defined between EDAM concepts, only the inverse 'has_input'.
@graph.rdfs:label: is input of

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: 'A is_output_of B' defines for the subject A, that it as a necessary or actual output or output argument of the object B.
OBO_REL:participates_in
true
@graph.rdfs:comment: Subject A can be any concept or entity outside of an ontology (or an ontology concept in a role of an entity being semantically annotated). Object B can either be a concept that is or has an 'Operation' function, or an entity outside of an ontology that has an 'Operation' function or is an 'Operation'. In EDAM, 'is_output_of' is not explicitly defined between EDAM concepts, only the inverse 'has_output'.
@graph.rdfs:label: is output of

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: When 'true', the concept has been proposed to be refactored.
concept_properties
@graph.rdfs:label: refactor_candidate

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: 'A is_topic_of B' defines for the subject A, that it is a topic of the object B (a topic A is the scope of B).
OBO_REL:quality_of
true
@graph.rdfs:comment: Subject A can either be a concept that is a 'Topic', or in unexpected cases an entity outside of an ontology (or an ontology concept in a role of an entity being semantically annotated) that is a 'Topic' or is in the role of a 'Topic'. Object B can be any concept or entity outside of an ontology. In EDAM, 'is_topic_of' is not explicitly defined between EDAM concepts, only the inverse 'has_topic'.
@graph.rdfs:label: is topic of

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: When 'true', the concept has been proposed or is supported within Debian as a tag.
concept_properties
@graph.rdfs:label: isdebtag

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: 'Media type' trailing modifier (qualifier, 'media_type') of 'xref' links of 'Format' concepts. When 'true', the link is pointing to a page specifying a media type of the given data format.
MIME type
concept_properties
@graph.rdfs:label: Media type

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Whether terms associated with this concept are recommended for use in annotation.
concept_properties

concept_properties
@graph.rdfs:label: Obsolete since

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: EDAM concept URI of the erstwhile "parent" of a now deprecated concept.
concept_properties
@graph.rdfs:label: Old parent

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: EDAM concept URI of an erstwhile related concept (by has_input, has_output, has_topic, is_format_of, etc.) of a now deprecated concept.
concept_properties
@graph.rdfs:label: Old related

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: 'Ontology used' concept property ('ontology_used' metadata tag) of format concepts links to a domain ontology that is used inside the given data format, or contains a note about ontology use within the format.
concept_properties
@graph.rdfs:label: Ontology used

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Function
A function that processes a set of inputs and results in a set of outputs, or associates arguments (inputs) with values (outputs).
@graph.rdfs:comment: Special cases are: a) An operation that consumes no input (has no input arguments). Such operation is either a constant function, or an operation depending only on the underlying state. b) An operation that may modify the underlying state but has no output. c) The singular-case operation with no input or output, that still may modify the underlying state.
@graph.rdfs:label: Operation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Search or query a data resource and retrieve entries and / or annotation.
Database retrieval
Query
@graph.rdfs:label: Query and retrieval

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Search database to retrieve all relevant references to a particular entity or entry.
@graph.rdfs:label: Data retrieval (database cross-reference)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Annotate an entity (typically a biological or biomedical database entity) with terms from a controlled vocabulary.
@graph.rdfs:comment: This is a broad concept and is used a placeholder for other, more specific concepts.
@graph.rdfs:label: Annotation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Generate an index of (typically a file of) biological data.
@graph.rdfs:label: Indexing

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Analyse an index of biological data.
@graph.rdfs:label: Data index analysis

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Retrieve basic information about a molecular sequence.
@graph.rdfs:label: Annotation retrieval (sequence)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Generate a molecular sequence by some means.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence generation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Edit or change a molecular sequence, either randomly or specifically.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence editing

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Merge two or more (typically overlapping) molecular sequences.
Sequence splicing
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence merging

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Convert a molecular sequence from one type to another.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence conversion

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Calculate sequence complexity, for example to find low-complexity regions in sequences.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence complexity calculation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Calculate sequence ambiguity, for example identity regions in protein or nucleotide sequences with many ambiguity codes.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence ambiguity calculation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Calculate character or word composition or frequency of a molecular sequence.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence composition calculation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Find and/or analyse repeat sequences in (typically nucleotide) sequences.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Repeat sequences include tandem repeats, inverted or palindromic repeats, DNA microsatellites (Simple Sequence Repeats or SSRs), interspersed repeats, maximal duplications and reverse, complemented and reverse complemented repeats etc. Repeat units can be exact or imperfect, in tandem or dispersed, of specified or unspecified length.
@graph.rdfs:label: Repeat sequence analysis

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Discover new motifs or conserved patterns in sequences or sequence alignments (de-novo discovery).
Motif discovery
@graph.rdfs:comment: Motifs and patterns might be conserved or over-represented (occur with improbable frequency).
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence motif discovery

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Find (scan for) known motifs, patterns and regular expressions in molecular sequence(s).
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence motif recognition

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Find motifs shared by molecular sequences.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence motif comparison

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Analyse the sequence, conformational or physicochemical properties of transcription regulatory elements in DNA sequences.
@graph.rdfs:comment: For example transcription factor binding sites (TFBS) analysis to predict accessibility of DNA to binding factors.
@graph.rdfs:label: Transcription regulatory sequence analysis

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identify common, conserved (homologous) or synonymous transcriptional regulatory motifs (transcription factor binding sites).
@graph.rdfs:label: Conserved transcription regulatory sequence identification

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Extract, calculate or predict non-positional (physical or chemical) properties of a protein from processing a protein (3D) structure.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein property calculation (from structure)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Analyse flexibility and motion in protein structure.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Use this concept for analysis of flexible and rigid residues, local chain deformability, regions undergoing conformational change, molecular vibrations or fluctuational dynamics, domain motions or other large-scale structural transitions in a protein structure.
@graph.rdfs:label: Simulation analysis

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identify or screen for 3D structural motifs in protein structure(s).
@graph.rdfs:comment: This includes conserved substructures and conserved geometry, such as spatial arrangement of secondary structure or protein backbone. Methods might use structure alignment, structural templates, searches for similar electrostatic potential and molecular surface shape, surface-mapping of phylogenetic information etc.
@graph.rdfs:label: Structural motif discovery

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identify structural domains in a protein structure from first principles (for example calculations on structural compactness).
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein domain recognition

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Analyse the architecture (spatial arrangement of secondary structure) of protein structure(s).
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein architecture analysis

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Calculate or extract inter-atomic, inter-residue or residue-atom contacts, distances and interactions in protein structure(s).
@graph.rdfs:label: Residue interaction calculation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Calculate, visualise or analyse phi/psi angles of a protein structure.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein geometry calculation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Extract, calculate or predict non-positional (physical or chemical) properties of a protein, including any non-positional properties of the molecular sequence, from processing a protein sequence or 3D structure.
Protein property rendering
@graph.rdfs:comment: This includes methods to render and visualise the properties of a protein sequence, and a residue-level search for properties such as solvent accessibility, hydropathy, secondary structure, ligand-binding etc.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein property calculation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Predict antigenicity, allergenicity / immunogenicity, allergic cross-reactivity etc of peptides and proteins.
Immunogenicity prediction
rdfs:comment: This includes methods that generate a graphical rendering of antigenicity of a protein, such as a Hopp and Woods plot.
This is usually done in the development of peptide-specific antibodies or multi-epitope vaccines. Methods might use sequence data (for example motifs) and / or structural data.
@graph.rdfs:label: Peptide immunogenicity prediction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Predict, recognise and identify positional features in molecular sequences such as key functional sites or regions.
Motif database search
@graph.rdfs:comment: Look at "Protein feature detection" (http://edamontology.org/operation_3092) and "Nucleic acid feature detection" (http://edamontology.org/operation_0415) in case more specific terms are needed.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence feature detection

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Extract a sequence feature table from a sequence database entry.
@graph.rdfs:label: Data retrieval (feature table)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Query the features (in a feature table) of molecular sequence(s).
@graph.rdfs:label: Feature table query

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Compare the feature tables of two or more molecular sequences.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence feature comparison

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Display basic information about a sequence alignment.
@graph.rdfs:label: Data retrieval (sequence alignment)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Analyse a molecular sequence alignment.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence alignment analysis

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Compare (typically by aligning) two molecular sequence alignments.
@graph.rdfs:comment: See also 'Sequence profile alignment'.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence alignment comparison

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Convert a molecular sequence alignment from one type to another (for example amino acid to coding nucleotide sequence).
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence alignment conversion

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Process (read and / or write) physicochemical property data of nucleic acids.
@graph.rdfs:label: Nucleic acid property processing

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Calculate or predict physical or chemical properties of nucleic acid molecules, including any non-positional properties of the molecular sequence.
@graph.rdfs:label: Nucleic acid property calculation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Predict splicing alternatives or transcript isoforms from analysis of sequence data.
@graph.rdfs:label: Alternative splicing prediction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Detect frameshifts in DNA sequences, including frameshift sites and signals, and frameshift errors from sequencing projects.
Frameshift error detection
@graph.rdfs:comment: Methods include sequence alignment (if related sequences are available) and word-based sequence comparison.
@graph.rdfs:label: Frameshift detection

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Detect vector sequences in nucleotide sequence, typically by comparison to a set of known vector sequences.
@graph.rdfs:label: Vector sequence detection

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Predict secondary structure of protein sequences.
Secondary structure prediction (protein)
@graph.rdfs:comment: Methods might use amino acid composition, local sequence information, multiple sequence alignments, physicochemical features, estimated energy content, statistical algorithms, hidden Markov models, support vector machines, kernel machines, neural networks etc.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein secondary structure prediction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Predict super-secondary structure of protein sequence(s).
@graph.rdfs:comment: Super-secondary structures include leucine zippers, coiled coils, Helix-Turn-Helix etc.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein super-secondary structure prediction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Predict and/or classify transmembrane proteins or transmembrane (helical) domains or regions in protein sequences.
@graph.rdfs:label: Transmembrane protein prediction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Analyse transmembrane protein(s), typically by processing sequence and / or structural data, and write an informative report for example about the protein and its transmembrane domains / regions.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Use this (or child) concept for analysis of transmembrane domains (buried and exposed faces), transmembrane helices, helix topology, orientation, inter-helical contacts, membrane dipping (re-entrant) loops and other secondary structure etc. Methods might use pattern discovery, hidden Markov models, sequence alignment, structural profiles, amino acid property analysis, comparison to known domains or some combination (hybrid methods).
@graph.rdfs:label: Transmembrane protein analysis

@graph.http://edamontology.org/deprecation_comm: This is a "organisational class" not very useful for annotation per se.
@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Predict tertiary structure of a molecular (biopolymer) sequence.
@graph.rdfs:label: Structure prediction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Predict contacts, non-covalent interactions and distance (constraints) between amino acids in protein sequences.
Residue interaction prediction
@graph.rdfs:comment: Methods usually involve multiple sequence alignment analysis.
@graph.rdfs:label: Residue contact prediction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Analyse experimental protein-protein interaction data from for example yeast two-hybrid analysis, protein microarrays, immunoaffinity chromatography followed by mass spectrometry, phage display etc.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein interaction raw data analysis

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identify or predict protein-protein interactions, interfaces, binding sites etc in protein sequences.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein-protein interaction prediction (from protein sequence)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identify or predict protein-protein interactions, interfaces, binding sites etc in protein structures.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein-protein interaction prediction (from protein structure)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Analyse a network of protein interactions.
Protein interaction network comparison
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein interaction network analysis

@graph.http://edamontology.org/deprecation_comm: Notions of pathway and network were mixed up, EDAM 1.24 disentangles them.
@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Compare two or more biological pathways or networks.
@graph.rdfs:label: Pathway or network comparison

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Predict RNA secondary structure (for example knots, pseudoknots, alternative structures etc).
RNA shape prediction
@graph.rdfs:comment: Methods might use RNA motifs, predicted intermolecular contacts, or RNA sequence-structure compatibility (inverse RNA folding).
@graph.rdfs:label: RNA secondary structure prediction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Analyse some aspect of RNA/DNA folding, typically by processing sequence and/or structural data.  For example, compute folding energies such as minimum folding energies for DNA or RNA sequences or energy landscape of RNA mutants.
Nucleic acid folding energy calculation
@graph.rdfs:label: Nucleic acid folding analysis

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Retrieve information on restriction enzymes or restriction enzyme sites.
@graph.rdfs:label: Data retrieval (restriction enzyme annotation)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identify genetic markers in DNA sequences.
@graph.rdfs:comment: A genetic marker is any DNA sequence of known chromosomal location that is associated with and specific to a particular gene or trait. This includes short sequences surrounding a SNP, Sequence-Tagged Sites (STS) which are well suited for PCR amplification, a longer minisatellites sequence etc.
@graph.rdfs:label: Genetic marker identification

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Generate a genetic (linkage) map of a DNA sequence (typically a chromosome) showing the relative positions of genetic markers based on estimation of non-physical distances.
QTL mapping
rdfs:comment: Mapping involves ordering genetic loci along a chromosome and estimating the physical distance between loci. A genetic map shows the relative (not physical) position of known genes and genetic markers.
This includes mapping of the genetic architecture of dynamic complex traits (functional mapping), e.g. by characterisation of the underlying quantitative trait loci (QTLs) or nucleotides (QTNs).
@graph.rdfs:label: Genetic mapping

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Analyse genetic linkage.
@graph.rdfs:comment: For example, estimate how close two genes are on a chromosome by calculating how often they are transmitted together to an offspring, ascertain whether two genes are linked and parental linkage, calculate linkage map distance etc.
@graph.rdfs:label: Linkage analysis

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Calculate codon usage statistics and create a codon usage table.
Codon usage table construction
@graph.rdfs:label: Codon usage table generation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Compare two or more codon usage tables.
@graph.rdfs:label: Codon usage table comparison

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Analyse codon usage in molecular sequences or process codon usage data (e.g. a codon usage table).
@graph.rdfs:label: Codon usage analysis

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identify and plot third base position variability in a nucleotide sequence.
@graph.rdfs:label: Base position variability plotting

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Find exact character or word matches between molecular sequences without full sequence alignment.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence word comparison

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Calculate a sequence distance matrix or otherwise estimate genetic distances between molecular sequences.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence distance matrix generation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Compare two or more molecular sequences, identify and remove redundant sequences based on some criteria.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence redundancy removal

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Build clusters of similar sequences, typically using scores from pair-wise alignment or other comparison of the sequences.
@graph.rdfs:comment: The clusters may be output or used internally for some other purpose.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence clustering

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Includes methods that align sequence profiles (representing sequence alignments): ethods might perform one-to-one, one-to-many or many-to-many comparisons.  See also 'Sequence alignment comparison'.
Align (identify equivalent sites within) molecular sequences.
@graph.rdfs:comment: See also "Read mapping"
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence alignment

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Align two or more molecular sequences of different types (for example genomic DNA to EST, cDNA or mRNA).
@graph.rdfs:label: Hybrid sequence alignment construction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Align molecular sequences using sequence and structural information.
Sequence alignment (structure-based)
@graph.rdfs:label: Structure-based sequence alignment

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Includes methods that align structural (3D) profiles or templates (representing structures or structure alignments) - including methods that perform one-to-one, one-to-many or many-to-many comparisons.
Align (superimpose) molecular tertiary structures.
Structural alignment
@graph.rdfs:label: Structure alignment

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Generate some type of sequence profile (for example a hidden Markov model) from a sequence alignment.
Sequence profile construction
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence profile generation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Generate some type of structural (3D) profile or template from a structure or structure alignment.
@graph.rdfs:label: 3D profile generation
