@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Align sequence profiles (representing sequence alignments).
@graph.rdfs:label: Profile-profile alignment

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Align structural (3D) profiles or templates (representing structures or structure alignments).
@graph.rdfs:label: 3D profile-to-3D profile alignment

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Align molecular sequence(s) to sequence profile(s), or profiles to other profiles.  A profile typically represents a sequence alignment.
@graph.rdfs:comment: A sequence profile typically represents a sequence alignment. Methods might perform one-to-one, one-to-many or many-to-many comparisons.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence profile alignment

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Align molecular sequence(s) to structural (3D) profile(s) or template(s) (representing a structure or structure alignment).
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence-to-3D-profile alignment

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: This includes sequence-to-3D-profile alignment methods, which align molecular sequence(s) to structural (3D) profile(s) or template(s) (representing a structure or structure alignment) - methods might perform one-to-one, one-to-many or many-to-many comparisons.
Align molecular sequence to structure in 3D space (threading).
Sequence-structure alignment
@graph.rdfs:comment: Use this concept for methods that evaluate sequence-structure compatibility by assessing residue interactions in 3D. Methods might perform one-to-one, one-to-many or many-to-many comparisons.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein threading

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Recognize (predict and identify) known protein structural domains or folds in protein sequence(s) which (typically) are not accompanied by any significant sequence similarity to know structures.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Methods use some type of mapping between sequence and fold, for example secondary structure prediction and alignment, profile comparison, sequence properties, homologous sequence search, kernel machines etc. Domains and folds might be taken from SCOP or CATH.
@graph.rdfs:label: Fold recognition

@graph.http://edamontology.org/deprecation_comm: (jison)Too fine-grained, the operation (Data retrieval) hasn't changed, just what is retrieved.
@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Search for and retrieve data concerning or describing some core data, as distinct from the primary data that is being described.
@graph.rdfs:comment: This includes documentation, general information and other metadata on entities such as databases, database entries and tools.
@graph.rdfs:label: Metadata retrieval

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Query scientific literature, in search for articles, article data, concepts, named entities, or for statistics.
@graph.rdfs:label: Literature search

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Text analysis
Process and analyse text (typically scientific literature) to extract information from it.
@graph.rdfs:label: Text mining

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Perform in-silico (virtual) PCR.
@graph.rdfs:label: Virtual PCR

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Design or predict oligonucleotide primers for PCR and DNA amplification etc.
http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: PCR primer design (based on gene structure)
PCR primer design (for gene transcription profiling)
PCR primer design (for large scale sequencing)
rdfs:comment: Primer design involves predicting or selecting primers that are specific to a provided PCR template. Primers can be designed with certain properties such as size of product desired, primer size etc. The output might be a minimal or overlapping primer set.

This includes predicting primers based on gene structure, promoters, exon-exon junctions, predicting primers that are conserved across multiple genomes or species, primers for for gene transcription profiling,  for genotyping polymorphisms, for example single nucleotide polymorphisms (SNPs),  for large scale sequencing, or for methylation PCRs.
@graph.rdfs:label: PCR primer design

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Predict and/or optimize oligonucleotide probes for DNA microarrays, for example for transcription profiling of genes, or for genomes and gene families.
Microarray probe prediction
@graph.rdfs:label: Microarray probe design

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Combine (align and merge) overlapping fragments of a DNA sequence to reconstruct the original sequence.
@graph.rdfs:comment: For example, assemble overlapping reads from paired-end sequencers into contigs (a contiguous sequence corresponding to read overlaps). Or assemble contigs, for example ESTs and genomic DNA fragments, depending on the detected fragment overlaps.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence assembly

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Standardize or normalize microarray data.
@graph.rdfs:label: Microarray data standardisation and normalisation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Process (read and / or write) SAGE, MPSS or SBS experimental data.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequencing-based expression profile data processing

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Perform cluster analysis of expression data to identify groups with similar expression profiles, for example by clustering.
@graph.rdfs:label: Expression profile clustering

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The measurement of the gene expression of multiple genes in a cell, tissue, sample etc., in order to get an impression of biological function.
@graph.rdfs:label: Gene expression profiling

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Comparison of expression profiles.
@graph.rdfs:label: Expression profile comparison

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Interpret (in functional terms) and annotate gene expression data.
@graph.rdfs:label: Functional profiling

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Analyse EST or cDNA sequences.
@graph.rdfs:comment: For example, identify full-length cDNAs from EST sequences or detect potential EST antisense transcripts.
@graph.rdfs:label: EST and cDNA sequence analysis

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identify and select targets for protein structural determination.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Methods will typically navigate a graph of protein families of known structure.
@graph.rdfs:label: Structural genomics target selection

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Includes secondary structure assignment from circular dichroism (CD) spectroscopic data, and from protein coordinate data.
Assign secondary structure from protein coordinate or experimental data.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein secondary structure assignment

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Assign a protein tertiary structure (3D coordinates), or other aspects of protein structure, from raw experimental data.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein structure assignment

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Evaluate the quality or correctness a protein three-dimensional model.
Protein model validation
Residue validation
rdfs:comment: Model validation might involve checks for atomic packing, steric clashes (bumps), volume irregularities, agreement with electron density maps, number of amino acid residues, percentage of residues with missing or bad atoms, irregular Ramachandran Z-scores, irregular Chi-1 / Chi-2 normality scores, RMS-Z score on bonds and angles etc.

The PDB file format has had difficulties, inconsistencies and errors. Corrections can include identifying a meaningful sequence, removal of alternate atoms, correction of nomenclature problems, removal of incomplete residues and spurious waters, addition or removal of water, modelling of missing side chains, optimisation of cysteine bonds, regularisation of bond lengths, bond angles and planarities etc.

This includes methods that calculate poor quality residues. The scoring function to identify poor quality residues may consider residues with bad atoms or atoms with high B-factor, residues in the N- or C-terminal position, adjacent to an unstructured residue, non-canonical residues, glycine and proline (or adjacent to these such residues).
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein structure validation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: WHATIF: CorrectedPDBasXML
Refine (after evaluation) a model of a molecular structure (typically a protein structure) to reduce steric clashes, volume irregularities etc.
Protein model refinement
@graph.rdfs:label: Molecular model refinement

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Construct a phylogenetic tree.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Phylogenetic trees are usually constructed from a set of sequences from which an alignment (or data matrix) is calculated.
@graph.rdfs:label: Phylogenetic tree construction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Analyse an existing phylogenetic tree or trees, typically to detect features or make predictions.
Phylogenetic tree analysis
Phylogenetic modelling
@graph.rdfs:comment: Phylgenetic modelling is the modelling of trait evolution and prediction of trait values using phylogeny as a basis.
@graph.rdfs:label: Phylogenetic analysis

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Compare two or more phylogenetic trees.
@graph.rdfs:comment: For example, to produce a consensus tree, subtrees, supertrees, calculate distances between trees or test topological similarity between trees (e.g. a congruence index) etc.
@graph.rdfs:label: Phylogenetic tree comparison

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Edit a phylogenetic tree.
@graph.rdfs:label: Phylogenetic tree editing

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Comparison of a DNA sequence to orthologous sequences in different species and inference of a phylogenetic tree, in order to identify regulatory elements such as transcription factor binding sites (TFBS).
Phylogenetic shadowing
@graph.rdfs:comment: Phylogenetic shadowing is a type of footprinting where many closely related species are used.  A phylogenetic 'shadow' represents the additive differences between individual sequences. By masking or 'shadowing' variable positions a conserved sequence is produced with few or none of the variations, which is then compared to the sequences of interest to identify significant regions of conservation.
@graph.rdfs:label: Phylogenetic footprinting

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Simulate the folding of a protein.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein folding simulation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Predict the folding pathway(s) or non-native structural intermediates of a protein.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein folding pathway prediction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Map and model the effects of single nucleotide polymorphisms (SNPs) on protein structure(s).
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein SNP mapping

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Predict the effect of point mutation on a protein structure, in terms of strucural effects and protein folding, stability and function.
Variant functional prediction
@graph.rdfs:comment: Protein SNP mapping maps and modesl the effects of single nucleotide polymorphisms (SNPs) on protein structure(s).  Methods might predict silent or pathological mutations.
@graph.rdfs:label: Variant effect prediction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Design molecules that elicit an immune response (immunogens).
@graph.rdfs:label: Immunogen design

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Predict and optimise zinc finger protein domains for DNA/RNA binding (for example for transcription factors and nucleases).
@graph.rdfs:label: Zinc finger prediction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Calculate Km, Vmax and derived data for an enzyme reaction.
@graph.rdfs:label: Enzyme kinetics calculation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Reformat a file of data (or equivalent entity in memory).
@graph.rdfs:label: Formatting

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Test and validate the format and content of a data file.
File format validation
@graph.rdfs:label: Format validation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Visualise, plot or render (graphically) biomolecular data such as molecular sequences or structures.
@graph.rdfs:comment: This includes methods to render and visualise molecules.
@graph.rdfs:label: Visualisation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI:
Search a sequence database by sequence comparison and retrieve similar sequences.
sequences matching a given sequence motif or pattern, such as a Prosite pattern or regular expression.
@graph.rdfs:comment: This excludes direct retrieval methods (e.g. the dbfetch program).
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence database search

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Search a tertiary structure database, typically by sequence and/or structure comparison, or some other means, and retrieve structures and associated data.
@graph.rdfs:label: Structure database search

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Search a secondary protein database (of classification information) to assign a protein sequence(s) to a known protein family or group.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein secondary database search

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Screen a sequence against a motif or pattern database.
@graph.rdfs:label: Motif database search

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Search a database of sequence profiles with a query sequence.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence profile database search

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Search a database of transmembrane proteins, for example for sequence or structural similarities.
@graph.rdfs:label: Transmembrane protein database search

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Query a database and retrieve sequences with a given entry code or accession number.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence retrieval (by code)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Query a database and retrieve sequences containing a given keyword.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence retrieval (by keyword)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Search a sequence database and retrieve sequences that are similar to a query sequence.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence similarity search

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Search a sequence database and retrieve sequences matching a given sequence motif or pattern, such as a Prosite pattern or regular expression.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence database search (by motif or pattern)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Search a sequence database and retrieve sequences of a given amino acid composition.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence database search (by amino acid composition)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Search a sequence database and retrieve sequences with a specified property, typically a physicochemical or compositional property.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence database search (by property)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Search a sequence database and retrieve sequences that are similar to a query sequence using a word-based method.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Word-based methods (for example BLAST, gapped BLAST, MEGABLAST, WU-BLAST etc.) are usually quicker than alignment-based methods. They may or may not handle gaps.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence database search (by sequence using word-based methods)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Search a sequence database and retrieve sequences that are similar to a query sequence using a sequence profile-based method, or with a supplied profile as query.
@graph.rdfs:comment: This includes tools based on PSI-BLAST.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence database search (by sequence using profile-based methods)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Search a sequence database for sequences that are similar to a query sequence using a local alignment-based method.
@graph.rdfs:comment: This includes tools based on the Smith-Waterman algorithm or FASTA.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence database search (by sequence using local alignment-based methods)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Search sequence(s) or a sequence database for sequences that are similar to a query sequence using a global alignment-based method.
@graph.rdfs:comment: This includes tools based on the Needleman and Wunsch algorithm.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence database search (by sequence using global alignment-based methods)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Search a DNA database (for example a database of conserved sequence tags) for matches to Sequence-Tagged Site (STS) primer sequences.
@graph.rdfs:comment: STSs are genetic markers that are easily detected by the polymerase chain reaction (PCR) using specific primers.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence database search (by sequence for primer sequences)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Search sequence(s) or a sequence database for sequences which match a set of peptide masses, for example a peptide mass fingerprint from mass spectrometry.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence database search (by molecular weight)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Search sequence(s) or a sequence database for sequences of a given isoelectric point.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence database search (by isoelectric point)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Query a tertiary structure database and retrieve entries with a given entry code or accession number.
@graph.rdfs:label: Structure retrieval (by code)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Query a tertiary structure database and retrieve entries containing a given keyword.
@graph.rdfs:label: Structure retrieval (by keyword)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Search a tertiary structure database and retrieve structures with a sequence similar to a query sequence.
@graph.rdfs:label: Structure database search (by sequence)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Search a database of molecular structure and retrieve structures that are similar to a query structure.
@graph.rdfs:label: Structural similarity search

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Annotate a molecular sequence record with terms from a controlled vocabulary.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence annotation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Annotate a genome sequence with terms from a controlled vocabulary.
@graph.rdfs:label: Genome annotation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Generate the reverse and / or complement of a nucleotide sequence.
http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Nucleic acid sequence reverse and complement
@graph.rdfs:label: Reverse complement

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Generate a random sequence, for example, with a specific character composition.
@graph.rdfs:label: Random sequence generation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Generate digest fragments for a nucleotide sequence containing restriction sites.
Nucleic acid restriction digest
@graph.rdfs:label: Restriction digest

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: This is often followed by calculation of protein fragment masses (http://edamontology.org/operation_0398).
Cleave a protein sequence into peptide fragments (corresponding to enzymatic or chemical cleavage).
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein sequence cleavage

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Mutate a molecular sequence a specified amount or shuffle it to produce a randomised sequence with the same overall composition.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence mutation and randomisation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Mask characters in a molecular sequence (replacing those characters with a mask character).
@graph.rdfs:comment: For example, SNPs or repeats in a DNA sequence might be masked.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence masking

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Cut (remove) characters or a region from a molecular sequence.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence cutting

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Create (or remove) restriction sites in sequences, for example using silent mutations.
@graph.rdfs:label: Restriction site creation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Translate a DNA sequence into protein.
@graph.rdfs:label: DNA translation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Transcribe a nucleotide sequence into mRNA sequence(s).
@graph.rdfs:label: DNA transcription

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Calculate base frequency or word composition of a nucleotide sequence.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence composition calculation (nucleic acid)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Calculate amino acid frequency or word composition of a protein sequence.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence composition calculation (protein)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Find (and possibly render) short repetitive subsequences (repeat sequences) in (typically nucleotide) sequences.
@graph.rdfs:label: Repeat sequence detection

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Analyse repeat sequence organisation such as periodicity.
@graph.rdfs:label: Repeat sequence organisation analysis

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Analyse the hydrophobic, hydrophilic or charge properties of a protein structure.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein hydropathy calculation (from structure)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Calculate solvent accessible or buried surface areas in protein or other molecular structures.
Protein solvent accessibility calculation
@graph.rdfs:comment: Solvent accessibility might be calculated for the backbone, sidechain and total (backbone plus sidechain).
@graph.rdfs:label: Accessible surface calculation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identify clusters of hydrophobic or charged residues in a protein structure.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein hydropathy cluster calculation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Calculate whether a protein structure has an unusually large net charge (dipole moment).
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein dipole moment calculation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Calculate the molecular surface area in proteins and other macromolecules.
@graph.rdfs:label: Molecular surface calculation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identify or predict catalytic residues, active sites or other ligand-binding sites in protein structures.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein binding site prediction (from structure)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Analyse the interaction of protein with nucleic acids, e.g. RNA or DNA-binding sites, interfaces etc.
Protein-nucleic acid binding site analysis
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein-nucleic acid interaction analysis

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Decompose a structure into compact or globular fragments (protein peeling).
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein peeling

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Calculate a matrix of distance between residues (for example the C-alpha atoms) in a protein structure.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein distance matrix calculation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Calculate a residue contact map (typically all-versus-all inter-residue contacts) for a protein structure.
Protein contact map calculation
@graph.rdfs:label: Contact map calculation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Calculate clusters of contacting residues in protein structures.
@graph.rdfs:comment: This includes for example clusters of hydrophobic or charged residues, or clusters of contacting residues which have a key structural or functional role.
@graph.rdfs:label: Residue cluster calculation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identify potential hydrogen bonds between amino acids and other groups.
@graph.rdfs:comment: The output might include the atoms involved in the bond, bond geometric parameters and bond enthalpy.
@graph.rdfs:label: Hydrogen bond calculation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Calculate non-canonical atomic interactions in protein structures.
@graph.rdfs:label: Residue non-canonical interaction detection

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Calculate a Ramachandran plot of a protein structure.
@graph.rdfs:label: Ramachandran plot calculation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Validate a Ramachandran plot of a protein structure.
@graph.rdfs:label: Ramachandran plot validation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Calculate the molecular weight of a protein sequence or fragments.
Peptide mass calculation
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein molecular weight calculation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Predict extinction coefficients or optical density of a protein sequence.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein extinction coefficient calculation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Calculate pH-dependent properties from pKa calculations of a protein sequence.
Protein pH-dependent property calculation
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein pKa calculation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Hydropathy calculation on a protein sequence.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein hydropathy calculation (from sequence)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Plot a protein titration curve.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein titration curve plotting

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Calculate isoelectric point of a protein sequence.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein isoelectric point calculation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Estimate hydrogen exchange rate of a protein sequence.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein hydrogen exchange rate calculation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Calculate hydrophobic or hydrophilic / charged regions of a protein sequence.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein hydrophobic region calculation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Calculate aliphatic index (relative volume occupied by aliphatic side chains) of a protein.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein aliphatic index calculation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Calculate the hydrophobic moment of a peptide sequence and recognize amphiphilicity.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Hydrophobic moment is a peptides hydrophobicity measured for different angles of rotation.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein hydrophobic moment plotting

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Predict the stability or globularity of a protein sequence, whether it is intrinsically unfolded etc.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein globularity prediction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Predict the solubility or atomic solvation energy of a protein sequence.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein solubility prediction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Predict crystallizability of a protein sequence.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein crystallizability prediction

@graph.http://edamontology.org/deprecation_comm: (jison)Too fine-grained.
@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Detect or predict signal peptides (and typically predict subcellular localisation) of eukaryotic proteins.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein signal peptide detection (eukaryotes)

@graph.http://edamontology.org/deprecation_comm: (jison)Too fine-grained.
@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Detect or predict signal peptides (and typically predict subcellular localisation) of bacterial proteins.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein signal peptide detection (bacteria)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Predict MHC class I or class II binding peptides, promiscuous binding peptides, immunogenicity etc.
@graph.rdfs:label: MHC peptide immunogenicity prediction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Predict, recognise and identify positional features in protein sequences such as functional sites or regions and secondary structure.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Methods typically involve scanning for known motifs, patterns and regular expressions.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein feature prediction (from sequence)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Predict, recognise and identify features in nucleotide sequences such as functional sites or regions, typically by scanning for known motifs, patterns and regular expressions.
Sequence feature detection (nucleic acid)
rdfs:comment: Methods typically involve scanning for known motifs, patterns and regular expressions.

This is placeholder but does not comprehensively include all child concepts - please inspect other concepts under "Nucleic acid sequence analysis" for example "Gene prediction", for other feature detection operations.
@graph.rdfs:label: Nucleic acid feature detection

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Predict antigenic determinant sites (epitopes) in protein sequences.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Epitope mapping is commonly done during vaccine design.
@graph.rdfs:label: Epitope mapping

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Predict post-translation modification sites in protein sequences.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Methods might predict sites of methylation, N-terminal myristoylation, N-terminal acetylation, sumoylation, palmitoylation, phosphorylation, sulfation, glycosylation, glycosylphosphatidylinositol (GPI) modification sites (GPI lipid anchor signals) etc.
@graph.rdfs:label: PTM site prediction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Detect or predict signal peptides and signal peptide cleavage sites in protein sequences.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Methods might use sequence motifs and features, amino acid composition, profiles, machine-learned classifiers, etc.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein signal peptide detection

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Predict catalytic residues, active sites or other ligand-binding sites in protein sequences.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein binding site prediction (from sequence)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Predict or detect RNA and DNA-binding binding sites in protein sequences.
Zinc finger prediction
@graph.rdfs:comment: This includes methods that predict and optimise zinc finger protein domains for DNA/RNA binding (for example for transcription factors and nucleases).
@graph.rdfs:label: Nucleic acids-binding site prediction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Predict protein sites that are key to protein folding, such as possible sites of nucleation or stabilisation.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein folding site prediction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Detect or predict cleavage sites (enzymatic or chemical) in protein sequences.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein cleavage site prediction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Predict epitopes that bind to MHC class I molecules.
@graph.rdfs:label: Epitope mapping (MHC Class I)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Predict epitopes that bind to MHC class II molecules.
@graph.rdfs:label: Epitope mapping (MHC Class II)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Detect, predict and identify whole gene structure in DNA sequences. This includes protein coding regions, exon-intron structure, regulatory regions etc.
@graph.rdfs:label: Whole gene prediction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Detect, predict and identify genetic elements such as promoters, coding regions, splice sites, etc in DNA sequences.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Methods for gene prediction might be ab initio, based on phylogenetic comparisons, use motifs, sequence features, support vector machine, alignment etc.
@graph.rdfs:label: Gene component prediction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Detect or predict transposons, retrotransposons / retrotransposition signatures etc.
@graph.rdfs:label: Transposon prediction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Detect polyA signals in nucleotide sequences.
@graph.rdfs:label: PolyA signal detection

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Detect quadruplex-forming motifs in nucleotide sequences.
Quadruplex structure prediction
@graph.rdfs:comment: Quadruplex (4-stranded) structures are formed by guanine-rich regions and are implicated in various important biological processes and as therapeutic targets.
@graph.rdfs:label: Quadruplex formation site detection

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Find CpG rich regions in a nucleotide sequence or isochores in genome sequences.
@graph.rdfs:comment: An isochore is long region (> 3 KB) of DNA with very uniform GC content, in contrast to the rest of the genome. Isochores tend tends to have more genes, higher local melting or denaturation temperatures, and different flexibility. Methods might calculate fractional GC content or variation of GC content, predict methylation status of CpG islands etc. This includes methods that visualise CpG rich regions in a nucleotide sequence, for example plot isochores in a genome sequence.
@graph.rdfs:label: CpG island and isochore detection

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Find and identify restriction enzyme cleavage sites (restriction sites) in (typically) DNA sequences, for example to generate a restriction map.
@graph.rdfs:label: Restriction site recognition

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identify or predict nucleosome exclusion sequences (nucleosome free regions) in DNA.
@graph.rdfs:label: Nucleosome position prediction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identify, predict or analyse splice sites in nucleotide sequences.
Splice prediction
@graph.rdfs:comment: Methods might require a pre-mRNA or genomic DNA sequence.
@graph.rdfs:label: Splice site prediction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Predict whole gene structure using a combination of multiple methods to achieve better predictions.
@graph.rdfs:label: Integrated gene prediction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Find operons (operators, promoters and genes) in bacteria genes.
@graph.rdfs:label: Operon prediction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Predict protein-coding regions (CDS or exon) or open reading frames in nucleotide sequences.
@graph.rdfs:label: Coding region prediction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Predict selenocysteine insertion sequence (SECIS) in a DNA sequence.
Selenocysteine insertion sequence (SECIS) prediction
@graph.rdfs:comment: SECIS elements are around 60 nucleotides in length with a stem-loop structure directs the cell to translate UGA codons as selenocysteines.
@graph.rdfs:label: SECIS element prediction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: This includes comparative genomics approaches that identify common, conserved (homologous) or synonymous transcriptional regulatory elements.  For example cross-species comparison of transcription factor binding sites (TFBS). Methods might analyse co-regulated or co-expressed genes, or sets of oppositely expressed genes.
Identify or predict transcriptional regulatory motifs, patterns, elements or regions in DNA sequences.
@graph.rdfs:comment: This includes promoters, enhancers, silencers and boundary elements / insulators, regulatory protein or transcription factor binding sites etc. Methods might be specific to a particular genome and use motifs, word-based / grammatical methods, position-specific frequency matrices, discriminative pattern analysis etc.
@graph.rdfs:label: Transcriptional regulatory element prediction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Predict translation initiation sites, possibly by searching a database of sites.
@graph.rdfs:label: Translation initiation site prediction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identify or predict whole promoters or promoter elements (transcription start sites, RNA polymerase binding site, transcription factor binding sites, promoter enhancers etc) in DNA sequences.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Methods might recognize CG content, CpG islands, splice sites, polyA signals etc.
@graph.rdfs:label: Promoter prediction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identify, predict or analyse cis-regulatory elements  in DNA sequences (TATA box, Pribnow box, SOS box, CAAT box, CCAAT box, operator etc.) or in RNA sequences (e.g. riboswitches).
@graph.rdfs:comment: Cis-regulatory elements (cis-elements) regulate the expression of genes located on the same strand from which the element was transcribed. Cis-elements are found in the 5' promoter region of the gene, in an intron, or in the 3' untranslated region. Cis-elements are often binding sites of one or more trans-acting factors. They also occur in RNA sequences, e.g. a riboswitch is a region of an mRNA molecule that bind a small target molecule that regulates the gene's activity.
@graph.rdfs:label: cis-regulatory element prediction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identify, predict or analyse cis-regulatory elements (for example riboswitches) in RNA sequences.
@graph.rdfs:label: Transcriptional regulatory element prediction (RNA-cis)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identify or predict functional RNA sequences with a gene regulatory role (trans-regulatory elements) or targets.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Trans-regulatory elements regulate genes distant from the gene from which they were transcribed.
@graph.rdfs:label: trans-regulatory element prediction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identify matrix/scaffold attachment regions (MARs/SARs) in DNA sequences.
@graph.rdfs:comment: MAR/SAR sites often flank a gene or gene cluster and are found nearby cis-regulatory sequences. They might contribute to transcription regulation.
@graph.rdfs:label: S/MAR prediction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identify or predict transcription factor binding sites in DNA sequences.
@graph.rdfs:label: Transcription factor binding site prediction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identify or predict exonic splicing enhancers (ESE) in exons.
@graph.rdfs:comment: An exonic splicing enhancer (ESE) is 6-base DNA sequence motif in an exon that enhances or directs splicing of pre-mRNA or hetero-nuclear RNA (hnRNA) into mRNA.
@graph.rdfs:label: Exonic splicing enhancer prediction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Evaluate molecular sequence alignment accuracy.
Sequence alignment quality evaluation
@graph.rdfs:comment: Evaluation might be purely sequence-based or use structural information.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence alignment validation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Analyse character conservation in a molecular sequence alignment, for example to derive a consensus sequence.
Residue conservation analysis
@graph.rdfs:comment: Use this concept for methods that calculate substitution rates, estimate relative site variability, identify sites with biased properties, derive a consensus sequence, or identify highly conserved or very poorly conserved sites, regions, blocks etc.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence alignment analysis (conservation)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Analyse correlations between sites in a molecular sequence alignment.
@graph.rdfs:comment: This is typically done to identify possible covarying positions and predict contacts or structural constraints in protein structures.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence alignment analysis (site correlation)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Detects chimeric sequences (chimeras) from a sequence alignment.
Chimeric sequence detection
@graph.rdfs:comment: A chimera includes regions from two or more phylogenetically distinct sequences. They are usually artifacts of PCR and are thought to occur when a prematurely terminated amplicon reanneals to another DNA strand and is subsequently copied to completion in later PCR cycles.
@graph.rdfs:label: Chimera detection

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Detect recombination (hotspots and coldspots) and identify recombination breakpoints in a sequence alignment.
Sequence alignment analysis (recombination detection)
@graph.rdfs:comment: Tools might use a genetic algorithm, quartet-mapping, bootscanning, graphical methods, random forest model and so on.
@graph.rdfs:label: Recombination detection

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identify insertion, deletion and duplication events from a sequence alignment.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Tools might use a genetic algorithm, quartet-mapping, bootscanning, graphical methods, random forest model and so on.
@graph.rdfs:label: Indel detection

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Predict nucleosome formation potential of DNA sequences.
@graph.rdfs:label: Nucleosome formation potential prediction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Calculate a thermodynamic property of DNA or DNA/RNA, such as melting temperature, enthalpy and entropy.
@graph.rdfs:label: Nucleic acid thermodynamic property calculation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Calculate and plot a DNA or DNA/RNA melting profile.
@graph.rdfs:comment: A melting profile is used to visualise and analyse partly melted DNA conformations.
@graph.rdfs:label: Nucleic acid melting profile plotting

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Calculate and plot a DNA or DNA/RNA stitch profile.
@graph.rdfs:comment: A stitch profile represents the alternative conformations that partly melted DNA can adopt in a temperature range.
@graph.rdfs:label: Nucleic acid stitch profile plotting

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Calculate and plot a DNA or DNA/RNA melting curve.
@graph.rdfs:label: Nucleic acid melting curve plotting

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Calculate and plot a DNA or DNA/RNA probability profile.
@graph.rdfs:label: Nucleic acid probability profile plotting

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Calculate and plot a DNA or DNA/RNA temperature profile.
@graph.rdfs:label: Nucleic acid temperature profile plotting

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Calculate curvature and flexibility / stiffness of a nucleotide sequence.
@graph.rdfs:comment: This includes properties such as.
@graph.rdfs:label: Nucleic acid curvature calculation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identify or predict microRNA sequences (miRNA) and precursors or microRNA targets / binding sites in a DNA sequence.
@graph.rdfs:label: miRNA target prediction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identify or predict tRNA genes in genomic sequences (tRNA).
@graph.rdfs:label: tRNA gene prediction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Assess binding specificity of putative siRNA sequence(s), for example for a functional assay, typically with respect to designing specific siRNA sequences.
@graph.rdfs:label: siRNA binding specificity prediction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Predict secondary structure of protein sequence(s) using multiple methods to achieve better predictions.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein secondary structure prediction (integrated)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Predict helical secondary structure of protein sequences.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein secondary structure prediction (helices)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Predict turn structure (for example beta hairpin turns) of protein sequences.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein secondary structure prediction (turns)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Predict open coils, non-regular secondary structure and intrinsically disordered / unstructured regions of protein sequences.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein secondary structure prediction (coils)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Predict cysteine bonding state and disulfide bond partners in protein sequences.
@graph.rdfs:label: Disulfide bond prediction

@graph.http://edamontology.org/deprecation_comm: Not sustainable to have protein type-specific concepts.
@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Predict G protein-coupled receptors (GPCR).
@graph.rdfs:label: GPCR prediction

@graph.http://edamontology.org/deprecation_comm: Not sustainable to have protein type-specific concepts.
@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Analyse G-protein coupled receptor proteins (GPCRs).
@graph.rdfs:label: GPCR analysis

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: This includes methods that predict the folding pathway(s) or non-native structural intermediates of a protein.
Predict tertiary structure (backbone and side-chain conformation) of protein sequences.
Protein folding pathway prediction
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein structure prediction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Predict structure of DNA or RNA.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Methods might identify thermodynamically stable or evolutionarily conserved structures.
@graph.rdfs:label: Nucleic acid structure prediction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Predict tertiary structure of protein sequence(s) without homologs of known structure.
de novo structure prediction
@graph.rdfs:label: Ab initio structure prediction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Build a three-dimensional protein model based on known (for example homologs) structures.
@graph.rdfs:comment: The model might be of a whole, part or aspect of protein structure. Molecular modelling methods might use sequence-structure alignment, structural templates, molecular dynamics, energy minimisation etc.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein modelling

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Model the structure of a protein in complex with a small molecule or another macromolecule.
@graph.rdfs:comment: This includes protein-protein interactions, protein-nucleic acid, protein-ligand binding etc. Methods might predict whether the molecules are likely to bind in vivo, their conformation when bound, the strength of the interaction, possible mutations to achieve bonding and so on.
@graph.rdfs:label: Molecular docking

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Model protein backbone conformation.
Protein modelling (backbone)
@graph.rdfs:comment: Methods might require a preliminary C(alpha) trace.
@graph.rdfs:label: Backbone modelling

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Model, analyse or edit amino acid side chain conformation in protein structure, optimize side-chain packing, hydrogen bonding etc.
Protein modelling (side chains)
Rotamer likelihood prediction
rdfs:comment: Methods might use a residue rotamer library.

This includes rotamer likelihood prediction: the prediction of rotamer likelihoods for all 20 amino acid types at each position in a protein structure, where output typically includes, for each residue position, the likelihoods for the 20 amino acid types with estimated reliability of the 20 likelihoods.
@graph.rdfs:label: Side chain modelling

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Model loop conformation in protein structures.
@graph.rdfs:label: Loop modelling

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Model protein-ligand (for example protein-peptide) binding using comparative modelling or other techniques.
Ligand-binding simulation
Protein-peptide docking
rdfs:comment: Methods aim to predict the position and orientation of a ligand bound to a protein receptor or enzyme.

Virtual screening is used in drug discovery to search libraries of small molecules in order to identify those molecules which are most likely to bind to a drug target (typically a protein receptor or enzyme).
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein-ligand docking

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Predict or optimise RNA sequences (sequence pools) with likely secondary and tertiary structure for in vitro selection.
@graph.rdfs:label: RNA inverse folding

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Find single nucleotide polymorphisms (SNPs) - single nucleotide change in base positions - between sequences. Typically done for sequences from a high-throughput sequencing experiment that differ from a reference genome and which might, especially by reference to population frequency or functional data, indicate a polymorphism.
@graph.rdfs:comment: This includes functional SNPs for large-scale genotyping purposes, disease-associated non-synonymous SNPs etc.
@graph.rdfs:label: SNP detection

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Generate a physical (radiation hybrid) map of genetic markers in a DNA sequence using provided radiation hybrid (RH) scores for one or more markers.
@graph.rdfs:label: Radiation Hybrid Mapping

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Map the genetic architecture of dynamic complex traits.
@graph.rdfs:comment: This can involve characterisation of the underlying quantitative trait loci (QTLs) or nucleotides (QTNs).
@graph.rdfs:label: Functional mapping

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Infer haplotypes, either alleles at multiple loci that are transmitted together on the same chromosome, or a set of single nucleotide polymorphisms (SNPs) on a single chromatid that are statistically associated.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Haplotype inference can help in population genetic studies and the identification of complex disease genes, , and is typically based on aligned single nucleotide polymorphism (SNP) fragments. Haplotype comparison is a useful way to characterize the genetic variation between individuals. An individual's haplotype describes which nucleotide base occurs at each position for a set of common SNPs. Tools might use combinatorial functions (for example parsimony) or a likelihood function or model with optimisation such as minimum error correction (MEC) model, expectation-maximisation algorithm (EM), genetic algorithm or Markov chain Monte Carlo (MCMC).
@graph.rdfs:label: Haplotype mapping

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Calculate linkage disequilibrium; the non-random association of alleles or polymorphisms at two or more loci (not necessarily on the same chromosome).
@graph.rdfs:comment: Linkage disequilibrium is identified where a combination of alleles (or genetic markers) occurs more or less frequently in a population than expected by chance formation of haplotypes.
@graph.rdfs:label: Linkage disequilibrium calculation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Predict genetic code from analysis of codon usage data.
@graph.rdfs:label: Genetic code prediction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Render a representation of a distribution that consists of group of data points plotted on a simple scale.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Dot plots are useful when having not too many (e.g. 20) data points for each category. Example: draw a dotplot of sequence similarities identified from word-matching or character comparison.
@graph.rdfs:label: Dot plot plotting

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Align exactly two molecular sequences.
Pairwise alignment
@graph.rdfs:comment: Methods might perform one-to-one, one-to-many or many-to-many comparisons.
@graph.rdfs:label: Pairwise sequence alignment

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Align more than two molecular sequences.
Multiple alignment
@graph.rdfs:comment: This includes methods that use an existing alignment, for example to incorporate sequences into an alignment, or combine several multiple alignments into a single, improved alignment.
@graph.rdfs:label: Multiple sequence alignment

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Locally align exactly two molecular sequences.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Local alignment methods identify regions of local similarity.
@graph.rdfs:label: Pairwise sequence alignment generation (local)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Globally align exactly two molecular sequences.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Global alignment methods identify similarity across the entire length of the sequences.
@graph.rdfs:label: Pairwise sequence alignment generation (global)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Locally align two or more molecular sequences.
Smith-Waterman
@graph.rdfs:comment: Local alignment methods identify regions of local similarity.
@graph.rdfs:label: Local alignment

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Globally align two or more molecular sequences.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Global alignment methods identify similarity across the entire length of the sequences.
@graph.rdfs:label: Global alignment

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Align two or more molecular sequences with user-defined constraints.
@graph.rdfs:label: Constrained sequence alignment

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Align two or more molecular sequences using multiple methods to achieve higher quality.
@graph.rdfs:label: Consensus-based sequence alignment

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Align multiple sequences using relative gap costs calculated from neighbors in a supplied phylogenetic tree.
http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Phylogenetic tree-based multiple sequence alignment construction
@graph.rdfs:comment: This is supposed to give a more biologically meaningful alignment than standard alignments.
@graph.rdfs:label: Tree-based sequence alignment

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Align molecular secondary structure (represented as a 1D string).
@graph.rdfs:label: Secondary structure alignment generation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Align protein secondary structures.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein secondary structure alignment generation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Align RNA secondary structures.
@graph.rdfs:label: RNA secondary structure alignment

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Align (superimpose) exactly two molecular tertiary structures.
Structure alignment (pairwise)
Pairwise protein structure alignment
@graph.rdfs:label: Pairwise structure alignment

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Align (superimpose) more than two molecular tertiary structures.
Structure alignment (multiple)
Multiple protein structure alignment
@graph.rdfs:comment: This includes methods that use an existing alignment.
@graph.rdfs:label: Multiple structure alignment

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Align protein tertiary structures.
@graph.rdfs:label: Structure alignment (protein)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Align RNA tertiary structures.
@graph.rdfs:label: Structure alignment (RNA)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Locally align (superimpose) exactly two molecular tertiary structures.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Local alignment methods identify regions of local similarity, common substructures etc.
@graph.rdfs:label: Pairwise structure alignment generation (local)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Globally align (superimpose) exactly two molecular tertiary structures.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Global alignment methods identify similarity across the entire structures.
@graph.rdfs:label: Pairwise structure alignment generation (global)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Locally align (superimpose) two or more molecular tertiary structures.
Structure alignment (local)
Local protein structure alignment
@graph.rdfs:comment: Local alignment methods identify regions of local similarity, common substructures etc.
@graph.rdfs:label: Local structure alignment

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Globally align (superimpose) two or more molecular tertiary structures.
Structure alignment (global)
Global protein structure alignment
@graph.rdfs:comment: Global alignment methods identify similarity across the entire structures.
@graph.rdfs:label: Global structure alignment

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Align exactly two molecular profiles.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Methods might perform one-to-one, one-to-many or many-to-many comparisons.
@graph.rdfs:label: Profile-profile alignment (pairwise)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Align two or more molecular profiles.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence alignment generation (multiple profile)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Align exactly two molecular Structural (3D) profiles.
@graph.rdfs:label: 3D profile-to-3D profile alignment (pairwise)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Align two or more molecular 3D profiles.
@graph.rdfs:label: Structural profile alignment generation (multiple)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Search and retrieve names of or documentation on bioinformatics tools, for example by keyword or which perform a particular function.
@graph.rdfs:label: Data retrieval (tool metadata)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Search and retrieve names of or documentation on bioinformatics databases or query terms, for example by keyword.
@graph.rdfs:label: Data retrieval (database metadata)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Predict primers for large scale sequencing.
@graph.rdfs:label: PCR primer design (for large scale sequencing)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Predict primers for genotyping polymorphisms, for example single nucleotide polymorphisms (SNPs).
@graph.rdfs:label: PCR primer design (for genotyping polymorphisms)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Predict primers for gene transcription profiling.
@graph.rdfs:label: PCR primer design (for gene transcription profiling)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Predict primers that are conserved across multiple genomes or species.
@graph.rdfs:label: PCR primer design (for conserved primers)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Predict primers based on gene structure.
@graph.rdfs:label: PCR primer design (based on gene structure)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Predict primers for methylation PCRs.
@graph.rdfs:label: PCR primer design (for methylation PCRs)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Sequence assembly by combining fragments using an existing backbone sequence, typically a reference genome.
Sequence assembly (mapping assembly)
@graph.rdfs:comment: The final sequence will resemble the backbone sequence. Mapping assemblers are usually much faster and less memory intensive than de-novo assemblers.
@graph.rdfs:label: Mapping assembly

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Sequence assembly by combining fragments without the aid of a reference sequence or genome.
@graph.rdfs:comment: De-novo assemblers are much slower and more memory intensive than mapping assemblers.
@graph.rdfs:label: De-novo assembly

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The process of assembling many short DNA sequences together such thay they represent the original chromosomes from which the DNA originated.
Breakend assembly
@graph.rdfs:label: Genome assembly

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Sequence assembly for EST sequences (transcribed mRNA).
Sequence assembly (EST assembly)
@graph.rdfs:comment: Assemblers must handle (or be complicated by) alternative splicing, trans-splicing, single-nucleotide polymorphism (SNP), recoding, and post-transcriptional modification.
@graph.rdfs:label: EST assembly

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Make sequence tag to gene assignments (tag mapping) of SAGE, MPSS and SBS data.
Tag to gene assignment
@graph.rdfs:comment: Sequence tag mapping assigns experimentally obtained sequence tags to known transcripts or annotate potential virtual sequence tags in a genome.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence tag mapping

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Process (read and / or write) serial analysis of gene expression (SAGE) data.
@graph.rdfs:label: SAGE data processing

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Process (read and / or write) massively parallel signature sequencing (MPSS) data.
@graph.rdfs:label: MPSS data processing

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Process (read and / or write) sequencing by synthesis (SBS) data.
@graph.rdfs:label: SBS data processing

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Generate a heat map of expression data from e.g. microarray data.
@graph.rdfs:comment: The heat map usually uses a coloring scheme to represent expression values. They can show how quantitative measurements were influenced by experimental conditions.
@graph.rdfs:label: Heat map generation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Analyse one or more gene expression profiles, typically to interpret them in functional terms.
@graph.rdfs:label: Gene expression profile analysis

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Map an expression profile to known biological pathways, for example, to identify or reconstruct a pathway.
Pathway mapping
@graph.rdfs:label: Expression profile pathway mapping

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Assign secondary structure from protein coordinate data.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein secondary structure assignment (from coordinate data)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Assign secondary structure from circular dichroism (CD) spectroscopic data.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein secondary structure assignment (from CD data)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Assign a protein tertiary structure (3D coordinates) from raw X-ray crystallography data.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein structure assignment (from X-ray crystallographic data)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Assign a protein tertiary structure (3D coordinates) from raw NMR spectroscopy data.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein structure assignment (from NMR data)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Construct a phylogenetic tree from a specific type of data.
Phylogenetic tree generation (data centric)
@graph.rdfs:comment: Subconcepts of this concept reflect different types of data used to generate a tree, and provide an alternate axis for curation.
@graph.rdfs:label: Phylogenetic tree construction (data centric)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Construct a phylogenetic tree using a specific method.
Phylogenetic tree generation (method centric)
@graph.rdfs:comment: Subconcepts of this concept reflect different computational methods used to generate a tree, and provide an alternate axis for curation.
@graph.rdfs:label: Phylogenetic tree construction (method centric)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Phylogenetic tree construction from molecular sequences.
Phylogenetic tree generation (from molecular sequences)
@graph.rdfs:comment: Methods typically compare multiple molecular sequence and estimate evolutionary distances and relationships to infer gene families or make functional predictions.
@graph.rdfs:label: Phylogenetic tree construction (from molecular sequences)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Phylogenetic tree construction from continuous quantitative character data.
Phylogenetic tree generation (from continuous quantitative characters)
@graph.rdfs:label: Phylogenetic tree construction (from continuous quantitative characters)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Phylogenetic tree construction from gene frequency data.
Phylogenetic tree generation (from gene frequencies)
@graph.rdfs:label: Phylogenetic tree construction (from gene frequencies)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Phylogenetic tree construction from polymorphism data including microsatellites, RFLP (restriction fragment length polymorphisms), RAPD (random-amplified polymorphic DNA) and AFLP (amplified fragment length polymorphisms) data.
Phylogenetic tree generation (from polymorphism data)
@graph.rdfs:label: Phylogenetic tree construction (from polymorphism data)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Construct a phylogenetic species tree, for example, from a genome-wide sequence comparison.
@graph.rdfs:label: Species tree construction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Construct a phylogenetic tree by computing a sequence alignment and searching for the tree with the fewest number of character-state changes from the alignment.
Phylogenetic tree generation (parsimony methods)
@graph.rdfs:comment: This includes evolutionary parsimony (invariants) methods.
@graph.rdfs:label: Phylogenetic tree construction (parsimony methods)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Construct a phylogenetic tree by computing (or using precomputed) distances between sequences and searching for the tree with minimal discrepancies between pairwise distances.
Phylogenetic tree generation (minimum distance methods)
@graph.rdfs:comment: This includes neighbor joining (NJ) clustering method.
@graph.rdfs:label: Phylogenetic tree construction (minimum distance methods)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Construct a phylogenetic tree by relating sequence data to a hypothetical tree topology using a model of sequence evolution.
Phylogenetic tree generation (maximum likelihood and Bayesian methods)
@graph.rdfs:comment: Maximum likelihood methods search for a tree that maximizes a likelihood function, i.e. that is most likely given the data and model. Bayesian analysis estimate the probability of tree for branch lengths and topology, typically using a Monte Carlo algorithm.
@graph.rdfs:label: Phylogenetic tree construction (maximum likelihood and Bayesian methods)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Construct a phylogenetic tree by computing four-taxon trees (4-trees) and searching for the phylogeny that matches most closely.
Phylogenetic tree generation (quartet methods)
@graph.rdfs:label: Phylogenetic tree construction (quartet methods)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Construct a phylogenetic tree by using artificial-intelligence methods, for example genetic algorithms.
Phylogenetic tree generation (AI methods)
@graph.rdfs:label: Phylogenetic tree construction (AI methods)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identify a plausible model of DNA substitution that explains a molecular (DNA or protein) sequence alignment.
Nucleotide substitution modelling
@graph.rdfs:label: DNA substitution modelling

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Analyse the shape (topology) of a phylogenetic tree.
Phylogenetic tree analysis (shape)
@graph.rdfs:label: Phylogenetic tree topology analysis

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Apply bootstrapping or other measures to estimate confidence of a phylogenetic tree.
@graph.rdfs:label: Phylogenetic tree bootstrapping

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Construct a "gene tree" which represents the evolutionary history of the genes included in the study.  This can be used to predict families of genes and gene function based on their position in a phylogenetic tree.
Phylogenetic tree analysis (gene family prediction)
@graph.rdfs:comment: Gene trees can provide evidence for gene duplication events, as well as speciation events. Where sequences from different homologs are included in a gene tree, subsequent clustering of the orthologs can demonstrate evolutionary history of the orthologs.
@graph.rdfs:label: Gene tree construction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Analyse a phylogenetic tree to identify allele frequency distribution and change that is subject to evolutionary pressures (natural selection, genetic drift, mutation and gene flow). Identify type of natural selection (such as stabilizing, balancing or disruptive).
Phylogenetic tree analysis (natural selection)
@graph.rdfs:comment: Stabilizing/purifying (directional) selection favors a single phenotype and tends to decrease genetic diversity as a population stabilizes on a particular trait, selecting out trait extremes or deleterious mutations. In contrast, balancing selection maintain genetic polymorphisms (or multiple alleles), whereas disruptive (or diversifying) selection favors individuals at both extremes of a trait.
@graph.rdfs:label: Allele frequency distribution analysis

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Compare two or more phylogenetic trees to produce a consensus tree.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Methods typically test for topological similarity between trees using for example a congruence index.
@graph.rdfs:label: Consensus tree construction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Compare two or more phylogenetic trees to detect subtrees or supertrees.
Phylogenetic sub/super tree detection
@graph.rdfs:label: Phylogenetic sub/super tree construction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Compare two or more phylogenetic trees to calculate distances between trees.
@graph.rdfs:label: Phylogenetic tree distances calculation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Annotate a phylogenetic tree with terms from a controlled vocabulary.
@graph.rdfs:label: Phylogenetic tree annotation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Predict and optimise peptide ligands that elicit an immunological response.
@graph.rdfs:label: Immunogenicity prediction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Predict or optimise DNA to elicit (via DNA vaccination) an immunological response.
@graph.rdfs:label: DNA vaccine design

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Reformat (a file or other report of) molecular sequence(s).
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence formatting

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Reformat (a file or other report of) molecular sequence alignment(s).
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence alignment formatting

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Reformat a codon usage table.
@graph.rdfs:label: Codon usage table formatting

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Visualise, format or render a molecular sequence or sequences such as a sequence alignment, possibly with sequence features or properties shown.
Sequence rendering
Sequence alignment visualisation
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence visualisation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Visualise, format or print a molecular sequence alignment.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence alignment visualisation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Visualise, format or render sequence clusters.
Sequence cluster rendering
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence cluster visualisation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Render or visualise a phylogenetic tree.
Phylogenetic tree rendering
@graph.rdfs:label: Phylogenetic tree visualisation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Visualise RNA secondary structure, knots, pseudoknots etc.
@graph.rdfs:label: RNA secondary structure visualisation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Render and visualise protein secondary structure.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein secondary structure visualisation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Visualise or render molecular 3D structure, for example a high-quality static picture or animation.
Structure rendering
@graph.rdfs:comment: This includes visualisation of protein secondary structure such as knots, pseudoknots etc. as well as tertiary and quaternary structure.
@graph.rdfs:label: Structure visualisation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Visualise microarray or other expression data.
Expression data rendering
@graph.rdfs:label: Expression data visualisation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identify and analyse networks of protein interactions.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein interaction network visualisation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Draw or visualise a DNA map.
@graph.rdfs:label: Map drawing

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Render a sequence with motifs.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence motif rendering

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Draw or visualise restriction maps in DNA sequences.
@graph.rdfs:label: Restriction map drawing

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Draw a linear maps of DNA.
@graph.rdfs:label: DNA linear map rendering

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: DNA circular map rendering
Draw a circular maps of DNA, for example a plasmid map.
@graph.rdfs:label: Plasmid map drawing

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Visualise operon structure etc.
Operon rendering
@graph.rdfs:label: Operon drawing

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identify folding families of related RNAs.
@graph.rdfs:label: Nucleic acid folding family identification

Gene sets can be defined beforehand by biological function, chromosome locations and so on.
@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Gene set testing

Identify classes of genes or proteins that are over or under-represented in a large set of genes or proteins.  For example analysis of a set of genes corresponding to a gene expression profile, annotated with Gene Ontology (GO) concepts, where eventual over-/under-representation of certain GO concept within the studied set of genes is revealed.
Gene set analysis
rdfs:comment: The Gene Ontology (GO) is typically used, the input is a set of Gene IDs, and the output of the analysis is typically a ranked list of GO concepts, each associated with a p-value.

"Gene set analysis" (often used interchangeably or in an overlapping sense with "gene-set enrichment analysis") refers to the functional analysis (term enrichment) of a differentially expressed set of genes, rather than all genes analysed.
@graph.rdfs:label: Gene-set enrichment analysis

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Cut (remove) the end from a molecular sequence.
Trimming
@graph.rdfs:comment:
This includes

ennd trimming
Trim sequences (typically from an automated DNA sequencer) to remove misleading ends.
For example trim polyA tails, introns and primer sequence flanking the sequence of amplified exons, or other unwanted sequence.

trimming to a reference sequence, 
Trim sequences (typically from an automated DNA sequencer) to remove the sequence ends that extend beyond an assembled reference sequence.

vector trimming
Trim sequences (typically from an automated DNA sequencer) to remove sequence-specific end regions, typically contamination from vector sequences.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence trimming

@graph.rdfs:label: Genotyping

@graph.rdfs:comment: Genetic variation annotation provides contextual interpretation of coding SNP consequences in transcripts. It allows comparisons to be made between variation data in different populations or strains for the same transcript.
@graph.rdfs:label: Genetic variation analysis

@graph.rdfs:comment: The purpose of read mapping is to identify the location of sequenced fragments within a reference genome and assumes that there is, in fact, at least local similarity between the fragment and reference sequences.

Split-read mapping
@graph.rdfs:label: Split read mapping

@graph.http://edamontology.org/deprecation_comm: "Polymorphism detection" and "Variant calling" are essentially the same thing - keeping the later as a more prevalent term nowadays.
@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Detect mutations in multiple DNA sequences, for example, from the alignment and comparison of the fluorescent traces produced by DNA sequencing hardware.

@graph.rdfs:label: Chromatogram visualisation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Determine cytosine methylation status of specific positions in a nucleic acid sequences.

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Analysing the DNA methylation of specific genes or regions of interest.

The Burrows-Wheeler Transform (BWT) is a permutation of the genome based on a suffix array algorithm.  A suffix array consists of the lexicographically sorted list of suffixes of a genome.
@graph.rdfs:label: Genome indexing

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Generate an index of a genome sequence using the Burrows-Wheeler algorithm.
@graph.rdfs:comment: The Burrows-Wheeler Transform (BWT) is a permutation of the genome based on a suffix array algorithm.

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Generate an index of a genome sequence using a suffix arrays algorithm.
@graph.rdfs:comment: A suffix array consists of the lexicographically sorted list of suffixes of a genome.
@graph.rdfs:label: Genome indexing (suffix arrays)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Analyse one or more spectra from mass spectrometry (or other) experiments.
