@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identify peaks in a spectrum from a mass spectrometry, NMR, or some other spectrum-generating experiment.
@graph.rdfs:label: Peak detection

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Link together a non-contiguous series of genomic sequences into a scaffold, consisting of sequences separated by gaps of known length.  The sequences that are linked are typically typically contigs; contiguous sequences corresponding to read overlaps.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Scaffold may be positioned along a chromosome physical map to create a "golden path".
@graph.rdfs:label: Scaffolding

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Fill the gaps in a sequence assembly (scaffold) by merging in additional sequences.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Different techniques are used to generate gap sequences to connect contigs, depending on the size of the gap. For small (5-20kb) gaps, PCR amplification and sequencing is used.  For large (>20kb) gaps, fragments are cloned (e.g. in BAC (Bacterial artificial chromosomes) vectors) and then sequenced.
@graph.rdfs:label: Scaffold gap completion

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Raw sequence data quality control.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Analyse raw sequence data from a sequencing pipeline and identify (and possiby fix) problems.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequencing quality control

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Pre-process sequence reads to ensure (or improve) quality and reliability.
Sequence read pre-processing
@graph.rdfs:comment: For example process paired end reads to trim low quality ends remove short sequences, identify sequence inserts, detect chimeric reads, or remove low quality sequnces including vector, adaptor, low complexity and contaminant sequences. Sequences might come from genomic DNA library, EST libraries, SSH library and so on.
@graph.rdfs:label: Read pre-processing

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Estimate the frequencies of different species from analysis of the molecular sequences, typically of DNA recovered from environmental samples.
@graph.rdfs:label: Species frequency estimation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identify putative protein-binding regions in a genome sequence from analysis of Chip-sequencing data or ChIP-on-chip data.
Protein binding peak detection
Peak-pair calling
@graph.rdfs:comment: Chip-sequencing combines chromatin immunoprecipitation (ChIP) with massively parallel DNA sequencing to generate a set of reads, which are aligned to a genome sequence.  The enriched areas contain the binding sites of DNA-associated proteins.  For example, a transcription factor binding site. ChIP-on-chip in contrast combines chromatin immunoprecipitation ('ChIP') with microarray ('chip').  "Peak-pair calling" is similar to "Peak calling" in the context of ChIP-exo.
@graph.rdfs:label: Peak calling

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identify from molecular sequence analysis (typically from analysis of microarray or RNA-seq data) genes whose expression levels are significantly different between two sample groups.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Differential gene expression analysis is used, for example, to identify which genes are up-regulated (increased expression) or down-regulated (decreased expression) between a group treated with a drug and a control groups.
@graph.rdfs:label: Differential gene expression analysis

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Analyse gene expression patterns (typically from DNA microarray datasets) to identify sets of genes that are associated with a specific trait, condition, clinical outcome etc.
@graph.rdfs:label: Gene set testing

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Classify variants based on their potential effect on genes, especially functional effects on the expressed proteins.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Variants are typically classified by their position (intronic, exonic, etc.) in a gene transcript and (for variants in coding exons) by their effect on the protein sequence (synonymous, non-synonymous, frameshifting, etc.)
@graph.rdfs:label: Variant classification

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identify biologically interesting variants by prioritizing individual variants, for example, homozygous variants absent in control genomes.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Variant prioritisation can be used for example to produce a list of variants responsible for 'knocking out' genes in specific genomes. Methods amino acid substitution, aggregative approaches, probabilistic approach, inheritance and unified likelihood-frameworks.
@graph.rdfs:label: Variant prioritisation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Detect, identify and map mutations, such as single nucleotide polymorphisms, short indels and structural variants, in multiple DNA sequences. Typically the alignment and comparison of the fluorescent traces produced by DNA sequencing hardware, to study genomic alterations.
Variant mapping
rdfs:comment: Methods often utilise a database of aligned reads.
Somatic variant calling is the detection of variations established in somatic cells and hence not inherited as a germ line variant.
Variant detection
@graph.rdfs:label: Variant calling

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Detect large regions in a genome subject to copy-number variation, or other structural variations in genome(s).
Structural variation discovery
@graph.rdfs:comment: Methods might involve analysis of whole-genome array comparative genome hybridisation or single-nucleotide polymorphism arrays, paired-end mapping of sequencing data, or from analysis of short reads from new sequencing technologies.
@graph.rdfs:label: Structural variation detection

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Analyse sequencing data from experiments aiming to selectively sequence the coding regions of the genome.
Exome sequence analysis
@graph.rdfs:label: Exome assembly

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Analyse mapping density (read depth) of (typically) short reads from sequencing platforms, for example, to detect deletions and duplications.
@graph.rdfs:label: Read depth analysis

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Combine classical quantitative trait loci (QTL) analysis with gene expression profiling, for example, to describe describe cis- and trans-controlling elements for the expression of phenotype associated genes.
http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Gene expression quantitative trait loci profiling
@graph.rdfs:label: Gene expression QTL analysis

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Estimate the number of copies of loci of particular gene(s) in DNA sequences typically from gene-expression profiling technology based on microarray hybridisation-based experiments. For example, estimate copy number (or marker dosage) of a dominant marker in samples from polyploid plant cells or tissues, or chromosomal gains and losses in tumors.
Transcript copy number estimation
@graph.rdfs:comment: Methods typically implement some statistical model for hypothesis testing, and methods estimate total copy number, i.e. do not distinguish the two inherited chromosomes quantities (specific copy number).
@graph.rdfs:label: Copy number estimation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Adapter removal
Remove forward and/or reverse primers from nucleic acid sequences (typically PCR products).
@graph.rdfs:label: Primer removal

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Infer a transcriptome sequence by analysis of short sequence reads.
@graph.rdfs:label: Transcriptome assembly

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Infer a transcriptome sequence without the aid of a reference genome, i.e. by comparing short sequences (reads) to each other.
de novo transcriptome assembly
@graph.rdfs:label: Transcriptome assembly (de novo)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Infer a transcriptome sequence by mapping short reads to a reference genome.
@graph.rdfs:label: Transcriptome assembly (mapping)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Convert one set of sequence coordinates to another, e.g. convert coordinates of one assembly to another, cDNA to genomic, CDS to genomic, protein translation to genomic etc.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence coordinate conversion

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Calculate similarity between 2 or more documents.
@graph.rdfs:label: Document similarity calculation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Cluster (group) documents on the basis of their calculated similarity.
@graph.rdfs:label: Document clustering

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Recognise named entities, ontology concepts, tags, events, and dictionary terms within documents.
@graph.rdfs:label: Named-entity and concept recognition

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Map data identifiers to one another for example to establish a link between two biological databases for the purposes of data integration.
@graph.rdfs:comment: The mapping can be achieved by comparing identifier values or some other means, e.g. exact matches to a provided sequence.
@graph.rdfs:label: ID mapping

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Process data in such a way that makes it hard to trace to the person which the data concerns.
Data anonymisation
@graph.rdfs:label: Anonymisation

@graph.http://edamontology.org/deprecation_comm: (jison)Too fine-grained, the operation (Data retrieval) hasn't changed, just what is retrieved.
@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Search for and retrieve a data identifier of some kind, e.g. a database entry accession.
@graph.rdfs:label: ID retrieval

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Generate a checksum of a molecular sequence.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence checksum generation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Construct a bibliography from the scientific literature.
Bibliography construction
@graph.rdfs:label: Bibliography generation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Predict the structure of a multi-subunit protein and particularly how the subunits fit together.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein quaternary structure prediction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Analyse the surface properties of proteins or other macromolecules, including surface accessible pockets, interior inaccessible cavities etc.
@graph.rdfs:label: Molecular surface analysis

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Compare two or more ontologies, e.g. identify differences.
@graph.rdfs:label: Ontology comparison

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Compare two or more ontologies, e.g. identify differences.
@graph.rdfs:label: Ontology comparison

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Recognition of which format the given data is in.
@graph.rdfs:comment: 'Format recognition' is not a bioinformatics-specific operation, but of great relevance in bioinformatics. Should be removed from EDAM if/when captured satisfactorily in a suitable domain-generic ontology.
@graph.rdfs:label: Format detection

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Split a file containing multiple data items into many files, each containing one item
File splitting
@graph.rdfs:label: Splitting

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Construct some data entity.
Construction
@graph.rdfs:comment: For non-analytical operations, see the 'Processing' branch.
@graph.rdfs:label: Generation

@graph.http://edamontology.org/deprecation_comm: (jison)This is a distinction made on basis of input; all features exist can be mapped to a sequence so this isn't needed.
@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Predict, recognise and identify functional or other key sites within nucleic acid sequences, typically by scanning for known motifs, patterns and regular expressions.
@graph.rdfs:label: Nucleic acid sequence feature detection

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Deposit some data in a database or some other type of repository or software system.
@graph.rdfs:comment: For non-analytical operations, see the 'Processing' branch.
@graph.rdfs:label: Deposition

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Group together some data entities on the basis of similarities such that entities in the same group (cluster) are more similar to each other than to those in other groups (clusters).
@graph.rdfs:label: Clustering

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Construct some entity (typically a molecule sequence) from component pieces.
@graph.rdfs:label: Assembly

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Convert a data set from one form to another.
@graph.rdfs:label: Conversion

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Standardize or normalize data by some statistical method.
@graph.rdfs:comment: In the simplest normalisation means adjusting values measured on different scales to a common scale (often between 0.0 and 1.0), but can refer to more sophisticated adjustment whereby entire probability distributions of adjusted values are brought into alignment. Standardisation typically refers to an operation whereby a range of values are standardised to measure how many standard deviations a value is from its mean.
@graph.rdfs:label: Standardisation and normalisation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Combine multiple files or data items into a single file or object.
@graph.rdfs:label: Aggregation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Compare two or more scientific articles.
@graph.rdfs:label: Article comparison

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Mathematical determination of the value of something, typically a properly of a  molecule.
@graph.rdfs:label: Calculation

@graph.http://edamontology.org/deprecation_comm: Notions of pathway and network were mixed up, EDAM 1.24 disentangles them.
@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Predict a molecular pathway or network.
@graph.rdfs:label: Pathway or network prediction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The process of assembling many short DNA sequences together such thay they represent the original chromosomes from which the DNA originated.
@graph.rdfs:label: Genome assembly

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Generate a graph, or other visual representation, of data, showing the relationship between two or more variables.
@graph.rdfs:label: Plotting

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Image processing
The analysis of a image (typically a digital image) of some type in order to extract information from it.
@graph.rdfs:label: Image analysis

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Analysis of data from a diffraction experiment.
@graph.rdfs:label: Diffraction data analysis

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Analysis of cell migration images in order to study cell migration, typically in order to study the processes that play a role in the disease progression.
@graph.rdfs:label: Cell migration analysis

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Processing of diffraction data into a corrected, ordered, and simplified form.
@graph.rdfs:label: Diffraction data reduction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Measurement of neurites; projections (axons or dendrites) from the cell body of a neuron, from analysis of neuron images.
@graph.rdfs:label: Neurite measurement

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The evaluation of diffraction intensities and integration of diffraction maxima from a diffraction experiment.
@graph.rdfs:label: Diffraction data integration

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Phase a macromolecular crystal structure, for example by using molecular replacement or experimental phasing methods.
@graph.rdfs:label: Phasing

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A technique used to construct an atomic model of an unknown structure from diffraction data, based upon an atomic model of a known structure, either a related protein or the same protein from a different crystal form.
@graph.rdfs:comment: The technique solves the phase problem, i.e. retrieve information concern phases of the structure.
@graph.rdfs:label: Molecular replacement

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A method used to refine a structure by moving the whole molecule or parts of it as a rigid unit, rather than moving individual atoms.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Rigid body refinement usually follows molecular replacement in the assignment of a structure from diffraction data.
@graph.rdfs:label: Rigid body refinement

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An image processing technique that combines and analyze multiple images of a particulate sample, in order to produce an image with clearer features that are more easily interpreted.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Single particle analysis is used to improve the information that can be obtained by relatively low resolution techniques, , e.g. an image of a protein or virus from transmission electron microscopy (TEM).
@graph.rdfs:label: Single particle analysis

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Compare (align and classify) multiple particle images from a micrograph in order to produce a representative image of the particle.
@graph.rdfs:comment: A micrograph can include particles in multiple different orientations and/or conformations. Particles are compared and organised into sets based on their similarity. Typically iterations of classification and alignment and are performed to optimise the final 3D EM map.
@graph.rdfs:label: Single particle alignment and classification

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Clustering of molecular sequences on the basis of their function, typically using information from an ontology of gene function, or some other measure of functional phenotype.
Functional sequence clustering
@graph.rdfs:label: Functional clustering

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Classifiication (typically of molecular sequences) by assignment to some taxonomic hierarchy.
Taxonomy assignment
Taxonomic profiling
@graph.rdfs:label: Taxonomic classification

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The prediction of the degree of pathogenicity of a microorganism from analysis of molecular sequences.
Pathogenicity prediction
@graph.rdfs:label: Virulence prediction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Analyse the correlation patterns among features/molecules across across a variety of experiments, samples etc.
Co-expression analysis
@graph.rdfs:label: Expression correlation analysis

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identify a correlation, i.e. a statistical relationship between two random variables or two sets of data.
@graph.rdfs:label: Correlation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Compute the covariance model for (a family of) RNA secondary structures.
@graph.rdfs:label: RNA structure covariance model generation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Predict RNA secondary structure by analysis, e.g. probabilistic analysis, of the shape of RNA folds.
@graph.rdfs:label: RNA secondary structure prediction (shape-based)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Prediction of nucleic-acid folding using sequence alignments as a source of data.
@graph.rdfs:label: Nucleic acid folding prediction (alignment-based)

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Count k-mers (substrings of length k) in DNA sequence data.
@graph.rdfs:comment: k-mer counting is used in genome and transcriptome assembly, metagenomic sequencing, and for error correction of sequence reads.
@graph.rdfs:label: k-mer counting

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Reconstructing the inner node labels of a phylogenetic tree from its leafes.
Phylogenetic tree reconstruction
@graph.rdfs:comment: Note that this is somewhat different from simply analysing an existing tree or constructing a completely new one.
@graph.rdfs:label: Phylogenetic reconstruction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Generate some data from a choosen probibalistic model, possibly to evaluate algorithms.
@graph.rdfs:label: Probabilistic data generation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Generate sequences from some probabilistic model, e.g. a model that simulates evolution.
@graph.rdfs:label: Probabilistic sequence generation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identify or predict causes for antibiotic resistance from molecular sequence analysis.
@graph.rdfs:label: Antimicrobial resistance prediction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Analysis of a set of objects, such as genes, annotated with given categories, where eventual over-/under-representation of certain categories within the studied set of objects is revealed.
Functional enrichment
@graph.rdfs:comment: Categories from a relevant ontology can be used. The input is typically a set of genes or other biological objects, possibly represented by their identifiers, and the output of the analysis is typically a ranked list of categories, each associated with a statistical metric of over-/under-representation within the studied data.
@graph.rdfs:label: Enrichment analysis

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Analyse a dataset with respect to concepts from an ontology of chemical structure, leveraging chemical similarity information.
Chemical class enrichment
@graph.rdfs:label: Chemical similarity enrichment

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Plot an incident curve such as a survival curve, death curve, mortality curve.
@graph.rdfs:label: Incident curve plotting

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identify and map patterns of genomic variations.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Methods often utilise a database of aligned reads.
@graph.rdfs:label: Variant pattern analysis

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Model some biological system using mathematical techniques including  dynamical systems, statistical models, differential equations, and game theoretic models.
@graph.rdfs:label: Mathematical modelling

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Visualise images resulting from various types of microscopy.
@graph.rdfs:label: Microscope image visualisation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Annotate an image of some sort, typically with terms from a controlled vocabulary.
@graph.rdfs:label: Image annotation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Replace missing data with substituted values, usually by using some statistical or other mathematical approach.
Data imputation
@graph.rdfs:label: Imputation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Visualise, format or render data from an ontology, typically a tree of terms.
Ontology browsing
@graph.rdfs:label: Ontology visualisation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A method for making numerical assessments about the maximum percent of time that a conformer of a flexible macromolecule can exist and still be compatible with the experimental data.
@graph.rdfs:label: Maximum occurence analysis

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Compare the models or schemas used by two or more databases, or any other general comparison of databases rather than a detailed comparison of the entries themselves.
@graph.rdfs:label: Database comparison

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Simulate the bevaviour of a biological pathway or network.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Notions of pathway and network were mixed up, EDAM 1.24 disentangles them.
@graph.rdfs:label: Network simulation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Analyze read counts from RNA-seq experiments.
@graph.rdfs:label: RNA-seq read count analysis

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identify and remove redudancy from a set of small molecule structures.
@graph.rdfs:label: Chemical redundancy removal

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Analyze time series data from an RNA-seq experiment.
@graph.rdfs:label: RNA-seq time series data analysis

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Simulate gene expression data, e.g. for purposes of benchmarking.
@graph.rdfs:label: Simulated gene expression data generation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identify semantic relations among entities and concepts within a text, using text mining techniques.
@graph.rdfs:label: Relation extraction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Re-adjust the output of mass spectrometry experiments with shifted ppm values.
@graph.rdfs:label: Mass spectra calibration

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Align multiple data sets using information from chromatography and/or peptide identification, from mass spectrometry experiments.
@graph.rdfs:label: Chromatographic alignment

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The removal of isotope peaks in a spectrum, to represent the fragment ion as one data point.
Deconvolution
@graph.rdfs:comment: Deisotoping is commonly done to reduce complexity, and done in conjunction with the charge state deconvolution.
@graph.rdfs:label: Deisotoping

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Technique for determining the amount of proteins in a sample.
Protein quantitation
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein quantification

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Determination of peptide sequence from mass spectrum.
Peptide-spectrum-matching
@graph.rdfs:label: Peptide identification

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Calculate the isotope distribution of a given chemical species.
@graph.rdfs:label: Isotopic distributions calculation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Prediction of retention time in a mass spectrometry experiment based on compositional and structural properties of the separated species.
Retention time calculation
@graph.rdfs:label: Retention time prediction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Quantification without the use of chemical tags.
@graph.rdfs:label: Label-free quantification

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Quantification based on the use of chemical tags.
@graph.rdfs:label: Labeled quantification

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Quantification by Selected/multiple Reaction Monitoring workflow (XIC quantitation of precursor / fragment mass pair).
@graph.rdfs:label: MRM/SRM

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Calculate number of identified MS2 spectra as approximation of peptide / protein quantity.
@graph.rdfs:label: Spectral counting

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Quantification analysis using stable isotope labeling by amino acids in cell culture.
@graph.rdfs:label: SILAC

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Quantification analysis using the AB SCIEX iTRAQ isobaric labelling workflow, wherein 2-8 reporter ions are measured in MS2 spectra near 114 m/z.
@graph.rdfs:label: iTRAQ

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Quantification analysis using labeling based on 18O-enriched H2O.
@graph.rdfs:label: 18O labeling

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Quantification analysis using the Thermo Fisher tandem mass tag labelling workflow.
@graph.rdfs:label: TMT-tag

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Quantification analysis using chemical labeling by stable isotope dimethylation
@graph.rdfs:label: Dimethyl

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Peptide sequence tags are used as piece of information about a peptide obtained by tandem mass spectrometry.
@graph.rdfs:label: Tag-based peptide identification

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Analytical process that derives a peptideâs amino acid sequence from its tandem mass spectrum (MS/MS) without the assistance of a sequence database.
@graph.rdfs:label: de Novo sequencing

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identification of post-translational modifications (PTMs) of peptides/proteins in mass spectrum.
@graph.rdfs:label: PTM identification

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Determination of best matches between MS/MS spectrum and a database of protein or nucleic acid sequences.
@graph.rdfs:label: Peptide database search

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Peptide database search for identification of known and unknown PTMs looking for mass difference mismatches.
@graph.rdfs:label: Blind peptide database search

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Statistical estimation of false discovery rate from score distribution for peptide-spectrum-matches, following a peptide database search.
@graph.rdfs:label: Validation of peptide-spectrum matches

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Validation of peptide-spectrum matches

Statistical estimation of false discovery rate from score distribution for peptide-spectrum-matches, following a peptide database search, and by comparison to search results with a database containing incorrect information.
@graph.rdfs:label: Target-Decoy

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Analyse data in order to deduce properties of an underlying distribution or population.
Empirical Bayes
@graph.rdfs:label: Statistical inference

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A statistical calculation to estimate the relationships among variables.
Regression
@graph.rdfs:label: Regression analysis

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Model a metabolic network.  This can include 1) reconstruction to break down a metabolic pathways into reactions, enzymes, and other relevant information, and compilation of this into a mathematical model and 2) simulations of metabolism based on the model.
@graph.rdfs:comment: The terms and synyonyms here reflect that for practical intents and purposes, "pathway" and "network" can be treated the same.
@graph.rdfs:label: Metabolic network modelling

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Predict the effect or function of an individual single nucleotide polymorphism (SNP).
@graph.rdfs:label: SNP annotation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Prediction of genes or gene components from first principles, i.e. without reference to existing genes.
Gene prediction (ab-initio)
@graph.rdfs:label: Ab-initio gene prediction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Prediction of genes or gene components by reference to homologous genes.
@graph.rdfs:label: Homology-based gene prediction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Construction of a statistical model, or a set of assumptions around some observed data, usually by describing a set of probability distributions which approximate the distribution of data.
@graph.rdfs:label: Statistical modelling

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Compare two or more molecular surfaces.
@graph.rdfs:label: Molecular surface comparison

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Annotate one or more sequences with functional information, such as cellular processes or metaobolic pathways, by reference to a controlled vocabulary - invariably the Gene Ontology (GO).
Sequence functional annotation
@graph.rdfs:label: Gene functional annotation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Variant filtering is used to eliminate false positive variants based for example on base calling quality, strand and position information, and mapping info.
@graph.rdfs:label: Variant filtering

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identify binding sites in nucleic acid sequences that are statistically significantly differentially bound between sample groups.
@graph.rdfs:label: Differential binding analysis

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Analyze data from RNA-seq experiments.
@graph.rdfs:label: RNA-Seq analysis

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Visualise, format or render a mass spectrum.
@graph.rdfs:label: Mass spectrum visualisation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Filter a set of files or data items according to some property.
@graph.rdfs:label: Filtering

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identification of the best reference for mapping for a specific dataset from a list of potential references, when performing genetic variation analysis.
@graph.rdfs:label: Reference identification

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Label-free quantification by integration of ion current (ion counting).
Ion current integration
@graph.rdfs:label: Ion counting

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Chemical tagging free amino groups of intact proteins with stable isotopes.
ICPL
@graph.rdfs:label: Isotope-coded protein label

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Labeling all proteins and (possibly) all amino acids using C-13 or N-15 enriched grown medium or feed.
@graph.rdfs:comment: This includes N-15 metabolic labeling (labeling all proteins and (possibly) all amino acids using N-15 enriched grown medium or feed) and C-13 metabolic labeling (labeling all proteins and (possibly) all amino acids using C-13 enriched grown medium or feed).
@graph.rdfs:label: Metabolic labeling

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Construction of a single sequence assembly of all reads from different samples, typically as part of a comparative metagenomic analysis.
Sequence assembly (cross-assembly)
@graph.rdfs:label: Cross-assembly

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The comparison of samples from a metagenomics study, for example, by comparison of metagenome shotgun reads or assembled contig sequences, by comparison of functional profiles, or some other method.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sample comparison

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Differential protein analysis
The analysis, using proteomics techniques, to identify proteins whose encoding genes are differentially expressed under a given experimental setup.
@graph.rdfs:label: Differential protein expression analysis

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The analysis, using any of diverse techniques, to identify genes that are differentially expressed under a given experimental setup.
@graph.rdfs:label: Differential gene expression analysis

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Visualise, format or render data arising from an analysis of multiple samples from a metagenomics/community experiment.
@graph.rdfs:label: Multiple sample visualisation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The extrapolation of empirical characteristics of individuals or populations, backwards in time, to their common ancestors.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Ancestral reconstruction is often used to recover possible ancestral character states of ancient, extinct organisms.
@graph.rdfs:label: Ancestral reconstruction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Site localisation of post-translational modifications in peptide or protein mass spectra.
@graph.rdfs:label: PTM localisation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Operations concerning the handling and use of other tools.
Endpoint management
@graph.rdfs:label: Service management

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An operation supporting the browsing or discovery of other tools and services.
@graph.rdfs:label: Service discovery

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An operation supporting the aggregation of other services (at least two) into a funtional unit, for the automation of some task.
@graph.rdfs:label: Service composition

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An operation supporting the calling (invocation) of other tools and services.
@graph.rdfs:label: Service invocation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A data mining method typically used for studying biological networks based on pairwise correlations between variables.
@graph.rdfs:label: Weighted correlation network analysis

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identification of protein, for example from one or more peptide identifications by tandem mass spectrometry.
Protein inference
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein identification

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Text annotation is the operation of adding notes, data and metadata, recognised entities and concepts, and their relations to a text (such as a scientific article).
@graph.rdfs:label: Text annotation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A method whereby data on several variants are "collapsed" into a single covariate based on regions such as genes.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Genome-wide association studies (GWAS) analyse a genome-wide set of genetic variants in different individuals to see if any variant is associated with a trait. Traditional association techniques can lack the power to detect the significance of rare variants individually, or measure their compound effect (rare variant burden).  "Collapsing methods" were developed to overcome these problems.
@graph.rdfs:label: Collapsing methods

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: miRNA analysis
The analysis of microRNAs (miRNAs) : short, highly conserved small noncoding RNA molecules that are naturally occurring plant and animal genomes.
miRNA expression profiling
@graph.rdfs:label: miRNA expression analysis

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Counting and summarising the number of short sequence reads that map to genomic features.
@graph.rdfs:label: Read summarisation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A technique whereby molecules with desired properties and function are isolated from libraries of random molecules, through iterative cycles of selection, amplification, and mutagenesis.
@graph.rdfs:label: In vitro selection

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The calculation of species richness for a number of individual samples, based on plots of the number of species as a function of the number of samples (rarefaction curves).
Species richness assessment
@graph.rdfs:label: Rarefaction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An operation which groups reads or contigs and assigns them to operational taxonomic units.
Binning
@graph.rdfs:comment: Binning methods use one or a combination of compositional features or sequence similarity.
@graph.rdfs:label: Read binning

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Counting and measuring experimentally determined observations into quantities.
Quantitation
@graph.rdfs:label: Quantification

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Quantification of data arising from RNA-Seq high-throughput sequencing, typically the quantification of transcript abundances durnig transcriptome analysis in a gene expression study.
RNA-Seq quantitation
@graph.rdfs:label: RNA-Seq quantification

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Match experimentally measured mass spectrum to a spectrum in a spectral library or database.
@graph.rdfs:label: Spectral library search

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Sort a set of files or data items according to some property.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sorting

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Metabolite identification
Mass spectra identification of compounds that are produced by living systems. Including polyketides, terpenoids, phenylpropanoids, alkaloids and antibiotics.
@graph.rdfs:label: Natural product identification

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identify and assess specific genes or regulatory regions of interest that are differentially methylated.
Differentially-methylated region identification
@graph.rdfs:label: DMR identification

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Genotyping of multiple loci, typically characterizing microbial species isolates using internal fragments of multiple housekeeping genes.
MLST
@graph.rdfs:label: Multilocus sequence typing

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Calculate a theoretical mass spectrometry spectra for given sequences.
Spectrum prediction
@graph.rdfs:label: Spectrum calculation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: 3D visualization of a molecular trajectory.
@graph.rdfs:label: Trajectory visualization

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Compute Essential Dynamics (ED) on a simulation trajectory: an analysis of molecule dynamics using PCA (Principal Component Analysis) applied to the atomic positional fluctuations.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Principal Component Analysis (PCA) is a multivariate statistical analysis to obtain collective variables and reduce the dimensionality of the system.
@graph.rdfs:label: Essential dynamics

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Obtain force field parameters (charge, bonds, dihedrals, etc.) from a molecule, to be used in molecular simulations
@graph.rdfs:label: Forcefield parameterisation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Analyse DNA sequences in order to determine an individual's DNA characteristics, for example in criminal forensics, parentage testing and so on.
DNA fingerprinting
@graph.rdfs:label: DNA profiling

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Predict or detect active sites in proteins; the region of an enzyme which binds a substrate bind and catalyses a reaction.
Active site detection
@graph.rdfs:label: Active site prediction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Predict or detect ligand-binding sites in proteins; a region of a protein which reversibly binds a ligand for some biochemical purpose, such as transport or regulation of protein function.
Ligand-binding site detection
@graph.rdfs:label: Ligand-binding site prediction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Predict or detect metal ion-binding sites in proteins.
@graph.rdfs:label: Metal-binding site prediction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Model or simulate protein-protein binding using comparative modelling or other techniques.
Protein docking
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein-protein docking

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Predict DNA-binding proteins.
@graph.rdfs:label: DNA-binding protein prediction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Predict DNA-binding proteins.
@graph.rdfs:label: RNA-binding protein prediction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Predict or detect RNA-binding sites in protein sequences.
@graph.rdfs:label: RNA binding site prediction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Predict or detect DNA-binding sites in protein sequences.
DNA binding site detection
@graph.rdfs:label: DNA binding site prediction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Identify or predict intrinsically disordered regions in proteins.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein disorder prediction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Extract structured information from unstructured ("free") or semi-structured textual documents.
IE
@graph.rdfs:label: Information extraction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Retrieve resources from information systems matching a specific information need.
@graph.rdfs:label: Information retrieval

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Detects chimeric sequences (chimeras) from a sequence alignment.
@graph.rdfs:label: Genome analysis

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The determination of cytosine methylation status of specific positions in a nucleic acid sequences (usually reads from a bisulfite sequencing experiment).
@graph.rdfs:label: Methylation calling

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The identification of changes in DNA sequence or chromosome structure, usually in the context of diagnostic tests for disease, or to study ancestry or phylogeny.
Genetic testing
@graph.rdfs:comment: This can include indirect methods which reveal the results of genetic changes, such as RNA analysis to indicate gene expression, or biochemical analysis to identify expressed proteins.
@graph.rdfs:label: DNA testing

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The processing of reads from high-throughput sequencing machines.
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence read processing

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI:
Laboratory experiment to identify the differences between a specific genome (of an individual) and a reference genome (developed typically from many thousands of individuals).

WGS re-sequencing is used as golden standard to detect variations compared to a given reference genome, including small variants (SNP and InDels) as well as larger genome re-organisations (CNVs, translocations, etc.).

ows re-sequencing of complete genomes of any given organism with high resolution and high accuracy.
Resequencing
Whole_genome_sequencing
rdfs:comment: Amplicon sequencing is the ultra-deep sequencing of PCR products (amplicons), usually for the purpose of efficient genetic variant identification and characterisation in specific genomic regions.
Ultra-deep sequencing
@graph.rdfs:label: Genome resequencing

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Render (visualise) a network - typically a biological network of some sort.
Network rendering
@graph.rdfs:label: Network visualisation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Render (visualise) a biological pathway.
Pathway rendering
@graph.rdfs:label: Pathway visualisation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Generate, process or analyse a biological network.
Biological network analysis
@graph.rdfs:label: Network analysis

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Generate, process or analyse a biological pathway.
Biological pathway analysis
@graph.rdfs:label: Pathway analysis

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Predict a metabolic pathway.
@graph.rdfs:label: Metabolic pathway prediction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Interdisciplinary science focused on extracting information from chemical systems by data analytical approaches, for example multivariate statistics, applied mathematics, and computer science.
Chemometrics
@graph.rdfs:label: Chemometrics

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Assigning sequence reads to separate groups / files based on their index tag (sample origin).
Sequence demultiplexing
@graph.rdfs:comment: NGS sequence runs are often performed with multiple samples pooled together.  In such cases, an index tag (or "barcode") - a unique sequence of between 6 and 12bp - is ligated to each sample's genetic material so that the sequence reads from different samples can be identified. The process of demultiplexing (dividing sequence reads into separate files for each index tag/sample) may be performed automatically by the sequencing hardware. Alternatively the reads may be lumped together in one file with barcodes still attached, requiring you to do the splitting using software. In such cases, a "mapping” file is used which indicates which barcodes correspond to which samples.
@graph.rdfs:label: Demultiplexing

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A process used in statistics, machine learning, and information theory that reduces the number of random variables by obtaining a set of principal variables.
Dimension reduction
@graph.rdfs:label: Dimensionality reduction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A dimensionality reduction process that selects a subset of relevant features (variables, predictors) for use in model construction.
@graph.rdfs:label: Feature selection

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A dimensionality reduction process which builds (ideally) informative and non-redundant values (features) from an initial set of measured data, to aid subsequent generalization, learning or interpretation.
Feature projection
@graph.rdfs:label: Feature extraction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Virtual screening is used in drug discovery to search libraries of small molecules in order to identify those molecules which are most likely to bind to a drug target (typically a protein receptor or enzyme).
@graph.rdfs:comment: Virtual screening is widely used for lead identification, lead optimization, and scaffold hopping during drug design and discovery. There are two broad categories of virtual screening techniques: ligand-based drug design (e.g. ligand similarity) and structure-based drug design (ligand docking) methods. Ligand similarity methods exploit structural similarities to known active ligands, whereas ligand docking methods use the 3D structure of a target protein to predict the binding modes and affinities of ligands to it.
@graph.rdfs:label: Virtual screening

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Biotechnology approach that seeks to optimize cellular genetic and regulatory processes in order to increase the cells' production of a certain substance.
@graph.rdfs:label: Metabolic engineering

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The application of phylogenetic and other methods to estimate paleogeographical events such as speciation.
@graph.rdfs:label: Tree dating

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The development and use of mathematical models and systems analysis for the description of ecological processes, and applications such as the sustainable management of resources.
@graph.rdfs:label: Ecological modelling

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Mapping between gene tree nodes and species tree nodes or branches, to analyse and account for possible differences between gene histories and species histories, explaining this in terms of gene-scale events such as duplication, loss, transfer etc.
Gene tree / species tree reconciliation
@graph.rdfs:comment: Methods typically test for topological similarity between trees using for example a congruence index.
@graph.rdfs:label: Phylogenetic tree reconciliation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The detection of genetic selection, or (the end result of) the process by which certain traits become more prevalent in a species than other traits.
@graph.rdfs:label: Selection detection

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: 'Organisation' trailing modifier (qualifier, 'organisation') of 'xref' links of 'Format' concepts. When 'true', the link is pointing to an organisation that developed, standardised, and maintains the given data format.
Organization
concept_properties
@graph.rdfs:label: Organisation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A comment explaining the proposed refactoring, including name of person commenting (jison, mkalas etc.)
concept_properties
@graph.rdfs:label: refactor_comment

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: 'Regular expression' concept property ('regex' metadata tag) specifies the allowed values of types of identifiers (accessions). Applicable to some other types of data, too.
concept_properties
@graph.rdfs:label: Regular expression

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: 'Repository' trailing modifier (qualifier, 'repository') of 'xref' links of 'Format' concepts. When 'true', the link is pointing to the public source-code repository where the given data format is developed or maintained.
concept_properties
@graph.rdfs:label: Repository

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Name of thematic editor (http://biotools.readthedocs.io/en/latest/governance.html#registry-editors) responsible for this concept and its children.
concept_properties
@graph.rdfs:label: thematic_editor

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: A category denoting a rather broad domain or field of interest, of study, application, work, data, or technology. Topics have no clearly defined borders between each other.
sumo:FieldOfStudy
@graph.rdfs:label: Topic

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The processing and analysis of nucleic acid sequence, structural and other data.
Nucleic_acids
@graph.rdfs:label: Nucleic acids

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Archival, processing and analysis of protein data, typically molecular sequence and structural data.
Proteins
Protein databases
@graph.rdfs:label: Proteins

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The structures of reactants or products of metabolism, for example small molecules such as including vitamins, polyols, nucleotides and amino acids.
@graph.rdfs:label: Metabolites

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The archival, processing and analysis of molecular sequences (monomer composition of polymers) including molecular sequence data resources, sequence sites, alignments, motifs and profiles.
Sequences
Sequence_analysis
@graph.rdfs:label: Sequence analysis

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The curation, processing, analysis and prediction of data about the structure of biological molecules, typically proteins and nucleic acids and other macromolecules.
Structure_analysis
@graph.rdfs:comment: This includes related concepts such as structural properties, alignments and structural motifs.
@graph.rdfs:label: Structure analysis

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The prediction of molecular structure, including the prediction, modelling, recognition or design of protein secondary or tertiary structure or other structural features, and the folding of nucleic acid molecules and the prediction or design of nucleic acid (typically RNA) sequences with specific conformations.
Structure_prediction
@graph.rdfs:comment: This includes the recognition (prediction and assignment) of known protein structural domains or folds in protein sequence(s), for example by threading, or the alignment of molecular sequences to structures, structural (3D) profiles or templates (representing a structure or structure alignment).
@graph.rdfs:label: Structure prediction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The alignment (equivalence between sites) of molecular sequences, structures or profiles (representing a sequence or structure alignment).
@graph.rdfs:label: Alignment

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The study of evolutionary relationships amongst organisms.
Phylogeny
@graph.rdfs:comment: This includes diverse phylogenetic methods, including phylogenetic tree construction, typically from molecular sequence or morphological data, methods that simulate DNA sequence evolution, a phylogenetic tree or the underlying data, or which estimate or use molecular clock and stratigraphic (age) data, methods for studying gene evolution etc.
@graph.rdfs:label: Phylogeny

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The study of gene or protein functions and their interactions in totality in a given organism, tissue, cell etc.
Functional_genomics
@graph.rdfs:label: Functional genomics

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The conceptualisation, categorisation and nomenclature (naming) of entities or phenomena within biology or bioinformatics. This includes formal ontologies, controlled vocabularies, structured glossary, symbols and terminology or other related resource.
Ontology_and_terminology
@graph.rdfs:label: Ontology and terminology

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The search and query of data sources (typically databases or ontologies) in order to retrieve entries or other information.
@graph.rdfs:label: Information retrieval

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: VT 1.5.6 Bioinformatics
The archival, curation, processing and analysis of complex biological data.
Bioinformatics
@graph.rdfs:comment: This includes data  processing in general, including basic handling of files and databases, datatypes, workflows and annotation.
@graph.rdfs:label: Bioinformatics

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Computer graphics
VT 1.2.5 Computer graphics
Rendering (drawing on a computer screen) or visualisation of molecular sequences, structures or other biomolecular data.
Data rendering
Data_visualisation
@graph.rdfs:label: Data visualisation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The study of the thermodynamic properties of a nucleic acid.
@graph.rdfs:label: Nucleic acid thermodynamics

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The archival, curation, processing and analysis of nucleic acid structural information, such as whole structures, structural features and alignments, and associated annotation.
Nucleic acid structure
Nucleic_acid_structure_analysis
@graph.rdfs:comment: Includes secondary and tertiary nucleic acid structural data, nucleic acid thermodynamic, thermal and conformational properties including DNA or DNA/RNA denaturation (melting) etc.
@graph.rdfs:label: Nucleic acid structure analysis

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: RNA sequences and structures.
RNA
Small RNA
@graph.rdfs:label: RNA

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Topic for the study of restriction enzymes, their cleavage sites and the restriction of nucleic acids.
@graph.rdfs:label: Nucleic acid restriction

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The mapping of complete (typically nucleotide) sequences. Mapping (in the sense of short read alignment, or more generally, just alignment) has application in RNA-Seq analysis (mapping of transcriptomics reads), variant discovery (e.g. mapping of exome capture), and re-sequencing (mapping of WGS reads).
Mapping
@graph.rdfs:comment: This includes resources that aim to identify, map or analyse genetic markers in DNA sequences, for example to produce a genetic (linkage) map of a chromosome or genome or to analyse genetic linkage and synteny. It also includes resources for physical (sequence) maps of a DNA sequence showing the physical distance (base pairs) between features or landmarks such as restriction sites, cloned DNA fragments, genes and other genetic markers.  It also covers for example the alignment of sequences of (typically millions) of short reads to a reference genome.
@graph.rdfs:label: Mapping

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The study of codon usage in nucleotide sequence(s), genetic codes and so on.
@graph.rdfs:label: Genetic codes and codon usage

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The translation of mRNA into protein and subsequent protein processing in the cell.
Protein_expression
Translation
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein expression

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Methods that aims to identify, predict, model or analyse genes or gene structure in DNA sequences.
@graph.rdfs:comment: This includes the study of promoters, coding regions, splice sites, etc. Methods for gene prediction might be ab initio, based on phylogenetic comparisons, use motifs, sequence features, support vector machine, alignment etc.
@graph.rdfs:label: Gene finding

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The transcription of DNA into mRNA.
@graph.rdfs:label: Transcription

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Promoters in DNA sequences (region of DNA that facilitates the transcription of a particular gene by binding RNA polymerase and transcription factor proteins).
@graph.rdfs:label: Promoters

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The folding (in 3D space) of nucleic acid molecules.
@graph.rdfs:label: Nucleic acid folding

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Gene structure, regions which make an RNA product and features such as promoters, coding regions, gene fusion, splice sites etc.
Gene features
Gene_structure
Fusion genes
rdfs:comment: This includes the study of promoters, coding regions etc.
This incudes operons (operators, promoters and genes) from a bacterial genome.  For example the operon leader and trailer gene, gene composition of the operon and associated information.
@graph.rdfs:label: Gene structure

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Protein and peptide identification, especially in the study of whole proteomes of organisms.
Proteomics
rdfs:comment: Includes metaproteomics: proteomics analysis of an environmental sample.

Proteomics includes any methods (especially high-throughput) that separate, characterize and identify expressed proteins such as mass spectrometry, two-dimensional gel electrophoresis and protein microarrays, as well as in-silico methods that perform proteolytic or mass calculations on a protein sequence and other analyses of protein production data, for example in different cells or tissues.
@graph.rdfs:label: Proteomics

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The elucidation of the three dimensional structure for all (available) proteins in a given organism.
Structural_genomics
@graph.rdfs:label: Structural genomics

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The study of the physical and biochemical properties of peptides and proteins, for example the hydrophobic, hydrophilic and charge properties of a protein.
Protein physicochemistry
Protein_properties
Protein hydropathy
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein properties

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Protein-protein, protein-DNA/RNA and protein-ligand interactions, including analysis of known interactions and prediction of putative interactions.
Protein_interactions
@graph.rdfs:comment: This includes experimental (e.g. yeast two-hybrid) and computational analysis techniques.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein interactions

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Protein stability, folding (in 3D space) and protein sequence-structure-function relationships.  This includes for example study of inter-atomic or inter-residue interactions in protein (3D) structures, the effect of mutation, and the design of proteins with specific properties, typically by designing changes (via site-directed mutagenesis) to an existing protein.
Protein_folding_stability_and_design
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein folding, stability and design

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Two-dimensional gel electrophoresis image and related data.
@graph.rdfs:label: Two-dimensional gel electrophoresis

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: An analytical chemistry technique that measures the mass-to-charge ratio and abundance of ions in the gas phase.
@graph.rdfs:label: Mass spectrometry

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Protein microarray data.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein microarrays

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The study of the hydrophobic, hydrophilic and charge properties of a protein.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein hydropathy

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The study of how proteins are transported within and without the cell, including signal peptides, protein subcellular localisation and export.
Protein_targeting_and_localisation
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein targeting and localisation

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Enzyme or chemical cleavage sites and proteolytic or mass calculations on a protein sequence.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein cleavage sites and proteolysis

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The comparison of two or more protein structures.
@graph.rdfs:comment: Use this concept for methods that are exclusively for protein structure.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein structure comparison

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: The processing and analysis of inter-atomic or inter-residue interactions in protein (3D) structures.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein residue interactions

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Protein-protein interactions, individual interactions and networks, protein complexes, protein functional coupling etc.
@graph.rdfs:label: Protein-protein interactions

@graph.http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Protein-ligand (small molecule) interactions.

http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI: Variable number of tandem repeat polymorphism
rdfs:comment: Includes microsatellite polymorphism in a DNA sequence.  A microsatellite polymorphism is a very short subsequence that is repeated a variable number of times between individuals. These repeats consist of the nucleotides cytosine and adenosine.
Includes restriction fragment length polymorphisms (RFLP) in a DNA sequence.  An RFLP is defined by the presence or absence of a specific restriction site of a bacterial restriction enzyme.

Includes single nucleotide polymorphisms (SNP) and associated data, for example, the discovery and annotation of SNPs.  A SNP is a DNA sequence variation where a single nucleotide differs between members of a species or paired chromosomes in an individual.

Includes variable number of tandem repeat (VNTR) polymorphism in a DNA sequence.  VNTRs occur in non-coding regions of DNA and consists sub-sequence that is repeated a multiple (and varied) number of times.
@graph.rdfs:label: DNA polymorphism

Gene_transcripts
rdfs:comment: This includes 5'untranslated region (5'UTR), coding sequences (CDS), exons, intervening sequences (intron) and 3'untranslated regions (3'UTR).

This includes Introns, and protein-coding regions including coding sequences (CDS), exons, translation initiation sites and open reading frames.  Also expressed sequence tag (EST) or complementary DNA (cDNA) sequences.

This includes coding sequences for a signal or transit peptide.  A signal peptide coding sequence encodes an N-terminal domain of a secreted protein, which is involved in attaching the polypeptide to a membrane leader sequence. A transit peptide coding sequence encodes an N-terminal domain of a nuclear-encoded organellar protein; which is involved in import of the protein into the organelle.

This includes regions or sites in a eukaryotic and eukaryotic viral RNA sequence which directs endonuclease cleavage or polyadenylation of an RNA transcript.  A polyA signal is required for endonuclease cleavage of an RNA transcript that is followed by polyadenylation. A polyA site is a site on an RNA transcript to which adenine residues will be added during post-transcriptional polyadenylation.
@graph.rdfs:label: Gene transcripts
